At the end of the course, students will be able to: 
a) Recognize the appropriate approach for the estimation of different econometric approaches including linear, non-linear, discrete choice and censored models, using cross-sectional, panel and time series data;
b) Understand the main assumption underpinning such different types of econometric models and estimators; 
c) Understand how to test such assumptions via appropriate prior- and post-estimation procedures; 
d) Develop simple econometric analyses using empirical data in order to answer specific economic questions; 
e) Critically evaluate the econometric analyses carried out by others.

	The course aims to provide students with a general understanding of the main categories of the Italian public law in the light of the principles set by the Republican Constitution, identifying in particular the individual institutes that characterize the existing forms of State and government.
At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
- master the various normative sources (internal and European), identifying how to overcome any antinomies among them;
- reconstruct the ways in which public decisions are taken and their transposition into legal acts;
- identify citizens’ rights and the appropriate tools to protect them;
- understand and use the legal language.

The course aims to introduce the notion of "community" as developed by sociology since its foundation, then critically grasp its evolution and transformation according to the epistemological, theoretical, methodological, operational and professional perspectives, showing its relevance for the design of services and interventions with territorial impact aimed at sustainability.
The community paradigm as a meso-level approach will be related to sustainability — with its political, economic, social, environmental and territorial components considered all interrelated — and, through the definition of "self-sustainable territorial development", we will consider designing as "a process of shared production of local added value”, rather than the design as an objective artefact.
In order to deepen the logic and practice of community design, a few cases will be analysed as simulative learning contexts by the support of professionals involved. They are examples of some areas of intervention for sociologists, made operational also thanks to the recent National Recovery and Resilience Plan (PNRR): energy communities, corporate-territorial welfare and urban-rural regeneration.
At the end of the course, students will have acquired critical familiarity with the sociological field of community, seen as part of the professionalization process for the "territorial project consultant" — also known as "community developer" and "community manager" — who is commissioned to make analysis, develop projects, manage interventions and carry out impact assessments about a community, often as a member of a multi-professional team. Therefore, the right toolbox will be taken care of, in order to ensure the achievement of metacognitive, theoretical, procedural and pragmatic skills:
- understanding key concepts and analysing issues highlighted by the community paradigm;
- applying design methods and techniques for / with the community according to the logic of sustainability in some empirical contexts and with operational purposes agreed with clients;
- evaluating the performance of "community work" according to the emerging practice in our country and also referring to the "community development & organizing process” dealt with in international literature;
- managing inter-disciplinary relationships with other professional practitioners, who also carry out analysis and interventions at the community level.

The purpose of the course is to offer a deeper understanding of the history of Italian literature between the age of the Counter-Reformation and the age of Restoration and Romanticism.
To this end, every year the course focuses on an individual author, a particularly significant work, or a characteristic literary genre.
The successful student will be able to:
a. provide historical and cultural context for the most representative authors of the period at hand;
b. interpret their most notable texts and contextualize them in the history of the genres they belong to;
c. have a deep understanding of the texts that will be subjected to critical reading in class.

The course has three educational goals:
1)	have a good knowledge of the main characteristics and problems of the Italian and European labour market;
2)	understand the mechanisms underpinning the labour supply decisions of individuals and families, as well as some related choices (education and fertility);
3)	learn to analyse the functioning of the labour market and to evaluate the possible consequences of labour market institutions and policies, as well as of information asymmetries, on employment, wages, payment schemes and gender differences. 
The course for Economics and Management has also the additional aim to deepen the knowledge of the Italian and European labour market (mainly through empirical evidence).

At the end of the course students are expected to be able to:
·       understand the basic principles of the classification of the main urban hydraulic infrastructures;
·       apply classical methods for the assessment of the design rainfall depth and intensity;
·       calculate the flow in pipes (under pressure or partially filled) and in open channels;  
·       characterize the intake, transport and distribution infrastructures that compose a water supply system;
·      characterize the urban drainage networks by accounting of the effects of land use and climate change on the extreme storm events (in an urban context);
·       intervene on existing networks in order to adapt them to the ongoing changes;
·     develop management and maintenance strategies

The course promotes linguistico-grammatical and historico-linguistic knowledge of Italian language, encouraging critical detachment from the language through the analysis of written and oral texts and system reasonings.
At the end of the course, the students will be able to:
a)	recognise the graphic, phonetic, morphologic, syntactic traits that characterise standard Italian;
b)	distinguish the varieties which diverge from the standard, in diatopia, diastratia and diaphasia in texts that feature these phenomena;
c)	notice the connection between Italian and its dialects in the form of diglossia or bilingualism, even through the form of linguistic autobiography;
d)	know the formation and standardisation process of the national language through its critical moments (questioni della lingua);
e)	know and recognise the evolution from Latin to Italo-Romance vernaculars (historical grammar basics, with practical exercises);
f)	recognise the fundamental features of the Italian language in Dantes linguistic thinking and vernacular.
For teaching training, consistent with the teaching methodologies developed in the research in didactics of the Italian language foreseen by the competition classes, attention is paid to the 4 fundamental, passive and active linguistic abilities, refining the analysis techniques of spoken texts and of written texts, the understanding of listening and reading, the production of paper texts and word processing.

The course has two main goals: 
1) To provide students with basic knowledge of the main categories of private law, with special emphasis on legal subjectivity and its forms, property law, the role of contract law and the other types of obligations, civil liability. Students will also learn how to find sources of law and how to interpret legal rules, with particular regard to EU law and the Italian Civil Code.
By the end of the course students will be able to:
a) Identify the main areas of private law;
b) Apply basic concepts of private law to new legal problems;
c) Use the main interpretation techniques in the field of private law;
d) identify the sources of private law which apply to a  specific problem.

Sanitary Engineering involves the fields of water supply engineering, wastewater treatment, air pollution, soil remediation, solid waste management, public health, all in accordance with regulations, technological trends and monitoring. I this context, the course aims to provide knowledge about:
- pollution phenomena in water, soils, air and waste production;
- strategies and technologies applied for wastewater treatment, drinking water production, soil remediation, treatmnet and disposal of solid wastes; 
- regulations in these fields; 
- a comprehensive view of the interaction between human activities and environment.
The course includes practical abilities, acquired through numerical exercises about self-purification, lake eutrophication, design of the main stages in wastewater treatmnt and water treatment, and exercises about solid wastes.

This course provides the basic conceptual and theoretical tools to understand the methodology, scope and subject matter of global history and transnational history. At the same time, the course familiarizes students with some heuristic instruments to better understand the historic dimensions of a globalizing present and explores relevant topics, focusing in particular on the long twentieth century.
After completion of this course, students will be able to: 
Define and explain global history and transnational history as concepts and as approaches;
Develop non-Eurocentric readings of the global past;
Show in which ways the interconnectedness of today’s world is not a new phenomenon, but one that is rooted in a long history of exchange and interaction;
Identify and explain the entanglements between specific regions and global political, socio-economic and cultural structures;
Present and discuss theoretical and empirical academic literature in the field of global history and transnational history;
Analyse a current global phenomenon from a historical perspective for the purpose of a final written assignment based on academic literature.

Commons and rural communities in the Bishopric of Trento (XV-XVIII centuries).

The aim of the course is:

a) to define the legal, political and social concept of the rural community in the Early modern age;
b) to define the concept of commons in the rural world of the Early modern age;
c) to grab the interactions between the communal identity ant the exploitation of the common goods;
d) to analyze the conflicts caused by the exploitation of the common goods;
e) to analyze the ecological implications of a commons-based economy;
f) read original sources;
g) write short essays based on assigned course readings or on primary sources.

Expected learning outcomes:

a) to place in an appropriate historical context the topic of the course;
b) to recognize the importance of studying the commons in the economic and political context of the rural communities;
c) to distinguish the various typologies of the rural charters;
d) to reconstruct a diachronic sense the transformation of these sources;
e) to identify the political actors involved with the conflicts around the commons;
f) to write a course paper choosing some topics related to the course.

The general goal of the course is providing the knowledge of the main quantum algorithms and their application to the development of machine learning schemes with quantum computers. The students will be involved in the study of the quantum versions of well-known procedures of classical machine learning. At the end of the course the students will have learned:
1) how the notions of quantum states and quantum measurements can be adapted into an information theoretical framework;
2) how to encode classical information into quantum systems and how to process it by means of quantum operations.
3) where quantum resources may be relevant in the context of Machine Learning;
4) the basics of the construction of quantum implementations of machine learning algorithms.

This module will embrace the anatomical, cellular, molecular and functional organization of the Peripheral Nervous System (PNS). 

At the end of this course, students will be able to:
•	Describe the anatomy of the PNS
•	Explain the similarities and differences between different branches of the PNS;
•	Understand the complexity of the physiological function controlled by the PNS;
•	Understand how the functions of the PNS are finely tuned at different levels;
•	Understand how the different components of the PNS operate in a coordinated manner;
•	Critically evaluate the experimental approaches used to study the PNS, and the evolving comprehension of the mechanisms underlining the functions of the PNS.

Recently, the judiciary has been going through a phase of profound transformation that deserves to be analysed and discussed with the typical tools of the law. In particular, judicial function increasingly assumes a supranational dimension: national judge has also become “European judge” and this inevitably has an effect on the concrete exercise of the function and on the very idea and culture of being a judge in contemporary society. At the same time, the judge has long since ceased to be “a mere mouth of the law”, to act as an alternative to the legislator in the production of law and in the identification and recognition of the always new social needs. 

Accordingly, the course aims to provide students with the theoretical and practical knowledge that will enable them to respond to some fundamental questions and to understand and know how to manage the dynamics of contemporary legal systems consciously and effectively. In particular, students will be able to critically address some core-issues not only in terms of the functioning of legal systems but also in terms of their future professionalization:

1. the meaning, guarantees and limits of the independence and autonomy of the judiciary in contemporary societies;
2. The role that the judge plays and should play in contemporary legal systems;
3. The effectiveness of the independence and autonomy of judge and public prosecutor in a multi-level system (Constitution, ECHR, European Union) and the identification of a common core of guarantee principles and instruments;
4. The main models of regulation of judicial systems existing at a comparative level and their compatibility with supranational and constitutional standards, with particular reference to the Italian one;
5. The relationship between the type of organization of the judicial systems and the effectiveness of autonomy and independence of the judiciary, with particular reference to the different solutions that can be adopted regarding selection, internal organization, remuneration, career, responsibility of the judiciary (judges and prosecutors).

At the end of the course, students will have acquired an exhaustive picture of essential principles and dynamics on the discipline of judicial systems, starting from the supranational dimension, passing through the discussion of cases derived from comparative law, to reach the Italian constitutional level. The goal is to provide not only theoretical skills and knowledge but, taking advantage of the potentials of comparative method and the analysis of case-law, to offer a description of the effective implementation dynamics of the different systems analysed.
In particular, students will know:
a) to understand and evaluate critically and consciously the dynamics that arise between powers, in particular between legislative and judicial;
b) to research and critically analyse principles which characterise the European and international framework (ECHR), with particular attention to the standards of guarantee of the rule of law and the autonomy and independence of the judge and public prosecutor;
c) critically evaluate the different national models regarding judicial systems, also through the use of the comparative method;
d) evaluate the Italian judicial system in the light of the comparative analysis carried out and the European parameters;
e) know the reality of the Italian judicial system, in particular in order to allow a more conscious choice of the professional path to be taken after the degree;
f) use a law study based on the "Learning by doing" and "law in action analysis" methods, also through dialogue with sector experts (professors and magistrates) who will participate in the lessons.

The course aims to provide basic, updated and comprehensive knowledge of the legal profiles concerning the organization and activity of public administrations, which will be contextualized with reference to the main problems concerning their evolution and future developments. The course addresses to those who, after graduation, intend to work in a public administration and, more generally, to anyone who plans to have relations with public administrations as a citizen, a professional, an entrepreneur, etc.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
- identify the general structure of public administrations, distinguishing between national and European level;
- distinguish legal sources and know the general principles relevant to the administrative activity;	
- know the basic legal concepts relating to the administrative activity, identifying the various relevant concepts based on the attribution of powers and the distribution of competencies, as well as the dynamics of inter-subjective and inter-body relations;	
- know the basics of administrative activity, in particular the legal differences between the administration and the private sector, and clearly distinguish the notions of act and administrative procedure;	
- know and understand the legal framework and the procedures for conducting the administrative procedure;
- know and understand the profiles relating to the information and communication activities of public administrations, with particular reference to access to administrative documents;	
- know and understand the conditions of validity of the administrative act and identify the general framework of the private protection instruments against invalid administrative acts.

The course gives an overview of the operative taxation system focusing on income tax and value-added tax.
At the end of the course, student will be able:
1) to achieve a good level of knowledge in individual income tax law, in enterprise tax law and in corporation tax law;
2) to analyze and to make critical evaluation of corporate processes and dynamics with respect to taxation law;
3) to acquire the ability to illustrate the main issues of the course using the appropriated legal lexicon;
4) to learn and to apply the links between the different legal matters;
5) to analyze case studies emerging in practice and to apply the appropriate fiscal rules of the national legal system.

The course offers an introduction to the fundamental concepts of the atmospheric boundary layer, including the description of turbulence and its effects on momentum, heat and mass transport processe. The course aims at providing students with a sufficient background for assessing the relevance of atmospheric boundary layer conditions and turbulence for the evaluation of transport processes in the lower atmosphere.
At the end of the course the student should:
•	be familiar with basics concepts on the atmospheric boundary layer introduced during frontal lectures;
•	know the basics on atmospheric turbulence, including modelling approaches in meteorological and dispersion models;
•	be aware of intruments and techniques for measurements in the atmospheric boundary layer.

OBJECTIVES
An engineering approach to the software development results fundamental for coping with the increasing complexity of systems and to guarantee their economical sustainability. As for any other engineering discipline, the software production requires a systematic organization of the activities, the adoption of a well-defined process and methods and tools to support the quality and the respect of the project constraints. The objective of the course is providing to the students concepts, approaches and techniques for the analysis, the design, and the development of the software. In particular, the course will focus on process models, modelling languages and verification and validation techniques. Moreover, diagrammatic languages, requirements analysis methods, design principles and testing techniques will allow the students to design high quality software. The students will be practicing by developing and implementing a web service applying the most modern development techniques, including the adoption of RESTful directives and the use of standard languages for the documentation of web APIs, the collaboration in the development of the source code in a central repository, the automation of code testing, and the configuration of services and tools to set-up a continuous integration process for the software. Finally, project management concepts and metrics for software products will be introduced.

EXPECTED RESULTS
At the end of the course, the student will be able to: 
1. define the most suitable development process and model for the analysis and the design of the software under consideration; 
2. represent with the different types of diagrams the requirements, the architecture, the intarction among the components, and the deployment of the system; 
3. define and mange in a consistent and complete way the functional and non functional requirements of a software system highlighting priorities and criticises. 
4. Define the architecture of a software system adopting architectural styles and principles of refinement, abstraction, modularity, functional independency and refactoring; 
5. Design a component of a software system identifying the control type and following the step-by-step process for the respect of the general design principles; 
6. Define and document a web service compliant with RESTful directives, collaborate into the development of the source code, testing the code, and automating the deployment of the software with a continuous integration process.

The course, focusing on the comprehension of the basic aspects of the mechanics of structures, takes on fundamental importance in the education of engineer-architects and represents the introduction to the forthcoming class of Structural Mechanics, 
AIM: the course aims at providing the participants with the fundamentals of the mechanics of rigid bodies, with particular emphasis on plane systems of beams as preferential application.
LEARNING OUTCOMES: the course will allow students to:
- know and apply the basic operations of the statics of rigid bodies, both from an analytical and a graphical perspective;
- provide static-kinematic classification of a system of rigid bodies, illustrating the operative procedure; 
- analyse the equilibrium conditions and understand the behaviour under assigned external loads of variously constrained statically determinate plane structures, evaluating the reaction forces; 
- assimilate the mechanical concept of beam and its internal forces, with special reference to plane beams;
- recognize the equilibrium configurations of statically determinate plane structures, evaluating and representing the internal forces functions;   
- compute the geometrical properties of areas;
- become aware of the simplificative hypotheses adopted in structural computation.

The course is aimed at familiarizing students with the way in which international law regulates the possibility to resort to armed force in international relations (the s.c. jus ad bellum) We will explore the mechanisms aimed at preventing and regulating conflicts and the role played in this endeavor by relevant International Organizations (both at universal and at regional level). 
At the end of the course the participants will 
•	Have a clear picture of the role of International Organisations involved in peace promotion and conflict management;
•	Understand the main rules regarding the jus ad bellum and the exceptions to the otherwise absolute prohibition to use armed force;
•	Understand the interplay between the UN and regional organisations in protecting and promoting international peace and security.

The course aims to:

- Identify the phenomena that describe digital era

- Analyze the problems posed by the digital revolution

- Check if and how information technologies are changing the legal (operational) rules

- Try to understand if the emergence of new rules coincides with the emergence of common characteristic features.


At the end of the course, students will know the most important elements charactering the law of digital age and be able:
- to critically analyze such elements;
- to apply rules to specific legal issues;
- to think logically and clearly;
- to communicate effectively orally and in writing;
- to apply a sound methodology for acquiring and using information from many sources;
- to work collaboratively.

The primary goal of the course is to enable students to become critical lawyers and capable problem solvers while dealing with intellectual property. This is based on the idea that learning happens when theoretical notions are accompanied by skills development and the ability to apply knowledge.
Core principles of intellectual property will be plainly explained. Furthermore, by means of an interdisciplinary and practical approach students will learn that copyright law is changing, as it is instrumental to the pursuit of certain social, economic or ethical aims. They also will experience that the evolution of copyright law is closely linked to technological changes as well as to developing business models.
At the end of the course, students will know the most important elements charactering the regulation of copyright law and be able:
• to critically analyze such elements;• to apply rules to specific legal issues;
• to read and understand decisions of national courts as well as those of the Court of Justice of the European Union;
• to read and understand contracts in the field of copyright law;
• to think logically and clearly;
• to communicate effectively orally and in writing;
• to apply a sound methodology for acquiring and using information from many sources;
• to work collaboratively.

This course is borrowed by the teaching of Archaeology of the Roman Provinces for the graduate programme 'Quaternario, Preistoria e Archeologia'.
The course aims at providing the students with a knowledge of:
•	what a Roman Province was and the varied and complex releationships between Rome and its Provinces;
•	Roman army, conquest and frontiers;
•	Sicily, the earliest province: changes between the late Republic and the imperial period. 
•	Britannia: urban and rural landscapes in the periphery;
•	production and trade in the Roman provinces. 
Some lectures will be offered by scholars with an experties on Roman Provinces in compresence with the Professor (max 8 hours out of 30). 
Thus, the course will provide the students with the following skills:
•	the integration of different research methods to the understanding of Roman Provinces;
•	the contextualisation of political events, settlement and economic patterns, and production in the Roman Provinces
•	the use of archaeological bibliography (also in English).

The course introduces imperative programming, focusing on both the theoretical foundations and the practical aspects. 

At the end the student will be able to:
(theory)
- understand the basic logic and set-theoretic notation;
- interpret recursive definitions for sets and relations;
- derive the induction principle associated to a recursive definition;
- apply the induction principles to prove properties on recursively defined objects;
- recursively define the syntax of a basic programming language;
- formalize the semantics of simple imperative programs;
- formally verify the correctness of simple programs;
(practice)
- experiment with the basic constructs of a feature-rich imperative programming language;
- access the documentation for the language and its libraries;
- use an integrated development environment;
- understand and fix the most common programming errors;
- develop programs in the laboratory to solve simple tasks;
- organize and document one's own code;
- solve a medium-sized given problem, by developing a suitable program in an independent way.

The course would like to provide the students with the historical and conceptual instruments to better understand the classics of the Jewish thought, especially those from the modern and contemporary age. It aims to offer:
a) a basic knowledge of the historical context of these classics;
b) the philosophical, theological, and ethical concepts present in these classics;
c) the ability to recognize their sources;
d) the ability to understand the methods and the major themes of a rabbinical discussions;
e) the appreciation for the philosophical value of those methods and discussions.

Course objectives: 
1) To introduce the reader expectation approach to writing through five interactive online modules. More specifically, students will be introduced to the concepts of action, agency, separations, theme and stress position; 
2) To develop an awareness of how these concepts contribute to effective writing and to develop an ability to recognise effective use (or not) of this approach in written texts, academic and non-academic;
3) To develop students' ability to use the reader expectation approach to writing to produce clear, effective prose in English.

Learning outcomes:
On completion of all components of the course, students will be able to apply to their own written production the notions, concepts and skills acquired, with a particular focus on clarity, coherence and thematic/logical progression. More specifically students will :
1) have achieved an understanding of textual cohesion through collaborative writing tasks;
2) have achieved an understanding of how arguments are constructed, developed and supported through evidence;
3) have achieved an understanding of how information can be organised to best effect in a text;
4) have developed an ability to write concise prose;
5) be able to present, develop/argue a position, and draw meaningful conclusions, in written English, through persuasive lines of reasoning;
6) be able to edit their own written production by employing techniques to ensure the intended message is effectively communicated to the reader, limiting instances of potential misunderstanding.

The goal of this course is to enable students to analyze various types of high-dimensional data types commonly encountered in the practice of Molecular Biology using a range of methodologies, including established statistical approaches, machine learning, and recently introduced methods.
At the end of the course, students are expected to possess the following skills:
-	familiarity with different types of Molecular Biology data and their specificity;
-	good understanding of different conceptual methods for analyzing the data;  
-	familiarity with practical computational tools for  carrying out the analysis;
-	ability to frame the results of their analysis in a biological context using networks;
-	ability to provide a functional interpretation of the results of their analysis;
-	ability to complete a project, write a structured report, and orally present the results of their work.

The course aims to: 
- Develop knowledge on the most relevant historical phases of the Middle Ages.
- Develop confidence in engaging with current scholarly debates.
- Develop skills in analysing a variety of types of primary sources.

After attending the course and after reading the reference bibliography, the students will be able to:
- define and describe the most important turning points of the Medieval history;
- recognize and analyze a variety of types of primary sources;
- analyze and comment a historiographic text;
- analyze a historic map;
- define and use the specific terms of the medieval studies.

The ultimate aim of the course is to provide the tools for understanding the main characteristics of model organisms related to their use in research and innovation laboratories.

Participation in the course and individual study will allow female students to:

a) Understand the basic principles of evolutionary biology that unites all living beings and the increasingly important role of its application to medicine and public health;
b) Understand the importance of studying small model organisms for basic biomedical research and drug development;
c) Develop critical thinking in describing and discussing examples of important past and contemporary experiments.

Course objectives: 
1) To introduce the reader expectation approach to writing through five interactive online modules. More specifically, students will be introduced to the concepts of action, agency, separations, theme and stress position; 
2) To develop an awareness of how these concepts contribute to effective writing and to develop an ability to recognise effective use (or not) of this approach in written texts, academic and non-academic;
3) To develop students' ability to use the reader expectation approach to writing to produce clear, effective prose in English.

Learning outcomes:
On completion of all components of the course, students will be able to apply to their own written production the notions, concepts and skills acquired, with a particular focus on clarity, coherence and thematic/logical progression. More specifically students will :
1) have achieved an understanding of textual cohesion through collaborative writing tasks;
2) have achieved an understanding of how arguments are constructed, developed and supported through evidence;
3) have achieved an understanding of how information can be organised to best effect in a text;
4) have developed an ability to write concise prose;
5) be able to present, develop/argue a position, and draw meaningful conclusions, in written English, through persuasive lines of reasoning;
6) be able to edit their own written production by employing techniques to ensure the intended message is effectively communicated to the reader, limiting instances of potential misunderstanding.

The course will give an overview of entangled geographies of security and insecurity at different spatial scales. It will highlight the importance of political geographies to understand security issues in the contemporary world and introduce major political dilemmas. 
The module will focus on the territorial elements that can originate or be at the center of political and/or social conflicts. The main goal of the course is to provide theoretical and analytical tools to understand the changes that occurred to the geographies of in/security after the end of the cold war and after 9/11. Attention will also be paid to the environment as a major area of concern and to the diverse framework of the climate crisis as a security issue. Moreover, students will be introduced to literature analysing how different ideas of security translate into different kinds of politics.
The expected learning outcomes include:
-	Knowledge and understanding of the geographical aspects of international security and of the different scales of in/security;
-	Ability to link diverse security issues with territorial factors and to critically analyse connections and relations of cause/effect;
-	Capacity to critically understand the concept of in/security and discuss its multifaceted nature (from global geopolitics to embodied experiences), especially with regard to present phenomena;
-	Understanding of the different factors (e.g. resources, identity issues, environmental politics, territorialities) and scales (e.g. local identities, geopolitical interests, globalization processes) impacting on or influencing social and political security issues;
-	Capacity to develop critical analysis and autonomous judgment, and to conduct independent research (at least via secondary sources) linking case studies to explanatory theories.

The aim of the course is to introduce the fundamental concepts as well as the basic tools of modern Geometric Analysis and Riemannian Geometry. At the end of the course, the students are expected:

- to have a good intuition of the notions of the intrinsic and the extrinsic notions of curvature;

- to be able to translate the geometric problems in a suitable analytical form;

- to master a reasonable set of analytic technique in order to study the  PDE's arising from the geometry;

- to have both the cultural and the technical preparation that are necessary to understand an advanced General Relativity text book.

The conduct of civil litigation presents fundamental similarities in any developed legal system. Every civil case involves a complaining party who seeks a remedy from a court for an asserted legal wrong against a defending party, who generally contests what the former asserts. The jurisdictional court must be and remain neutral and impartial between the conflicting parties, and is entrusted with the function of deciding the case, according to established legal rules. In light of recognised principles of fairness, the court has to hear both sides of the dispute. After the presentation of the case by the parties, the court must decide it, and render an ultimate decision (adjudication). This decision is subject to appellate review by a higher court. Due to the need for legal certainty, appellate review is generally limited and will result in a definitive conclusion which is thereafter binding on the parties (res judicata). If the losing party does not voluntary comply with the decision, it may be enforced by the prevailing party (judgment enforcement).
While these characteristics of a civil dispute are essentially the same in any developed legal system, various systems present significantly different approaches to civil litigation, especially comparing Civil Law and Common Law traditions or, better said, virtually all legal systems, on the one hand, and the US system, on the other hand.
Exploring these differences in a comparative perspective has increasingly become indispensable for anyone who is required to participate in civil litigation, and especially when civil litigation results in transnational litigation, that is, civil litigation presenting connections with various legal systems.
This course offers essential expertise on how to approach and resolve cross-border civil litigation in the world-wide judicial arena. In particular, at the end of the course students will be able to recognize:
-what the various in-court proceedings are designed to accomplish, and the issues that will have to be resolved in them;
-the main stages of in-court proceedings in the various systems;
-the reasons why legal systems respond differently to similar procedural issues and, in particular, the impact of the historical, social and economic context of a legal system on the rules and structure of its in-court proceedings;
-the most significant similarities and differences between in-court proceedings of Civil and Common Law traditions; and
-whether and how harmonization or unification of different procedures in the various legal systems is possible and/or desirable in a global context.

The primary goal of the course is to enable students to become critical lawyers and capable problem solvers while dealing with copyright law. This is based on the idea that learning happens when theoretical notions are accompanied by skills development and the ability to apply knowledge. 
Core principles of copyright law will be plainly explained (e.g. the notion of originality, the idea/expression dichotomy, etc.). Furthermore, by means of an interdisciplinary and practical approach students will learn that copyright law is changing, as it is instrumental to the pursuit of certain social, economic or ethical aims. They also will experience that the evolution of copyright law is closely linked to technological changes as well as to developing business models. 
At the end of the course, students will know the most important elements charactering the regulation of copyright law and be able:
•	to critically analyze such elements;
•	to apply rules to specific legal issues;
•	to read and understand decisions of national, European and North American courts;
•	to read and understand contracts in the field of copyright law; 
•	to think logically and clearly;
•	to communicate effectively orally and in writing;
•	to apply a sound methodology for acquiring and using information from many sources;
•	to work collaboratively.

The course intends to make students aware of pervasiveness of organisations in contemporary society, to outline main contributions and emergent perspectives in organisational studies, to offer them keys in order to analyse and critically interpret their features and processes. 

At the end of the course students are expected to acquire:
-	a thorough knowledge of the key concepts and of the main theoretical perspectives in organisational studies; 
-	a general knowledge of the main issues, classical and emergent, in organisational studies;
-	a basic interpretive lens to read and critically analyse the main organisational phenomena;
- a deeper understanding of the concept and processes of organisational innovation.

The course aims to introduce students to a set of digital methods that are particularly widespread within contemporary sociological studies by transmitting a series of basic but systematic skills for the collection and analysis of digital data (in particular from Facebook and Twitter). At the end of the course the students will be able to:
1) Read and understand empirical research in the field of sociology that makes use of digital methods;
2) Formulate research questions that involve the adoption of a digital sociological approach and digital research methods;
3) Carry out basic but systematic and theoretically informed analyses of digital data;
4) Translate their research and analysis path into a scientific paper;
5) Present their scientific production in public.

1. Learn concepts, techniques, and tool (including AI-based tools) for eliciting, analyzing,  and managing requirements for a software system.;
2.Develop an understanding of the role of the requirements engineering activities within the whole software development process, and an awareness of some pitfalls in requirements management;
3. Learn how to evaluate and select requirements engineering tools and techniques that are appropriate for a given software system project;
4. Develop an awareness of issues about requirements for AI-based software, including ethical requirements, and learn about guidelines and methods to address them.

The course aims at providing students with the concepts and skills needed to appreciate the role of innovation as a driver of economic dynamics at different levels of aggregation, i.e. firms, industries, and the overall economic system.

By the end of the course you will be able to:

a) understand the role of innovation as a driver of economic growth;
b) appreciate the significance of innovation activity both for firm and market dynamics;
c) recognize the main forces underlying industry dynamics of technological innovation;
d) appraise the relevance of networks in the dynamics of the innovative industry;
e) understand the interplay between firm heterogeneity, firm performance, and market selection.

The aim of the course is to provide students with a deeper understanding of the functioning of markets and of the determinants and effectiveness of firms' strategies, through the analysis of a specific industrial sector using appropriate data.
By the end of the course, students will be able to:
- identify the most appropriate data to describe the evolution of a specific market and of the phenomena that might have influenced it;
- represent data using graphical and statistical tools in order to extract relevant information;
- understand and interpret the market trends and the firm’s strategies, using the theoretical concepts learnt in other courses;
- co-ordinate with other members of a research group;
- develop a research report;
- present and discuss the results to an audience

The course aims to offer the necessary tools to learn public energy law through sharing the knowledge of the energy law regimes currently in force (european, state and local law) in the main energetic fields.

By the end of the course students should be able to demonstrate: 
- To know the fundamental contents of the matter relating to the management of markets and the administrative powers relating to energy sources; 
- To know the administrative acts which regulate the energy fields; 
- To be able to orient among the European, national and local legislative and regulatory framework, which regulate the electricity and natural gas fields; 
- To know the constitutional principles in the energy fields and the distribution of competences between State, regions and local authorities; 
- To know the organization and the functions of the independent competent authorities which operate in the fields;  
- To know the contents of the electrical regimes in the regions which have a special statute; 
- To know the contents of the renewable energy sources discipline, particularly the public water derivations for hydroelectric purposes; 
- To know the Jurisdiction of the Public Water Courts.

The course aims to provide analytical bases for understanding firms' strategies and competitive market dynamics. The topics will be analyzed following the modern industrial organization theory, providing students with the schemes, the concepts and the tools to frame problems related to market functioning and firms' decisions. Theoretical and analytical tools, useful for analyzing the functioning of strategic interactions between firms and their relationship with industrial policy and regulatory competition rules, will be discussed.
At the end of the course the student will be able:
-to identify and explain factors affecting markets' structure;
-to analyze firms' behavior and strategic choices in competitive contexts;
-to understand the implications in terms of industrial policy, promotion and protection of competition and regulation.

1. Learning objectives and course contents.
The purpose of the course is to provide students with an advanced understanding of the corporate investment and financing decisions. 
The first part focuses on the assessment of investments with leverage and enterprise value, with various approaches (the weighted average cost of capital method, the adjusted present value method and the flow-to-equity discounted cash flow method, multiples approach).
The second part analyses the typical sources of capital for corporation, in term of both equity and debt (bonds, leasing), with a medium/ long-term perspective.
The third part introduces mergers and acquisition

2. Expected learning outcomes.

1.	to describe the methods of evaluation of investment with leverage and to list the steps in computing each (define the input variables and describe how to compute their value; illustrate how the variables are used in the model; define and understand the output of the model);
2.	to understand and discuss the critical issues of each methods of evaluation (given the specific investment’s risk and leverage assumptions) and to identify the most suitable method of evaluation; to apply the methods of evaluation to examples / real cases;
3.	to describe the ways in which a private company can raise outside capital; to describe the bond indenture; to compare and discuss callable and convertible bonds with straight debt;
4.	to identify the sources of synergies that are commonly cited as justification given for an acquisition;  to discuss the premium; to calculate and discuss the maximum exchange ratio;

This module provides students with (1) an adequate knowledge of the main factors and processes that transformed the European and world economy from the early modern through the contemporary age, and (2) the tools for understanding, analyzing, and critically interpreting such transformations. 
At the end of the course students will be able to:
- remember the main concepts useful to analyse an economic system;
- outline the major historical manifestations of growth/development and crisis; 
- explain their causes and consequences, especially detecting the relationships between economic, technological and institutional aspects;
- apply the acquired knowledge and skills to a case study;
- communicate effectively in oral and written form, and discuss an economic-history topic.

The course International Business Management is divided into two modules each of 8 ECTS: International Marketing e International Corporate Strategy.
International Marketing:
The main objective of this module is to develop the ability to understand marketing issues linked to the presence of the company in foreign markets.
ILO, therefore, are:
knowledge and understanding of globalisation dynamics; knowledge and understanding of the internationalisation process of the firm and of the entry modes in foreign markets;
develoment of the capacity to implement the acquired knowledge in operational conditions through carrying out analysis of foreign markets and the drafting of international marketing plans;
acquisition of the soft skills needed to work in multinational groups (also in multiple locations).
At the end of the course the students shall be able to:
understand the dynamics of globalisation and internatonalisation within a company as well as those of the enty in foreign markets;
apply their knowledge to real situations;
carry out analysis of foreign markets targeted to specific needs of companies;
draft marketing plans for an international environment;
work in international groups both in personal contact and with distance links.
International Corporate Strategy:
To succeed in the future, managers must develop the resources and capabilities needed to gain and sustain advantage in competitive markets—traditional and emerging. The way in which organizations attempt to develop such competitive advantage constitutes the essence of their strategy.
The module has been designed to allow students to gain the knowledge and expertise necessary to perform a manager role as a strategist by encouraging and enabling students to develop the intellectual and professional acumen needed for the conception and analysis of responsible business strategies; to make appropriate choices between strategic options; and then to follow a strategic trajectory that will deliver results that are robust, ethically sound and socially responsible. Accordingly, the module adopts a contingency approach that is grounded in the understanding of the non-existence of a best way in strategy.

On completion of the module you should be able to:
• Assess, analyse and reflect upon strategy and strategic decision-making.
• Apply strategy concepts and models to analyse and appraise a company’s strategy.
• Identify and evaluate strategic choices for the future.

 Learning objectives
The concept of agent was introduced in the early 90's in the field of artificial intelligence as a new paradigm for the development of intelligent systems capable of taking autonomous decisions and carrying out actions to achieve goals. The complexity of multi-agent systems has led to the definition of different development methodologies, software architectures and programming languages ​​in which the concept of agent assumes a key role as well as the concept of object-oriented object-oriented design. The objective of the course is to examine and explore the credentials of agent-based approaches as a software engineering paradigm, and to gain an insight into what agent-oriented software engineering will look like. We will present agent-oriented analysis, design and implementation techniques. In particular, the course will deal with the agent concept and the development of multi-agent systems, architectures and algorithms for agent software design, planning principles, modeling techniques and goal-oriented analysis, communication languages ​​and agent-oriented software engineering methodologies. We will also present single and multi-agent planning techniques. 

Expected learning results
At the end of the course, the student will be able to: 
1.	Define the most appropriate agent-oriented development process and model for the analysis, design and implementation of a multi-agent system;
2.	adopt the TROPOS methodology at different stages of the development of a multi-agent system;
3.	adopt the most appropriate architecture for the development of a software agent (reactive, deliberative, hybrid, multi-level, BDI);
4.	Develop a goal-oriented model as a deliberative model of a BDI agent and define its control loop;
5.	Use the PDDL language to specify a planning problem and find its solutions using the backbox planner;
6.	Define the communication between two or more software agents using the basic constructs of the speech-act theory;
7.	Develop multi-agent systems

The educational objective of the course is to provide students with skills on the use of digital signal processing algorithms and techniques for measurement and control applications in mechatronic systems.
At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- Analyze signals in the frequency domain and understand the meaning of spectral analysis;
- Understand the behaviour of linear and time-invariant (LTI)  systems both in the time domain and in the frequency domain;
- Select and use different design techniques for digital filter design;
- Use some techniques for linear system identification.

The course provides an introduction to the atmosphere and climate processes relevant for various applications of environmental engineering, ranging from weather forecasting, to regional meteo-climatological characterisation, to the assessment of meteo-climatological factors within environmental impact studies for plants and infrastructures, to air quality management, to the assessment of available renewable energy resources and the management of plants for their exploitation, to energy saving in buildings.
At the end of the course the student should be able to:
- know the basic notions introduced during the frontal lessons;
- discuss the topics of the course with critical reasoning;
- resolve exercises on the topics of the course;
- interpret correctly the output of meteorological models;
- realize, on the basis of the output of meteorological models, a simple weather forecast.

This course aims to create a bridge between classical physics and modern physics, such as relativity and quantum mechanics. It represents a completion of the learning cycle in classical physics proposed in General Physics I and II, and a background for the more advanced courses planned in the third year. The primary objective is to allow students to grasp the essential elements that led to the development of modern physics, starting from time-dependent electric and magnetic phenomena, electromagnetic theory of light, interaction between light and matter, special relativity, and the atomistic nature of matter. From these problems the need to introduce completely new conceptual and formal tools will emerge.
At the end of the course students will be able to:
understand the time-dependent Maxwell equations;
describe different processes of emission and propagation of electromagnetic radiation;
understand and apply the principles of special relativity;
solve problems of electromagnetism and special relativity;
understand basic concepts of quantum physics, starting from the Planck's quantum to the Schroedinger equation and the meaning of wave functions.

