The course aims at giving the student a deeper understanding of the fundamental principles of fiscal law, starting with statutory reserve and contribution capacity and concluding with a study of tax implementation mechanisms.
At the end of the course, student will be able:
1) to know and to understand the taxation law sources relating to the law system in the national context;
2) to know the fundamental principles of the Italian Constitution relating to the Italian tax system;
3) to know taxable persons, tax obligation and tax return, tax investigation, tax assessment, collection and refund;
4) to achieve an appropriate level of knowledge in individual income tax law;
5) to acquire the ability to illustrate the main issues of the course using the appropriated legal lexicon;
6) to learn the main links between the different legal matters discussed during the course.

The educational goal of the course is to acquire a comprehensive competence in designing and developing autonomous aerial and terrestrial mobile systems, commonly known as UAVs (unmanned aerial vehicles) and UGVs (unmanned ground vehicles).
The course aims at teaching a solid design methodology including topics such as:
1) Vehicle dynamics.
2) Control and actuation systems.
3) Electrical and electronic components.
4) Navigation systems and positioning algorithms.
5) Programming of autonomous systems on local or distributed configuration.

The course focuses on the most advanced technological solutions and the theoretical and pragmatic aspects related to the creation of specific services on the platforms used in class and real-time information processing on the vehicle.

After completing the course, the student will be able:
- to understand the complexity, the problems, and the potential of autonomous mobile systems;
- to evaluate the different enabling technologies for communication, processing and management of energy autonomy, and choose the most ideas for the project case;
- to apply the best techniques and methods for the configuration of the drone system intended as a product, configuration of data processing, and configuration of the data acquisition and processing service.
- to make comparative evaluations about the different technological solutions available for UGV and UAV systems;
- to assess and analyse the practical and theoretical implications of an autonomous mobile system;
- to design an autonomous mobile system for a particular service or application or a specific objective;
- to critically assess the benefits and limitations of existing commercial or academic solutions.

The course aims to: 
- Develop knowledge on the most relevant historical phases of the Middle Ages.
- Develop confidence in engaging with current scholarly debates.
- Develop skills in analysing a variety of types of primary sources.

After attending the course and after reading the reference bibliography, the students will be able to:
- define and describe the most important turning points of the Medieval history;
- recognize and analyze a variety of types of primary sources;
- analyze and comment a historiographic text;
- analyze a historic map;
- define and use the specific terms of the medieval studies.

The course in Anthropology allows students to acquire an informed understanding of the current theoretical and methodological issues related to the biological and cultural evolution of Genus Homo.

At the end, students will be able:
- to know the history of studies about the evolutionism and to remember the main concepts related to the origin of species;
- to understand the theorical and methodological features of the main schools of thought as far as the study of prehistoric human groups is concerned;
- to chronologically and culturally determine the archaeological artefacts dated to the European Palaeolithic and Mesolithic

The main goal is to introduce students in sociology to the main theories and findings in social psychology research that can be used to analyze social phenomena.

Specifically, the expected educational goals of attending to classes and of the individual study are: 
- having a good knowledge of social psychological processes involved in social perception, social influence and social interactions; 
- getting mastery of scientific language and theories in social psychology;
- linking theory, empirical research and practice (e.g. generating practical examples for the processes and theories; identifying the conceptual knowledge that can be used to interpret a specific social phenomenon);
- consolidating learning abilities, critical thinking and comunication abilities.

The course aims at providing students with the theoretical knowledge and the analytical skills required in order to work in a modern oenological laboratory.
By the end of the course students should have acquired:
- a good understanding of the main concepts in international (OIV) and European winemaking regulation;
- capabilities to evaluate the best approach for testing the analytical composition of wine products;
-the ability to interpret the analytical results and draw pertinent conclusions regarding possible corrective actions in vineyard or winery;
-the capacity to conduct on his own quality controls applying standard methods;
Acquired competences will enable students to operate in chemical lab with technical efficacy and risk consciousness.

Deepening the understanding of the functioning of markets and of the determinants and effectiveness of firms'' strategies, through the analysis of a specific market with appropriate data.
Specific skills to be acquired include:
- identification of the most appropriate data to describe the object of interest;
- knowledge of the various data sources, their characteristics and reliability;
- ability to work with data in order to extract relevant information;
- ability to use the theoretical concepts learnt in other courses in order to identify possible causes of the phenomenon under investigation, and to collect empirical evidence about them;
- ability to write a research report.

"There is a difference between knowledge (what the jurist knows) and skill (what the lawyer is able to do). The former belongs to the cultural heritage of jurists. The latter concerns the various activities put in practice by the jurist from his own knowledge. Through an in-depth study of personality rights, the course will enable students to become familiar with the methods of civil law and learn some key legal skills, such as understand, interpret and edit legal texts, do problem solving, A suggested reading on the distinction between knowledge and skill in the legal practice is “G. Pascuzzi, Giuristi si diventa, Come riconoscere e apprendere le abilità proprie delle professioni legali, Il Mulino, Bologna”.

By the end of the course, students will know the most important elements featuring the regulation of contract law and thus will be able to:
- read and interpret legal materials related to personality rights
(contracts, judicial decisions, regulations, scholarly contributions);
- formulate a legal problem with regard to personality rights;
- find the rules applicable to a legal problem and solve it;
- discuss critical issues regarding personality rights.
"

The aim of the course is to give a basic knowledge on electrical and magnetic phenomena, on circuits, on electromagnetic induction and on wave phenomena, focusing on elastic, sound and electromagnetic waves.
After the course the student should be able to:
1) calculate forces and fields produced by simple charge distributions; 
2) know the behaviour of different materials in presence of electromagnetic fields; 
3) treat simple circuits with resistors, condensators and inductances;
4) know the principle of electromagnetic induction with applications;
5) know the working principles of optical intruments, by calculating in some cases position and dimensions of the images;
6) know the principles of interference and diffraction by calculating the phase difference between waves in some cases;
7) know the behaviour of elastic and sound waves.

Just slightly less than half of the world’s population lives in the tropics, in highly densely populated, rapidly growing and socially vulnerable regions that are highly susceptible to changes in weather and climate on a myriad of temporal scales. This course will examine tropical atmospheric circulations that induce variations in tropical weather and climate from daily to climatic timescales, starting from the large-scale energy balance and moving down to cumulus convection. 


Learning outcomes.
At the end of the course, the students will be able to:
- Describe in detail the key phenomenological features of tropical weather and climate;
- Reproduce the governing equations and the key approximations relevant to the tropical atmosphere;
- Explain why the dynamics of the tropical atmosphere are so different from the dynamics of the extratropical atmosphere;
- Understand the implications of the fundamental dynamics for predictability on different timescales;
- Provide order-of-magnitude estimates of dominant variables and balances;
- Recognise the central importance of diabatic processes on tropical climate and the conceptual difficulties in theoretically constraining and correctly representing their interaction with the atmospheric circulation;
- Articulate physical constraints behind robust responses to global warming.

Finance MODULE

The course aims to provide the concepts, methodologies and tools needed by multinational companies in order to make effective financing and investment decisions.
Upon completion of the course the student will be able to understand the main issues and decision processes which constitute the financial management of a multinational firm, namely: 

(1) the financing decision, and 

(2) the management of exchange rate risk. 

The student will also develop the ability to apply the models covered in the course to operational problems (currency risk hedging, effective cost of foreign exchange financing).


International Accounting MODULE

1. Training objectives
The financial statement is the basis of the corporate information system. It highlights wealth production under different profiles: the financial, economic and equity profiles. The values related to the production of wealth derive from a common language: the double entry system. However, different accounting systems give rise to different values.
The course aims are as follows: 
1)to provide students with a basic knowledge of the double entry logic in order to understand where the items of the financial statement originate; 
2)to analyse some of the main issues of the evaluation in an international comparative key; 
3)to provide students with tools to read and understand the financial statement in critical terms, taking into account the differences in the different accounting systems; 
4)to enable the student to understand the purposes and limits of the financial statement.
The first part of the course is aimed at recalling the logic of the double entry system;  the second part focuses on reading, analysing and understanding the financial statement in critical terms; and the third part of the course is devoted to evaluation issues.

2. Expected learning outcomes
At the end of the course, the student should be able to
1) Understand the logic of the double entry system; 
2) Understand how the differences in valuation resulting from different accounting systems affect the results of the financial statements;
3) Understand and be able to analyse and interpret the financial statements of companies of different typology and size;
4) Identify critical accounting issues, and formulate them in a clear and structured manner;
5) Elaborate on and propose, in contribution with the critical reflections of a working group, alternatives to the business information system that are aimed at widening the informative potential of the financial statement beyond the mandatory limits defined by law.

Course aims to develop basic knowledge about the planning and implementation of advanced photonics experiments. In particular we will focus on three main aspects: a) how to interface optoelectronic instrumentation with PC to realize complex experimental setup; b) to familiarize with simulation software to model photonic devices; c) to implement the know-how acquired in the two previous items and to exploit it working on advanced experiments of photonics in research laboratories.
Attendance and active participation to training activities will enable students to:
1) identify the key elements to organize an advanced photonics experiment;
2) to sketch and simplify its structure, maintaining a level of detail appropriate to the analysis of the investigated effects;
3) to physically implement it using the most appropriate instruments;
4) to analyze the data with the most appropriate techniques, integrating experimental data with those obtained from simulations;
5) to critically evaluate the results, using quantitative descriptors;
6) to present the results in written reports that summarize the methods used in the experiments, justifying their choice, quantifying them and, possibly, to propose alternatives to improve the quality of the measurements.

The course provides a detailed but non-technical introduction to some of the key issues of the intellectual revolution that gave rise to modern science, in the 16th and 17th centuries. At the same time, it purposes to show different ways in which the very idea of «science» evolved across the centuries – in its idea, practice, and scope. Ample space will be given to reading texts of some of the chief characters of the Scientific Revolution, paying specific attention to the works of Kepler and Galileo – two contemporaries who gave major contributions to scientific thought, but had a very different understanding of the very science they were practicing.
Special attention will be paid to the reading of the “dialogue” that took place between them, through their letters and works, particularly Kepler’s Dissertatio (1610) and Narratio (1611). Texts will be read against the scientific, historic, intellectual and religious background of the early decades of the 17th century, and in the light of the contribution of the authors’ contemporaries.
The second part of the course will be devoted to Galileo’s Dialogue on the Two Chief World Systems (1632), one of the most important scientific works of the early modern period. We will consider what came before the Dialogue, and what were the consequences of its publication: the trial, the sentence, the abjuration, and how the events affected the practice of science in Italy.
At the end of the course, students will have acquired a detailed knowledge (i.e. based on the actual reading of the original texts, and not merely on the historical reconstruction of their contents) of the debate on the nature, aim, and scope of early modern science.
Students are expected to be able:
— to understand the ways in which the very idea of science has evolved, and what characterizes in throughout its many transformations;
— to read and understand, in its original language or in translation, the works of some of the key protagonists of the Scientific Revolutions;
— to consult specialized works in the history of science;
— to deliver a presentation that develops a specific subject referred to in the course;
— to take an oral examination on the subjects presented at the course, discussing specific passages and putting them in their proper context.

 The monographic course of Doctrine of the State provides students with the fundamental notions concerning constitutional doctrines and the evolution of the forms of state and government. In particular, we will study the characteristics of the electoral legislation and its influence on the form of government. For this purpose we will comment on the book La legge elettorale cecoslovacca, written by Costantino Mortati in 1946.

At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
- master the language and the essential concepts of the European constitutional laboratory of the twentieth century;
- recognize elements of continuity and discontinuity in the legal experiences analyzed and the respective constitutional models;
- critically evaluate the current debates on constitutional transformations in the light of the legacy of legal-cultural reflection developed  in the twentieth century.

The course aims to make the student aware of the increasingly important role and influence of European Union law on the civil and commercial law of Member States. The course also aims to make the students aware of  the mechanisms through which harmonization and unification of private law take place I the European Union and make them aware of the ways and means by which our legal system evolves in the community.
At the end of the course, the student will be able to evaluate the effects on the Italian system of goals, instruments and solutions prepared by European law. In particular, it is expected that the student will demonstrate the ability to:
- to analyze the mechanisms of the process of Europeanization and harmonization of national law, that is to say the contents, tools and effects of the phases of harmonization, uniformization and unification;
- to identify the role of institutional actors involved in the process of Europeanization and harmonization and, more generally, in the process of circulating legal models;
- to have a critical reading of the operating rules, both positive and jurisdictional, in specific areas (companies, consumer contracts, producer responsibility, competition and antitrust rules, industrial law and intellectual property);
- to evaluate the effects of the process of Europeanization and harmonization of national law, with particular reference to the hypotheses of transforming the source system, forced abandonment of previous and consolidated principles, innovation of the meaning and content of internal rules.

The goal of the course is to offer instruments and skills to understand the complex relations between development and security. How did development help overcome security challenges? The answer to this question will be illustrated through case studies from the twentieth century, especially from Africa. Specific training objectives are:
1)	Students will acquire a basic knowledge of the main events and turning points in the history of development and its nexus with a broad definition of security;
2)	Students will acquire the skills to deal with current debates on the nexus between development and security, with a special focus on the African context;
3)	Students will be able to articulate persuasive and well-structured arguments with a sound historical basis and engage in a formal debate on complex emergency situations.

The course intends to make students aware of pervasiveness of organisations in contemporary society, to outline main contributions and emergent perspectives in organisational studies, to offer them keys in order to analyse and critically interpret their features and processes. 

At the end of the course students are expected to acquire:
-	a thorough knowledge of the key concepts and of the main theoretical perspectives in organisational studies; 
-	a general knowledge of the main issues, classical and emergent, in organisational studies;
-	a basic interpretive lens to read and critically analyse the main organisational phenomena;
- a deeper understanding of the concept and processes of organisational innovation.

At the end of the course, students will: 
- know and understand basic concepts of the debate on corporate governance and corporate social responsibility;
- know and understand main issues concerning on the efficiency of corporate governance structures; 
- know and understand institutions and practices of corporate governance in a national and international perspective.

The course introduces to the main theoretical and methodological perspectives of urban studies. The classical dichotomy urban-rural will be discussed, focusing the analysis on urban space, its evolution across the time and the historical dynamics affecting its change. Global cities, urban segregation, immigration, sprawl and gentrification will be specific topic of the course
At the end of the course, students have to be able of arguing about urban and rural spaces:
- discerning among different phenomena, theoretical approaches and interpretative levels;
- achieving skills in deconstructing and interpreting phenomena in a critical and documented way;
- being capable to formulate consistent statements and analyses;
- making a written text, that have to be clear, exhaustive, documented and consequential, focused on several topics developed during the course.

The course aims to introduce students to the study of the several legal issues involved in the management of data, by critically analysing a selection of topics characterizing this area. At the end of the course, students will be able:
- to familiarise with the basic concepts of the legal issues involved in Data science;
- to be able to critically analyse such issues;
- to learn how to manage a data science scenario from a legal point of view;
- to complete their data scientist profile with the necessary legal knowledges.

1. Teaching objectives and contents.
The aim of the course is to provide students with an introductory knowledge of the business administration of the company and of the business operation and accountint methods. The course aims to develop the concept of "economia aziendale" in a complete and timely manner and to deepen its operating mechanisms in terms of management, organization and accounting procedures. Teaching will enable you to thoroughly investigate all aspects of the accounting technique with reference to the operations of establishing, managing, settling and final drawing up of the financial and capital situation. Finally, we will offer some elements of financial statement analysis for flows and indices, after making the appropriate reclassification of the accounting schemes.

2. Expected results.
At the end of the course, students will be able to:
1. Know the concept of economia aziendale and identify the elements that characterize the company and the company's production process;
2. identify different corporate governance models and evaluate the different features in different business contexts;
3. recognize the different strategies pursued by companies, both at corporate and business level;
4. Understand the double book-keeping method mechanism for keeping the accounting and apply it to the various business management operations (constitution, purchases and sales of goods and services, labor costs, investments, asset operations, settlement and closing of accounts) ;
5. build an income statement and balance sheet in order to analyze the creation of company operating income and the dynamics of its assets;
6. analyze the financial statements through indices and flows to understand and describe the performance of a company.

The planet is currently shaped by very strong regional inequalities. Life-chances are distributed very unevenly among the populations of the many states existing in the world. What explains why some states enjoy a high standard of living while others are pretty poor? What explain why the development of some areas has been remarkable in recent decades, while others have failed in improving their conditions? Which social factors contribute to the development of a country, a region, a geographical area?
Attending the course, students will acquire:
- an adequate knowledge of the nature and evolution of regional inequalities among the various areas of the planet;
- an adequate knowledge of the main factors that interact in the development process;
- a familiarity with the main debates in the sociology of international development;
- competence in focusing, discuss and critically analyze such debates

The course aims at making the students able to understand the basic concepts of inferential statistics, and to use a statistical software (in the course, R will be used) to perform the most common analyses.

At the end of the course, successful students are expected to
- understand the basic concepts of probability (event, independence, conditional probability, random variable and their distribution);
- are able to apply these concepts in simple examples; are able to compute probabilities relative at least to the binomial model and the normal distribution;
- understand the key concepts of inferential statistics (confidence interval, hypothesis test) and are able to apply to standard cases analysed during the course;
- are able to use R to perform standard statistical analysis (t-test, chi-square, analysis of variance, linear regression), understanding the meaning of the output and the assumptions used in the analysis.

The course aims to provide students with the basic concepts of electricity and magnetism and the basic knowledge of the electrical and magnetic properties of matter. In this way, students will be able in the following courses to understand the application of the Maxwell equations in the study of time dependent electric and magnetic phenomena and the theory of electromagnetic radiation and its interaction with matter.

Electromagnetism will be presented starting from the phenomenology and examples will be discussed related to natural manifestations of electromagnetic phenomena and their technological applications.

Due to the frequency and to the active participation in the training activities offered by the course (lectures, exercises and tutoring) and to the individual study, the student will be able to:
- Describe the electrical and magnetic properties of matter;
- Understand the four Maxwell equations;
- Solve electromagnetism problems.

The main learning objectives of this course are:
deepening the students' knowledge in  marketing;
developing their capability to apply that knowledge to a firm's activity;
developing their capability to work in the unfamiliar context of an international group, under stressful conditions.
At the end of the course the students will be able to:
identify the information needed for evaluating the market situation of a company operating in durable consumer goods (and by analogy of all firms);
understand such informartion and carefully analyse it in order to identify the possible strategies and marketing actions that the firm can implement;
define the details of these actions and plan them, working in cooperation with the team;
develop the capacity to work under stress, in a multinational group of previously unknown people;
acquire multi-cultural and behavioural soft skills useful for working in an international firm.

GENERAL TRAINING OBJECTIVES OF THE COURSE
Starting from a brief introduction on the evolution of the media and on the "mediamorphosis" made in the course of contemporary history, we intend to reflect on the meaning of the expression "digital education". We will analyze the relationship dynamics produced through social networks, which have led to defining the paradigm of the "information society". Within this new social paradigm we intend to reflect, among other topics, on the theme of post-truth, on the new and impulsive forms of dialogue such as hate speech, on the growing importance assumed by web reputation, verifying from a pedagogically point of view, how this digitized horizon of existence affects the construction of personal identity.
EXPECTED LEARNING RESULTS
At the end of the course - which includes lectures, classroom discussions, seminar and cooperative learning activities, short optional reports - the student will have acquired the following knowledge and skills:
- Define the fundamental terms and concepts in the evolution technology, applying these notions to current life contexts in a pedagogical key on the basis of media education reflections;
- interpret the different forms of representation and theorizing in the relationship between human beings and digital technologies;
- Analyze and understand the results of the most recent research on the effects and interactions between childhood and digital media;
- Improve digital civic literacy, being aware of the methods used to deform reality and delegitimize dialogue skills (fake news, echo chambers, hate speech, etc.);
- Give an interpretation of the authors' texts proposed by the teacher during the lessons;
- Expose content with appropriate language;
- Perform a metacognitive work to evaluate the results achieved for the enrichment of the training path.

The aim of the course is to introduce students to the formal techniques for the automatic verification of security properties on cryptographic protocols. After discussing the theoretical foundations of programming languages, the course applies the related techniques to model protocols and construct algorithms which verify their robustness to attacks.

At the end of the course, students must have learned to:
- reason about fixed points of a functions over a domain;
- model protocols in suitable formalisms;
- know the negative results associated to protocol verification;
- describe the main protocol verification techniques (model checking, static analysis);
- understand some algorithms for protocol verification;
- use a software tool for protocol verification, including the generation of formal security proofs;
- know the basis of the logic used to write such formal proofs.

The course aims to give students the basic tools to learn and deepen the characteristics of labor law and the fundamental principles that characterize it through the study of the various institutes. 
The subject of the course is the study of the legislative and contractual discipline applicable to employment relationships also in relation to the principles established by the Constitution, from international and community sources. Particular attention will be given to the jurisprudence of the various institutes. 
The training goal is to provide students with a wealth of knowledge that allows them to use the various sources of labor law reasonably to properly address the issues and to address the issues that may arise in future professional activity. 

At the end of the course students will have to demonstrate: knowledge of the structural features of Labor law and its fundamental principles; 
ability to master the normative sources (including international and community) and its jurisprudence; 
ability to understand and correctly use the language of speech; 
ability to solve practical cases related to personnel management.

The main objective of the course is to provide theoretical and analytical tools deriving from political and economic geography aimed at understanding social, political and economic phenomena in their spatial deployment. More specifically, the module will focus on the relations between power and space with regard to development, territorial matters, resources, conflicts and other key topics. The module aims to develop students autonomous capacity to engage critically with current geopolitical and geo-economic issues.
The expected learning outcomes include: 
-	Knowledge and understanding of the spatial aspects of current phenomena and of the relations between places and global economy, as well as between space and politics;
-	Familiarity with the methods and tools of economic and political geography;
-	Ability to understand and accurately use key concepts related to the discipline (i.e. geographic scale, regions, nation state, borders);
-	Capacity to develop critical analysis and autonomous judgment. Students are expected to be able to connect their critical understandings of the relations between geographical space and related phenomena with the spheres of political science, international relations and sociology.

The goal of the course is to provide students with theoretical and practical tools for the design and implementation of correct and efficient algorithmic solutions for a large set of computational problems.

At the end of the course, students are expected:
A) to remember the characteristics of the main data structures and to understand what could be their contribution in the solution of computational problems;
B) to formally describe a selected collection of computational problems and their solution, being able to discuss their correctness;
C) to know the main algorithmic techniques and to select those better suited to solve a particular problem;
D) to analyze the computational complexity of algorithms, i.e. to quantify the resources needed for their executions;
E) to compare distinct algorithmic solutions and to select the one which is better suited given a particular input.

Based on these competences related to the literature of “classical” algorithms, students should be able to solve a large array of computational problems, i.e.:
F) to precisely understand the problem to be solved, by defining the mathematical relationship between the input and the output of the problem;
G) to design an algorithmic solution for such problem, by adapting an existing solution or by building a new solution from scratch;;
H) to evaluate the correctness and the computational complexity of the proposed solution;
I) to implement the selected solution by using an imperative programming language.

The module aims at providing basic knowledge on geology and geomorphology, with particular attention to the processes that modify the landscape at different spatial and temporal scale.
At the end of the module students will be able to:
- classify the main physical processes shaping the Earth’s surface;
- use the correct technical geological terminology;
- read and interpret a geological map;
- recognize the effects of different geological and geomorphological processes on the landscape.

The course aims to introduce students to the understanding of historical and political events that have structured the local administrative system of the unitary Italian State. The learning outcomes are: 
- the acquisition of the basics of the history of administrative institutions and its disciplinary tradition; 
- the knowledge of the diachronic and problematic framework of the topic;  
- the ability to use the comparison to highlight the different administrative traditions of the ancient Italian States and the new unitary State; 
- the awareness of the role and importance of local administrative institutions in Government and in the management of the territory.

The course aims at giving a comprehensive understanding of the logics of biolaw (with a few references to bioethics) in a number of Countries.
At the end of the course, the student will be apple to:
- Identify the (always changing) object of the life sciences (bio-objects);
- to navigate within the complex system of sources of the biolaw;
- to recognize, construct and critically evaluate normative models in the different fields treated
- define the principles and rules governing areas such as beginning of life, end-life, genetics, scientific research.

The main objective is to put students in the position to understand and appreciate the modern methods of quantization for Yang-Mills theories, the spontaneous symmetry breaking and in general terms the mathematical structure of the standard model of elementary particle interactions.
At the end of the course, the attending student should be able to:
1. know the fundamentals of non abelian gauge theories and their quantization;
2. understand spontaneous symmetry breaking and the most important Higgs mechanism;
3. understand the power of gauge symmetries in formulating interacting theories of fundamental weak and strong interaction;
4. know principles and applications of the Weinberg-Salam electroweak theory.

IN ORDER TO TEACH A LANGUAGE IS CRUCIAL THE UNDERSTANDING OF LEARNING PROCESSES AND ACQUISITIONAL SEQUENCES LEARNERS GO THROUGH. THE COURSE AIMS TO PROVIDE STUDENTS WITH THEORETICAL AND METHODOLOGICAL RESOURCES USEFUL TO COMPREHEND THIS PROCESS AND TO OBSERVE AND ANALYSE L2 ITALIAN LEARNERS’ DATA, IN ORDER TO INCREASE COMPETENCES IN THE EVALUATION OF LEARNERS’ NEEDS AND IN EFFECTIVE TEACHING.
AT THE END OF THE COURSE, STUDENTS WILL BE ABLE TO:
A) COMPREHEND DYNAMICS OF LANGUAGE LEARNING;
B) ANALYSE L2 ITALIAN INTERLANGUAGE;
C) PLAN AND PERFORM TEACHING ACTIVITIES FOCUSED ON LEARNERS’ NEEDS, ON THE BASIS OF THE COMPRENSION OF LEARNER’ ACQUISITIONAL PHASE AND OF THE SELECTION OF OBJECTIVES, MATERIALS AND MODALITIES SUITABLE FOR THE LEARNING CONTEXT.

The aim of the course is to introduce students to the formal techniques for the automatic verification of security properties on cryptographic protocols. After discussing the theoretical foundations of programming languages, the course applies the related techniques to model protocols and construct algorithms which verify their robustness to attacks.

At the end of the course, students must have learned to:
- reason about fixed points of a functions over a domain;
- model protocols in suitable formalisms;
- know the negative results associated to protocol verification;
- describe the main protocol verification techniques (model checking, static analysis);
- understand some algorithms for protocol verification;
- use a software tool for protocol verification, including the generation of formal security proofs;
- know the basis of the logic used to write such formal proofs.

Students will be provided with:
- solid theoretic-philosophical tools to understand the basic principles characterizing the main families of contemporary ethical and moral theories as well the role they play in the information society;
- practical knowledge on different approaches to analyze ethical implications in design and to embed ethical decisions in a design process;
- practical knowledge on the various aspects concerning deontology which are of interest to professions related with information technology, communication and research.

The course “Computer Science and Programming II” is dedicated to acquiring the competences and skills necessary for the design and development of the front-end applications (Web and mobile) using Web technologies and instruments. The course introduces and explains the basic technologies for the development of Web-based interfaces (HTML5, CSS, JavaScript); addresses the modern principles for the Web and mobile interface modelling; introduces the technologies and frameworks for their realization. Through the course materials the student will acquire the notions and knowledge, which then will allow them to
-	 Implement Web pages with the static and dynamic content;
-	 Customize and extend the Web interfaces using CSS Styles and the corresponding frameworks;
-	 Understand the design and modeling principles and the corresponding guidelines for the implementation of the front-end applications, such as “responsive design” and “material design”;
-	 Understand the models and architectural patters for the implementation of the front-end applications;
-	 Understand and be able to use the state-of-art frameworks for the implementation of the Wen and mobile app interfaces.

The course provides a detailed but non-technical introduction to some of the key issues of the intellectual revolution that gave rise to modern science, in the 16th and 17th centuries. At the same time, it purposes to show different ways in which the very idea of «science» evolved across the centuries – in its idea, practice, and scope. Ample space will be given to reading texts of some of the chief characters of the Scientific Revolution, paying specific attention to the works of Kepler and Galileo – two contemporaries who gave major contributions to scientific thought, but had a very different understanding of the very science they were practicing.
Special attention will be paid to the reading of the “dialogue” that took place between them, through their letters and works, particularly Kepler’s Dissertatio (1610) and Narratio (1611). Texts will be read against the scientific, historic, intellectual and religious background of the early decades of the 17th century, and in the light of the contribution of the authors’ contemporaries.
The second part of the course will be devoted to Galileo’s Dialogue on the Two Chief World Systems (1632), one of the most important scientific works of the early modern period. We will consider what came before the Dialogue, and what were the consequences of its publication: the trial, the sentence, the abjuration, and how the events affected the practice of science in Italy.
At the end of the course, students will have acquired a detailed knowledge (i.e. based on the actual reading of the original texts, and not merely on the historical reconstruction of their contents) of the debate on the nature, aim, and scope of early modern science.
Students are expected to be able:
— to understand the ways in which the very idea of science has evolved, and what characterizes in throughout its many transformations;
— to read and understand, in its original language or in translation, the works of some of the key protagonists of the Scientific Revolutions;
— to consult specialized works in the history of science;
— to deliver a presentation that develops a specific subject referred to in the course;
— to take an oral examination on the subjects presented at the course, discussing specific passages and putting them in their proper context.

Deepening the understanding of the functioning of markets and of the determinants and effectiveness of firms'' strategies, through the analysis of a specific market with appropriate data.
Specific skills to be acquired include:
- identification of the most appropriate data to describe the object of interest;
- knowledge of the various data sources, their characteristics and reliability;
- ability to work with data in order to extract relevant information;
- ability to use the theoretical concepts learnt in other courses in order to identify possible causes of the phenomenon under investigation, and to collect empirical evidence about them;
- ability to write a research report.

The course aims to provide students with a concise yet comprehensive picture of the main legal issues concerning international governmental organizations. Following a broad historical overview of the phenomenon, starting from the intergovernmental diplomatic conferences of the 19th century, the course will dwell on the fundamental stages of progressive institutionalization of international organizations. Within this context, the structure and functions of international organizations in light of their founding treaties and, possibly, ultra vires, will be examined in depth. The core part of the course will be devoted to the law of the United Nations, with particular attention to the admission to and membership of the UN, to the concepts of legitimacy and lawfulness in the UN system, and to the legal relationships among the main UN bodies. 
Special attention will be devoted to international current events, which provide ample opportunity to understand how international law and the law of international organizations, together with politics and economics, affect international relations and States’ internal affairs. 
In the current academic year special attention will be devoted to the role and functions of international organizations in dealing with health emergencies.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to: 
-	Appreciate the distinctive features of international organizations vis-à-vis their Member States; 
-	Understand the significance of founding treaties of international organizations, and their effects on the life of the organizations themselves; 
-	Identify – also by way of concrete examples – the impact of international organizations, and of the UN in particular, on the creation and development of international customary law and treaties; 
-	Discern the various functions performed by international organizations, at the regional and universal levels;
-	Understand how UN law affects the main issues concerning States’ relations (from the protection of human rights to the fight against international terrorism, the system of collective security, disarmament, protection of the environment, fight against pandemics…).

The course is aimed to obtain the necessary knowledge about:
- phases of building process (planning, implementation, use) as concerns definition and check of costs of the building process;
- global cost and life cycle concepts and their application to planning, programming and management of costs;
- cost analysis during different phases of the project;
- timelines and costs check during planning and implementation phases of a building;
- analysis of alternative design proposals through value analysis (basic concepts).

The course aims to provide a comprehensive, but detailed view of the cellular and molecular complexity of the nervous system. Particular emphasis will be given to morphological characteristics and genetic mechanisms that characterize the properties of neurons and to the interneuronal communication systems underlying synaptic transmission.
By the end of the course, the students will be able to:
1. Carefully and comprehensively define the cellular and molecular complexity of central nervous system (Remember), comparing and discussing different cell types of the brain based on their morphological and functional characteristics (Understand-Analyzing);
2. Examine the molecular mechanisms responsible for neuronal properties such as neuronal transport, active and passive electrical properties (Analyzing);
3. Classify basic characteristics interneuronal communication and synaptic transmission, discriminating different chemical and electrical neuron-to-neuron communication systems (electrical and chemical synapses, different neurotransmitters and their receptors) (understand, analyze);
4. Explain and discuss the cellular and molecular basis of neuron-glia metabolic unit (neuron – astrocytes – capillaries, glycolysis versus oxidative phosphorylation) (understand, analyze).

The goal of this course is to provide students with advanced notions on the
main problem and techniques in the designe and implementation of distributed systems. The course is a follow-up of "Distributed Systems 1".

Consider it as course on "Distributed Algorithms"; the focus is on the principles, rather than on a particular technology. Concretely this includes the following objectives:
- Present the principles underlying the functioning of distributed systems;
- Create an awareness of the major technical challenges in distributed systems design and implementation;
- Expose students to current techniques used to solve the aforementioned challenges;
- Provide experience in the implementation of typical algorithms used in distributed systems;
- Expose students to current technology and distributed infrastructure software.

 Learning objectives
The concept of agent was introduced in the early 90's in the field of artificial intelligence as a new paradigm for the development of intelligent systems capable of taking autonomous decisions and carrying out actions to achieve goals. The complexity of multi-agent systems has led to the definition of different development methodologies, software architectures and programming languages ​​in which the concept of agent assumes a key role as well as the concept of object-oriented object-oriented design. The objective of the course is to examine and explore the credentials of agent-based approaches as a software engineering paradigm, and to gain an insight into what agent-oriented software engineering will look like. We will present agent-oriented analysis, design and implementation techniques. In particular, the course will deal with the agent concept and the development of multi-agent systems, architectures and algorithms for agent software design, planning principles, modeling techniques and goal-oriented analysis, communication languages ​​and agent-oriented software engineering methodologies. We will also present single and multi-agent planning techniques. 

Expected learning results
At the end of the course, the student will be able to: 
1.	Define the most appropriate agent-oriented development process and model for the analysis, design and implementation of a multi-agent system;
2.	adopt the TROPOS methodology at different stages of the development of a multi-agent system;
3.	adopt the most appropriate architecture for the development of a software agent (reactive, deliberative, hybrid, multi-level, BDI);
4.	Develop a goal-oriented model as a deliberative model of a BDI agent and define its control loop;
5.	Use the PDDL language to specify a planning problem and find its solutions using the backbox planner;
6.	Define the communication between two or more software agents using the basic constructs of the speech-act theory;
7.	Develop multi-agent systems

Through the deep study of the Newtonian mechanics, at the end of the course the student will have acquired the knowledge of the scientific method and the skill to model and describe the physical phenomena .
The main objectives are therefore:
- To provide basic knowledge on the physical laws of Newtonian mechanics;
- Develop expertise on the scientific method;
- Develop the ability to model a simple physical problem and find the solution ("problem solving").

At the end of the course an engaged participant would have: 
[(i)] acquired a knowledge of and a basic command in a computer programming language; 
[(ii)] knowledge on how to systematically search for a solutions for socio-economic problems by employing simulations; 
[(iii)]  be equipped to construct alternative, virtual socio-economic scenarios to perform computational experiments; 
[(iv)] will have better understanding of the power and limitations of computations "not everything is computable"; 
[(v)] will be able to appreciate - in contrast to the standard idea of rational behavior characterized as optimizing agents or institutions - the connection that exists between "models of man", markets and institutions characterized as problem solvers and their formal descriptions as algorithms.

The course aims to teach the history and the theories of landscape as well as to experiment methodologies and techniques of landscapes’ analysis and design. Through the analysis and the design experimentation of the landscape in its different phases, the course offers the chance to acquire tools to interpret historical and contemporary, natural and artificial, open spaces and their transformations. By the end of the course students will be able to:
• know and use tools for analyzing the landscape;
• interpret and describe the sense of the places and the ongoing transformations in open spaces of the city (like the physical/morphological context, economic and social landscapes, systems and flows, frameworks);
• learn methodologies and techniques to design and management the landscape in Alpine urban contexts;
• define and design a project for a complex area by verifying the compatibility with general plans and the consistency with the context (nature and history, transformability and constraints, natural and social dynamics);
• define and represent a project idea that highlights the interpretation of context also through the experimentation of traditional or innovative tools (like urban design, urban performances, artistic actions in the city and the landscape, digital devices and new media);
• communicate the project through a variety of tools for a large group of stakeholders (technicians, practitioners, citizens).

The first part of the course aims to transmit the fundamentals of the engineering thermodynamics and to provide the skills for the process analysis of the moist air. The objectives of the second part include the study of heat and mass transfer mechanisms.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
• set energy balances and to evaluate the performance of a system by means the first and second laws of thermodynamics;
• Perform an analysis of the main power cycles;
• Perform a thorough analysis of moist air processes of technical interest (air conditioning processes and surface and interstitial condensation in building structures);
• Set up and solve stationary and multi-dimensional heat transfer problems, even in unsteady state, possibly by using numerical methods;
• Set up and solve mass transport problems within fluids and structures.

The aim of the class is to learn knowledge and skills to analyze consumer’s choice and, in general, the economic decision.

Students will be able through the attendance to the class of:

Identifying the most relevant aspects of the decision-making process;
Summarizing and interpreting data and information that are necessary for the description and prediction of consumer choice;
Comparing tools and methods discussed in the class and choosing that one which best fits the problem;
Applying the selected method within the framework of sustainable consumption;
Judging the applicability of methods for the descriptive and predictive analysis of consumer choice within the framework of sustainable consumption.

The active attendance to the class will consent the student to be able to work in a team, apply problem solving techniques, and critically defend found/expected results.

The main objective of the course is to train students in the main legal aspects of open science. 
Students will learn the core dynamics affecting the open science world, focusing on the opportunities and the benefits of making science and research open while being introduced to the legal constraints that risk endangering this treasured process.
At the end of the course, students will know the main elements that characterize the legal regulation of open science and will be able to:
- critically analyze these elements;
- apply the rules to specific legal issues;
- read and understand contracts in the area of intellectual property;
- develop logical and clear arguments;
- work collaboratively.

This course aims to provide a critical knowledge of the history of Italian literature in the period between Tasso and the end of the nineteenth century.
Within this chronological frame, we will focus either on a literary theme or genre, through texts by various authors, or on the study of a single author or work, also with respect to their critical reception through history.
At the end of the course students will be able to:
a. supply a critical and historical framework for the theme, genre, author, or work at hand;
b. have in-depth knowledge and comment texts introduced in class;
c. confidently orient themselves within the assigned secondary literature

The aim of the course is to provide an overview of the basic mechanisms in atomic physics, the techniques of experimental analysis and applications to high resolution quantum sensors. The course will focus in particular on the atomic structure, the atomic properties in interaction with electromagnetic fields, the basic elements of atomic interferometry. High-resolution laser spectroscopy and ultra-cold gas manipulation techniques will be treated theoretically and experimentally.

At the end of the course the student:
1. will be able to describe the salient properties of atomic spectra;
2. will be able to read and understand scientific articles on the topics covered in class;
3. will have a basic knowledge of the main experimental techniques in atomic spectroscopy;
4. will be able to propose basic experiments in which atoms interacting with electromagnetic fields realize quantum sensors.

The course aims at introducing the main time series forecasting tools used in business-oriented organizations. In particular, the program is focused on time series regression models, time series decomposition, exponential smoothing and ARIMA models. The approach is data-driven, i.e. we will introduce only the theory necessary for the analysis of real datasets. At the end of the course the student is expected to be able to (i) estimate a multiple time series regression model and interpret the results; (ii) predict a time series by means of an appropriate forecasting method and interpret the results; (iii) master the R software.
My main goal in teaching this class consists in transmitting to the students the belief that apparently complicated statistical techniques are not only mathematical sophistications, but also tools with a tremendous impact in practical applications, and that they are important assets for professional success. In my opinion, a manager who masters complex statistical methods has a better understanding of the processes and projects going on in an organization.
I am convinced that the most effective way of learning quantitative methods is based on problem solving. Accordingly, I will assign regular homeworks that have a threefold advantage:
1. they mimick a situation that the students will often encounter in their career: they will have to solve a problem within a deadline;
2. they encourage group work: even though the students will be individually responsible for the solution, hopefully they will realize that working together can produce a better result in a shorter time;
3. they will give the students a motivation for a thorough understanding of the methods presented in class.

