The course introduces to the main theoretical and methodological perspectives of urban studies. The classical dichotomy urban-rural will be discussed, focusing the analysis on urban space, its evolution across the time and the historical dynamics affecting its change. Global cities, urban segregation, immigration, sprawl and gentrification will be specific topic of the course
At the end of the course, students have to be able of arguing about urban and rural spaces:
- discerning among different phenomena, theoretical approaches and interpretative levels;
- achieving skills in deconstructing and interpreting phenomena in a critical and documented way;
- being capable to formulate consistent statements and analyses;
- making a written text, that have to be clear, exhaustive, documented and consequential, focused on several topics developed during the course.

The course aims to introduce students to a specific topic about the Middle Ages, to show them a research method and to provide them with skills to carry out individual research on Middle Age history.
At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
(a) report the main contents of the course, using an appropriate vocabulary;
(b) expose methods that have been used in the research path to reach determined conclusions;
(c) analyse a historical source about the subjects covered in the teaching describing the features and articulations of its form and content
(d) judge the results of the research critically, hypothesising different solutions or proposing further research.

The course shall focus on the emerging issues of marketing management. Each topic will be analysed both from a methodological and a operative point of view. The expected skills at the end of the course are the following:
- knowledge of the main logics of communication and brand value management;
- comprehension of the main market decisions of the firms;
- consideration of the new opportunities of communication and relation with the customers

- Get an in-depth and updated understanding of the problems related to multimessenger high energy astrophysics and of  astroparticle physics;

- In-depth knowledge of the basic problems related to multi-messenger astrophysics and of astroparticle  physics, of the goals of the scientific experiments currently underway or under construction both on ground and in space;

- Knowledge of modern instruments and observation techniques for multi-messenger astrophysics experiments and for  astroparticle physics, both on ground and in space;

- Knowledge of the specific technical-scientific lexicon.

The course has three educational goals:
1)	have a good knowledge of the main characteristics and problems of the Italian and European labour market;
2)	understand the mechanisms underpinning the labour supply decisions of individuals and families, as well as some related choices (education and fertility);
3)	learn to analyse the functioning of the labour market and to evaluate the possible consequences of labour market institutions and policies, as well as of information asymmetries, on employment, wages, payment schemes and gender differences. 
The course for Economics and Management has also the additional aim to deepen the knowledge of the Italian and European labour market (mainly through empirical evidence).

The course aims to provide the basics notions for understanding the legal and institutional context in which the various economic actors work, through the analysis of the structure and methods of intervention of public institutions that – globally, at the European and at the national level – operate for the regulation of economy.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
- identify the public institutions that take part in the governance of the economy, distinguishing between global, European and national level;	
- identify the rules and legal acts used for the regulation of the economy;	
- know the powers and procedures used by regulatory authorities and understand how they work;	
- distinguish the different ways for public authorities to intervene in the economy and understand the working dynamics of enterprises with public participation;	
- know and understand the functioning of the administrative tools used to regulate business activity in the market;	
- know and understand the ways in which public institutions intervene for the safeguard of the competitivity of the market.

The main goal is to introduce students in sociology to the main theories and findings in social psychology research that can be used to analyze social phenomena.

Specifically, the expected educational goals of attending to classes and of the individual study are: 
- having a good knowledge of social psychological processes involved in social perception, social influence and social interactions; 
- getting mastery of scientific language and theories in social psychology;
- linking theory, empirical research and practice (e.g. generating practical examples for the processes and theories; identifying the conceptual knowledge that can be used to interpret a specific social phenomenon);
- consolidating learning abilities, critical thinking and comunication abilities.

Teaching Objectives:
The criminal law course will be organized in three parts, in order to provide in-depth knowledge of:  1. a comparative prospective: constitutional principles and basic concepts of criminal law, foundations' structure and categories of criminal law, punishability and different kinds of penalties; 2. developments occurred in European criminal law both in the legislation and in the case-law as well as their influence on our criminal law and criminal justice system; 3.fundamental principles of international criminal law. The course aims to teach students a method that allows them to move with confidence in the complex international scene, mastering the system of the sources and their complex interactions.
Expected teaching results:
At the end of the course, the student is expected to show:
- Knowledge of constitutional principles and basic concepts and categories of Italian criminal law;
- knowledge of the doctrine on the purposes of criminal punishment and its evolution;
and of the sanctioning system;
-basic knowledge of the EU competences in the field of criminal law;
-knowledge and understanding of the main principles and instruments disciplining European cooperation in criminal matters; 
-general understanding of the system of protection of fundamental rights in the area of freedom security and justice.
- knowledge of the birth and evolution of International Criminal Justice;
- deep knowledge of the Statute of the International Criminal Court and the general principles of law contained in it;
- knowledge of the leading cases of the international jurisprudence;
- ability to carry out a critical analysis of the provisions of the Rome Statute and jurisprudential decisions;
- ability to use the technical language in an appropriate and precise fashion;
- ability to find in-depth materials, especially in the international case-law databases;
- familiarity with the website of the International Criminal Court.

The course aims to: 
- Appreciation of the political, social and cultural history of the Medieval age.
- Develop confidence in engaging with current scholarly debates.
- Develop skills in analysing a variety of types of primary sources.

After attending the course and after reading the reference bibliography, the students will be able to:
- define and describe the specific characters of the Medieval history;
- define and describe the most important turning points of the Medieval history;
- recognize and analyze a variety of types of primary sources;
- analyze and comment a historiographic text;
- analyze a historic map;
- define and use the specific terms of the medieval studies.
- be able to briefly present a book on medieval history.

The Chemistry course provides the basic concepts of inorganic chemistry with the aim to understand and interpret natural phenomena, both in everyday life and in the future professional activity.

The main aims of the course are to:
•	develop, in the students, the proper chemical knowledge and property of language suitable to handle chemical problems with a rigorous scientific approach; 
•	provide a description of the structure of atoms, of the chemical bonds and of the molecules that lead to the formation of inorganic compounds and that explain their physical-chemical properties; 
•	illustrate the interactions between atoms and between molecules, to comprehend the different aggregation states of the matter (solid, liquid and gas) and their phase transitions;
•	provide a description of the transformation of matter through the chemical reactions from a thermodynamic point of view, to determine energy balance, spontaneous reaction trend, and equilibrium conditions;
•	develop the capacity to carry out chemical calculations relative to mass, charge and energy balance; 
•	develop the capacity to analyse and study the most common reactions of simple inorganic compounds such as gaseous or solid solute dissolutions, acid and base dissociations in water solutions, oxidation-reduction processes.

This Chemistry course is therefore complementary to the Physics ones in the study of the intrinsic properties of the matter and in its transformations.

At the end of the course, the student will be able to: 
•	describe the elementary particle structure of atoms, isotopes and their ions;
•	describe the electronic configurations of the various elements, to predict their main periodic properties and their chemical reactivity; 
•	understand and justify atomic bonding in inorganic compounds by means of ionic- and valence-bond theory;
•	comprehend the interatomic and intermolecular interactions to understand the various aggregation states of the matter and their phase transitions, to interpret the phase diagrams of elements and pure substances; 
•	describe the behaviour of the ideal gas phase of pure substances and of their mixtures, correlating the macroscopic and microscopic physical quantity of the matter; 
•	describe the chemical solutions, the main concentration units, and the colligative properties and quantify their effects;
•	describe the equilibrium state of a chemical reaction, calculate its equilibrium constant value from the thermodynamic data of reagents and products, predict their theoretical final quantities;
•	calculate the solubility of different compounds (gasses, molecular or ionic solids) in saturated aqueous solutions;
•	calculate the pH value of ideal aqueous solutions for strong and weak acids and bases, hydrolysing salts, buffer solutions;
•	calculate the electric potential of chemical electrodes and the electromotive force of chemical cell.

The first part of the course aims to transmit the fundamentals of the engineering thermodynamics and to provide the skills for the process analysis of the moist air. The objectives of the second part include the study of heat and mass transfer mechanisms.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
• set energy balances and to evaluate the performance of a system by means the first and second laws of thermodynamics;
• Perform an analysis of the main power cycles;
• Perform a thorough analysis of moist air processes of technical interest (air conditioning processes and surface and interstitial condensation in building structures);
• Set up and solve stationary and multi-dimensional heat transfer problems, even in unsteady state, possibly by using numerical methods;
• Set up and solve mass transport problems within fluids and structures.

The aim of the course is to make students reflect on the specific scientific and methodological foundations of computer science, on the peculiarities as a discipline compared to other scientific disciplines, and on the specific aspects of its teaching. The course builds on these foundations and provides useful techniques and tools for teaching computer science, with a particular emphasis on high school level.

At the end of the course, the student:
- knows the historical and epistemological roots of computer science and the motivations underlying the need for its teaching;
- knows the national indications and curricula relating to computer science in schools at all levels;
- knows the multiple didactic approaches specific to the subject;
- knows the main cognitive difficulties that computer science learning poses (with particular reference to programming), and what are the possible strategies to adopt to overcome them;
- understands the pedagogical aspects and learning theories in the context of computer science teaching;
- is able to analyze computer science concepts from an educational viewpoint;
- is able to design simple learning units to introduce computing and programming concepts, scheduling its content in a suitable order;
- is able to present a computing concept in a suitable form for learning purposes;
- is able to perform a literature survey on computing education research.

This course aims to provide students with an advanced understanding of concepts and theories of International Relations and European politics. It offers an extended selection of lexis, categories and resources in order to problematize European and world politics according to a plurality of approaches. After having reviewed the main “languages” of International Relations and European politics, the course will turn towards emerging trends and debates in the fields, as well as alternative perspectives through which global, international, European and transnational politics can be interpreted. Furthermore, the students will be encouraged to critically think about what these approaches tell us about specific problems and issues.

By the end of the course students will be able to:
- navigate with ease across different authors and strands of literature featuring the fields of International Relations and European Studies;
- read and understand original texts and sources relevant to the fields, as well as explain in their own words the meanings of labels and concepts used in International Relations and European politics;
- unpack the complexity of European and international politics, identifying the different actors involved, their capabilities, interests, normative inclinations and positioning;
- demonstrate a deep understanding of actual debates about multifaceted policy issues and political matters unfolding in Europe and worldwide; 
 - conduct independent analyses of issues in international and European politics, linking theories and empirical evidence, and presenting the results of the analyses in an effective way.

The course provides the theoretical and analytical instruments to understand development cooperation dynamics. It addresses the following questions: Why do states invest in development cooperation? How do economic and geostrategic interests, domestic and international institutions, ideas and conceptions of development affect development cooperation? What is the contribution of NGOs and enterprises?
The course addresses these questions with the lenses of theories of International Development and International Relations and uses a case studies approach.
After the course, students will be able to:
•	Understand decision-making processes concerning development cooperation;
•	Develop a critical approach to potentialities and challenges of development cooperation;
•	Apply theoretical concepts and theories to case studies.

The course introduces Spanish culture and literature during the Golden Age through novel and short stories study. The student will acquire the tools to read original texts through historical, linguistic and literary contextualization.
At the end of the course the students
- will know the main historical, cultural and religious characteristics of Spain, with particular reference to the early modern age;
- will know the main theories about the structure of the classic novel and the basic notions of narratology;
- will have learned to recognize the lexicon and style of peculiar genres of the Golden Age novel;
- will have basic knowledge of legal and bibliographical aspects related to the production of the ancient book

The course LIFE AND SIGNS: PROBLEMS AND AUTHORS OF SEMIOTICS AND BIOSEMIOTICS aims to introduce to selected problems, authors and written works that exemplify the researches in semiotics and biosemiotics, fields of studies which take into account the modellization of information and the natural and cultural manifestations of life. The course focuses on: (a) the structuralist approach in linguistics; (b) the ecological advancements in theoretical biology; (c) evolutionism as complexity theory. The main idea of the course is that the living beings are not passive in front of thier enviroment but rather active agents capable of produce, mediate and interpretate the signs. In particular, at the end of the course the students will be able to:
1) present/ argue the main concepts and keywords of semiotics and biosemiotics research trends;
2) analyze and present the contribution of the leader authors involved;
3) make connections between different thesis debated and the main theorical options offered;
4)  autonomously evaluate cases of study;
5) offer personal comments on the issues discussed.

AIMS: The teaching aims to provide the learner with some advanced notions of computational mechanics.
The course of Computational Mechanics of Structures II is designed to provide students with basics to address the numerical analysis of structural and field problems with nonlinear behavior and referring to complex structures and issues; the course will analyze with numerical techniques some topics related to the continuum mechanics (plates and shells), civil engineering (numerical calculation of concrete structures and structures of composite laminates), and physics in general (and thermal and thermo-elastic problems).
As experimental science stands out for having a set of rules that allow the experimental approach to be rigorous and now universally recognized as a method for understanding natural phenomena useful and in some cases irreplaceable; Computational science is also based on a set of rules and axioms that ensure that it is not only a way of understanding the etiological joints that govern some natural phenomena, but also an irreplaceable instrument to build reproducible patterns that allow, once analyzed The phenomenon from the point of view of the fundamental laws that describe it, to generate a series of repeated analyzes to ascertain possible scenarios to vary the data describing the problem being analyzed. A computational model is for this reason not only a virtual reproduction of a natural phenomena that is to be analyzed but also an experimental laboratory where to analyze the effects produced by the mutation on the built model of some causes or structural parameter of the model (material, boundary conditions, geometry fo structures, etc.). The primary objective of the course is to provide the student with the knowledge of the enormous possibilities offered by the computational sceince and at the same time to develop a critical capacity that must enable the engineer to conceive, construct and interpret any computational model.
LEARNING OUTCOMES:  the course will allow students to
•	to recognize the equations of physics that constitute the basic mathematical model of the most important problems of civil engineering and mechanical engineering; 
•	formulate a problem of the physical mathematics with the variational formulation and/or weak formulations;
•	know the basic steps needed to create a discretized model starting with a weak form of the physical problem;
•	interpret and evaluate the results provided by a computational modeling;
•	know and exploit to deal with the effects of nonlinearity in mechanical structure problems;
•	use computational tools as tools for designing and optimizing structures.

This course aims to provide students with an opportunity for engaging in critical evaluation of different theoretical models of developmental psychology. Psychological development is considered as a complex and multidimensional process that affects the entire life cycle. Each phase of the life cycle presents new challenges to which a person, based on his/her own resources, can respond positively or negatively. We will also deal with functional and dysfunctional ways of facing the new evolutionary tasks that characterize the entire span of life, also addressing psychological disorders from an evolutionary psychopathology perspective. 

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
a.	understand the theories and methodologies of developmental psychology;
b.	develop critical skills and communicate clearly the acquired knowledge; 
c.	elaborate independently the acquired knowledge and relate what they have learned with other disciplines and to self-study also research areas of personal interest.

Deepening the understanding of the functioning of markets and of the determinants and effectiveness of firms' strategies, through the analysis of a specific market with appropriate data.
Specific skills to be acquired include:
- applying theoretical concepts learnt in other courses to the analysis of a market and an enterprise; 
- identifying the most appropriate data to describe a phenomenon of interest (e.g. the evolution of a specific market and its main determinants);
- ability to work with data in order to extract relevant information;
- organizing and discussing the results of the analysis and drafting a research report; 
- team work; 
- presenting the results to an audience.

The course aims to introduce students to the study of the several legal issues involved in the management of data, by critically analysing a selection of topics characterizing this area. At the end of the course, students will be able:
- to familiarise with the basic concepts of the legal issues involved in Data science;
- to be able to critically analyse such issues;
- to learn how to manage a data science scenario from a legal point of view;
- to complete their data scientist profile with the necessary legal knowledges.

La classicità grego-romana e la vicenda storica in cui si è sviluppata rappresentano una delle matrici culturali essenziali della storia europea. Nel dibattito pubblico di ieri e oggi, tuttavia, la complessità dell'esperienza antica risulta spesso appiattita sul presente e piegata alle sue esigenze, offrendo il fianco a derive nazionaliste, a costruzioni identitarie o pseudo-identitarie, a strumentalizzazioni ideologiche esito di una sostanziale disattenzione per la metodologia indispensabile a una corretta ricostruzione del passato. Proprio gli aspetti metodologici trasversali a tutte le discipline storiche (L-ANT/02 Storia Greca; L-ANT/03 Storia Romana; M-STO/01 Storia Medievale; M-STO/02 Storia Moderna; M-STO/04 Storia Contemporanea) costituiranno il focus precipuo del corso: dopo alcune lezioni di carattere introduttivo dedicate allo spazio riservato all'insegnamento della storia nella scuola italiana, all'analisi delle principali metodologie didattiche e alla presentazione delle risorse utili all'insegnamento della disciplina, il corso si concentrerà sul dema dell'uso pubblico della storia (Public History), affrontando in particolare alcuni casi di studio paradigmatici.
L'obiettivo formativo del corso, caratterizzato da una spiccata vocazione multidisciplinare e rivolto in primis a formatrici e formatori della scuola secondaria, è quello di dotare i futuri e le future docenti di storia, chiamati/e a svolgere un ruolo civile e sociale di importanza cruciale, di strumenti teorici e metodologici idonei a rispondere alle sfide educative del mondo contemporaneo, nonchè di spunti tematici utli nella progettazione didattica, implementando la coscienza del loro ruolo professionale.
Al termine del corso ci si attende che studenti e studentesse:
1. abbiano familiarità con le principali metodologie e risorse utili nella didattica della storia e le sappiano utilizzare in modo critico;
2. sappiano orientarsi nel dibattito teorico sulla Pubblic History e impiegare alcune sue applicazioni a scopi didattici;
3. siano in grado di articolare proposte didattiche inclusive, innovative, scientificamente rigorose, capaci di stimolare la riflessione critica e le competenze di cittadinanza di studenti e studentesse;
4. dimostrino un'adeguata consapevolezza metodologica e un'affinata competenza professionale.

The course offers an introduction to the basics of climate change, which is arguably one of the greatest challenges that our society is presently facing. Indeed, while Earth’s climate does, and did change in the past, due to natural variability, there is now a wealth of scientifically based evidence that anthropogenic activities are causing the planet to warm globally at an unprecedented rate, with a series of consequences for the whole earth system (e. g. the hydrological cycle, the ocean circulations, the ecosystems, and the whole living environment).
In this course, we will address the following questions: How does the climate system work? What do we know about changes occurred in the past, and mechanisms behind those change? How can we understand how climate will change in the future? What is the scientific basis of future climate projections? And what are the associated uncertainties? How can we assess the impact of climate-change mitigation policies at the global scale?

By the end of this course, students will:
•	Develop a scientific understanding of how the climate system changes naturally and in response to an external perturbation;
•	Articulate how the climate system has changed in the deep and recent past, and how science gets evidence of that;
•	Understand the drivers of these changes;
•	Become familiar with methods of climate data collection and the basics of climate modeling;
•	Understand the basis and uncertainties of climate projections;
•	Learn about the role of international bodies in providing regular scientific assessments of the state of the climate to policy- and decision-makers.

The course shall provide the fundamental notions of European Union Law and its interaction with the legal systems of its Member States.
After successful completion of the course students be able to:
• Give an account of the evolution of the European integration process and its main phases;
• Identify the objectives and the fundamental principles and to describe the attribution of competences between EU and Member States;
• Illustrate the structure of the EU’s form of government;
• Give an account of the EU’s main decision-making procedures;
• Define the sources of EU Law and illustrate their operation (direct effect, supremacy);
• Give an account of the judicial system of the EU and understand the functioning of the system of judicial action at the suprantional level;
• Give an account of the system of protection of fundamental rights in the EU;
• Give an account of the main strategies of regulation of the Internal Market (negative and positive harmonsation) and illustrate the main cases regarding the fundamental economic freedoms;
• Give an account of the principles in case-law and of the constitutional and legislative basis regarding the relations between EU Law and the constitutional law of Member States (in particular Italy).
• Analyze the most significant novelties introduced after the outbreak of the Covid-19 crisis, their impact on the EU institutional framework, the relationship between the EU and the member States, and more generally on the European integration process.

The course aims at:
