- capability of modelling and designing of steel frames;
- capability of designing steel-concrete composite beams;
- knowledge of the  basics of the structural fire design of steel structures;
- autonomy in identifying and solving structural design problems and in proposing constructional solutions;
- ability of reporting clearly and effectively the design results by means of suitable tools.

The course will provide students with the basic notions of Theoretical and Computational Linguistics.
By the end of the course the students are expected to:
- recognize different linguistic processes;
- understand the theoretical frame of some linguistic theories;
- analyze the syntactic structure of sentences and the morphological and phonological structure of words;
- classify and interpret forms of fiction and generate brief texts;
- apply statistics in linguistic research.

Part one (September-December 2021)
The course aims to provide students with a B1/a (CEFR) level in all four skills - speaking, listening, reading, and writing. By the of the course students will be able to:
1) communicate with suitable accuracy in simple routine situations;
2) understand spoken interaction in everyday contexts;
3) use grammatically accurate structures in predictable formats;
4) interact in appropriate social linguistic style;
5) read high-frequency everyday information.   

Part two (Jan-Feb 2022 intensive)
The course aims to provide guidance to achieving a B1/b level (according to the European Framework of Reference) in all 4 skills. By the end of this course, students are expected to be able to:
1) understand straightforward factual information about common everyday or job-related topics, identifying both general messages and specific details. In addition, the students will be able to understand the main points of clear standard speech on familiar matters.
2) read straightforward factual texts on subjects related to his/her field and interest with a satisfactory level of comprehension, understanding paraphrase, and differentiating between fact and opinion.
3)  communicate with some confidence familiar routine and non-routine matters related to his/her interests and professional field. The students will be able to take part in a dialogue in order to solve a problem, exchanging, checking, and confirming information.
4) successfully convey written information about practical and abstract topics, showing their ability to express and resolve daily issues with reasonable precision. In addition, the student will be able to engage in personal correspondence and write notes.

Within this course, we will provide the fundamentals for the informed use of analytical methodologies to characterize and date materials in the field of cultural heritage. 
We will discuss the methodological aspects of the scientific method, the principles of the measurement theory and we will provide an introduction to the main concepts in the physical and chemical description of matter. Finally, we will give an overview of some experimental techniques.
By the end of this course, the student will be able to:
- understand the role of an analytical approach in the field of cultural heritage;
- design and carry out analysis on relevant specimens with some techniques;
- understand and discuss the results of the measurements.

The module aims at providing basic knowledge on geology and geomorphology, with particular attention to the processes that modify the landscape at different spatial and temporal scale.
At the end of the module students will be able to:
- classify the main physical processes shaping the Earth’s surface;
- use the correct technical geological terminology;
- read and interpret a geological map;
- recognize the effects of different geological and geomorphological processes on the landscape.

The aim of the course is to provide the students with the basic concepts for the understanding of the structural and functional organization of prokaryotic cells and viruses, as well as their main biotechnological applications.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
-Understand fundamental concepts of microbiology;
-Describe prokaryotic and viral structures and how they relate to cell functionalities and to the interaction with other organisms and the environment;
-Describe metabolic diversity of prokaryotes and how these organisms derive energy, electrons, and carbon from their environment;
-Describe basic genetic mechanisms of microbes with specific reference to horizontal gene transfer;
-Describe the basis of pathogenicity mechanisms of microbes;
-Discuss the main options for the control of microbial growth in vitro and in vivo;
-Prepare and recognize microscopic preparations, culture plates and growth media; 
-Identify, enumerate and transform bacterial cells;
-Evaluate potential benefits and detriments caused by microorganisms;
-Retain and apply specialized language relevant to microbiology.

In the first year the goal of the social work internship is to make it clear to the trainee through a mainly observational experience the organization of the help, the actors and their roles, and what the role the professional social worker could be.
This course will enable students to develop a reflective approach to the profession through which enter the labor world in a more active and creative way.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
- know the main characteristics of the scientific method as a means of acquiring information in social work;
- identify the main social research strategies;
- design and develop in the field the main operational phases of social research;
- apply the main tools of qualitative research;
- understand and use social mapping as a tool for analysis and evaluation in the social service.

The course aims to teach students the clinical path and associated methodologies that accompany an oncologic patient from cancer diagnosis to the choice of the most appropriate therapy. In detail, the course describes different methods of bioptic sampling and processing, diagnostic criteria of tumor staging, surgery and pharmacological strategies for the treatment of specific types of solid cancer. Particular attention will be dedicated to technological innovations in the field of tumor diagnosis, in vivo imaging and radiology, as well as to dissecting the difference between classical chemotherapeutic drugs and innovative “target” therapies.
At the end of the course students will be able to:
-	Define different clinical approaches adopted for the diagnosis and treatment of specific forms of tumor;
-	Compare pros and cons of different clinical strategies; 
-	Classify a pathologic condition in low, medium, and high risk categories and propose a clinical approach and predict possible outcomes;
-	Examine and estimate tumor response to a specific therapy;
Integrate clinical information with genetic data in order to design targeted treatments.

The course has three educational goals:
1)	have a good knowledge of the main characteristics and problems of the Italian and European labour market;
2)	understand the mechanisms underpinning the labour supply decisions of individuals and families, as well as some related choices (education and fertility);
3)	learn to analyse the functioning of the labour market and to evaluate the possible consequences of labour market institutions and policies, as well as of information asymmetries, on employment, wages, payment schemes and gender differences. 
The course for Economics and Management has also the additional aim to deepen the knowledge of the Italian and European labour market (mainly through empirical evidence).

The aim of the course it to provide students with the basic analytical tools needed to understand the logic of organizational structure and design.
By the end of the course, the student will be able to:
1)	Understand the concept of division of labor and its organizational consequences in terms of task, job and role design;
2)	Recognize and interpret  the links between types of technology, ways of grouping transformation activities and tasks, interdependencies and modes of coordination;
3)	Know and apply the different modes of organizational assessment;
4)	Understand the reasons for individual participation to organizational activities.

The course aims to introduce students to a specific topic about the Middle Ages, to show them a research method and to provide them with skills to carry out individual research on Middle Age history.
At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
(a) report the main contents of the course, using an appropriate vocabulary;
(b) expose methods that have been used in the research path to reach determined conclusions;
(c) analyse a historical source about the subjects covered in the teaching describing the features and articulations of its form and content
(d) judge the results of the research critically, hypothesising different solutions or proposing further research.

In the framework of the integro-differential calculus for multivariable functions, and referring to the programme for a more detailed description of the course content, at the end of the course the student should:

- know and be able to apply the basic concepts of the differential calculus for vector-valued functions of several variables, with a specific focus on the dimensions 2 and 3, and to master its specific language. In particular, the student should be able to precisely state all the theorems and the definitions of the course programme;

- be able to illustrate theorems and definitions, also making use of examples (in particular of those proposed during the classes);

- be able to graphically illustrate the mathematical objects of the course, such as surfaces, solid figures, and vector fields;

- master the calculus techniques and argue properly;

- be able to solve problems similar to those proposed during the classes, and to derive new interesting pieces of information starting from those already developed;

- be able to prove a selection of the proposed theorems.

Objectives
The course provides a wide (albeit not always in-depth) overview of methodologies and algorithms used by a "Data scientist". This professional profile, increasingly demanded by all sorts of business, is usually tasked with extracting useful information and models out of raw data (such as those available to a company, collected during a scientific experiment, or fetched from a social network by web scraping), with the goal of obtaining knowledge and predictive capabilities, or to improve a productive process via the simulation of alternative scenarios.
After following the course, the students will be able to:
- read, preprocess and normalize data in various formats; identify the different types of data appearing in a file, manually and programmatically filter out unimportant data;
- apply rigorous methodologies to choose the most suitable machine learning algorithms for every context, evaluate their performance, to configure and execute them;
- generate a data model using a machine learning algorithm, perform analysis and predictions avoiding the several interpretation and usage errors they are prone to;
- visually represent the information obtained from data analysis;
- organize the above steps in a pipeline to automate, as much as possible, the process leading from raw data to analysis results.

	The course aims to introduce students to the understanding of the historical events that have led to the formation of the state in the modern West, in its multiple dimensions. The expected learning outcomes consist of:
- the acquisition of the basic notions and method of the history of political institutions;
- the awareness of the role and functions of political institutions in history, with special reference to the genesis of State;
- the knowledge of the diachronic and problematic picture of the topic dealt with, also with reference to historiographic interpretations;
- the ability to use the comparison tool to understand the different structures of government, the organization and the functioning of the analyzed state formations.

The course provides guidance on the analysis of the legal dimension of food security from a global perspective. It describes food security as a complex, global and systemic challenge and focuses on the understanding of the global food governance narrative. It addresses the urgency to achieve sustainable food security in the face of climate challenges and resource scarcity. It stresses the need to embrace a comprehensive and holistic approach that looks at the food system in its entirety.

By the end of this course students will be able to:
- define food security as a broad concept and interpret the most used food security conceptual frameworks;
- understand the complexity of food security;
- appreciate the links between food security and food safety;
- appreciate the content of the human right to food and its relationship with the food security concept; 
- be aware of the landscape in which international policies for the food sector operate;
- handle the main legal aspects of the global food system and their impact on food security worldwide;
- identify options for how policies can respond to new challenges that have an impact on food security such as climate change.

The recent advances in Neuroscience raise a number of important ethical issues. The aim of the course is that of presenting students with some of these issues, with a special emphasis on their potential impact on both the individual and society.

In particular, by the end of the course students should 

a) be more aware of the complex relation between neuroscience and society;
b) be able to connect previous knowledge from other courses with the relevant ethical issues presented;
c) be able to detect potentially critical aspects in neuroscientific research, its applications and its dissemination;
d) be able to critically discuss the ethical issues raised, both with specialists in the field and the lay public;
e) have improved transversal competencies related to team work, retrieving relevant material from different sources, and presenting in front of a group.

The course provides the basic knowledge concerning the functions, structure and techniques of protection of fundamental rights in the constitutional state. These topics are mainly explored in the context of the Italian constitutional legal order, although insights are also offered with regard to foreign, international and supranational experiences of fundamental rights adjudication. Teaching blends theoretical insights with critical investigation of constitutional case law.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to: 

•	Identify the main features of the most important historical manifestations of constitutionalism;
•	Define the functions and structure of fundamental rights in the constitutional state;
•	Critically discuss the classifications of fundamental rights with a view of theoretical debates concerning their nature;
•	Reconstruct the genesis and evolution of the systems of judicial review of legislation;
•	Recognise the forms of organization of judicial review of legislation and discuss their advantages and disadvantages;
•	Reflect critically on the problems concerning the legitimacy of judicial review of legislation;
•	Identify and employ the main techniques of constitutional adjudication;
•	Reconstruct and assess the distinctive characteristics of fundamental rights protection in the European Union;
•	Reconstruct and assess the distinctive characteristics of fundamental rights protection in the European Convention of Human Rights;
•	Reconstruct and assess the interactions between different systems of protection of fundamental rights in Europe.

The course aims to provide students with a comprehensive knowledge of the European and comparative regulatory framework in some crucial areas at the intersection between law and science. It uses a case-study methodology, to analyse the interaction between law and science. Some basic issue will be explored, such as equality, solidarity, liberty, accountability and &#34;new frontiers&#34;.  We will higlight similarities and differences among the States and at European level. Students will have to make an oral presentation discussing a case.  
At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- know the legal regulation of some biolaw issues;
- understand decision-making process at national, European, and supranational level, when regulating biolaw topics;
- analyse biolaw cases, in the light of the fundamental rights involved;
- analyze the interaction between science, law and ethics from a comparative and European perspective;
- use a comparative and interdisciplinary methodology in the field of biolaw:
- make a presentation and participate in the discussion of cases;
- understand and analyze interdisciplinary topics.

The course is divided in two partitions:
- Innovation and Entrepreneurship Basics --> For EIT Digital, AI and Innovation and ICT Innovation students
- Innovation and Business in ICT --> For Computer Science and Information and Communication/Telecommunications Engineering Master's

-----

Innovation and Entrepreneurship Basics: 


The course introduces students to the field of Innovation and Entrepreneurship (I&E) as a theory and as a practice, contextualising it in the field of ICT. The goal of the course is to give students strong fundamentals in the field of I&E, acquire a broader perspective of their main field of study, and help them develop “soft skills” such as leadership, critical thinking, and creativity.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- Outline key I&E concepts such as Digital Transformation, and discuss how they relate to current socio-technical phenomena;
- Critically assess technologies not just technically, but also with respect to their social and policy impacts;
- Create rough drafts of sustainable business models starting from an idea and/or product;
- Discuss the role of entrepreneurship in society from an economic and social perspective;
- Outline a few archetypical models of organisations and how they function;
- Discuss how technologies can become sources of disruption for contemporary society;
- Present and defend their ideas in public;
- Discuss ethical implications of innovations, business models and technologies;
- Identify and discuss technological macro-trends and contextualise them in the I&E field;
- Positively work in a group setting, managing deadlines and internal group dynamics.

-----

Innovation and Business in ICT:

The objective of this course is to develop theoretical and practical understanding of the innovation and entrepreneurial processes from idea generation to exploitation. It is aimed at students who want to enhance their entrepreneurial and innovation skills, or take an entrepreneurial role by setting up their new ventures or by developing innovative ideas in existing companies. This course will help students develop both hard skills (e.g. business modelling, entrepreneurial finance) and soft skills (e.g. empathy, creative thinking, storytelling). 

At the end of the course, students will be able to:

- Understand the stages/phases of the entrepreneurial and innovation processes from the initial perception of an innovative idea to its realisation in a market or social context
- Identify and evaluate entrepreneurial and innovation opportunities
- Reflect on the skills and behaviours of entrepreneurs and innovators
- Reflect on the challenges entrepreneurs and innovators face, and the resources and skills they need to draw upon, when developing new ideas in uncertain environments
- Critically assess the merits of alternative models and strategies for innovation that entrepreneurs can adopt to benefit from the value of new ideas
- Exhibit enhanced skills in terms of critical thinking, systems thinking, information synthesis, and creativity

The objective of the course is to introduce into the “Law of Diversity” and its elements and instruments by illustrating and discussing the role and potential of law, and in particular of Human and Minority  Rights, as a means of regulation and stabilization, especially after ethnic conflict.
In particular, students who have passed the exam shall be able to:
-	give an account of the debate regarding the definition of “minority” and to delimit it from other groups (such as migrants, indigenous peoples, etc.);
-	give an account of the historical evolution in Europe, leading to the Nation-State, and to the consequent marginalization of minority groups;
-	illustrate the different constitutional approaches regarding the phenomenon of diversity;
-	explain the fundamental rights, procedures and institutional solutions of minority-proection regarding linguistic, political and religious rights, including power-sharing and affirmative action.

The course will provide a qualitative and quantitative description of the production of mechanical movement in the industrial sector, through the application of incompressible fluids (oleo-hydraulics). It will introduce the transmission of movement through compressible fluids (pneumatics).
The core competencies for the analysis and design of industrial components and systems will be acquired.

EXPECTED LEARNING OUTCOMES:
By the end of the course, the students will have reached the following:
awareness of the base sector standards (ISO) and apply them in the analysis and design of simple systems;
to deconstruct circuits of industrial application, identifying the components and analyzing the function qualitatively and quantitatively;
to interpret the structure and describe qualitatively, quantitatively, and according to the standard the main components available in the industrial sector;
the ability to analyze a component and/or an industrial system to represent it in a lumped parameter modeling software, and verify the correct behaviour;
on the base of an agreed application, design and simulate an industrial movement system.

The objective of the English Test at B2 level is to measure a candidate's linguistic competences in listening, reading, writing and speaking according to the B2 competence descriptors in the CEFR (The Common European Framework of Reference for Languages). 

The tests require candidates to demonstrate their competence in English in a range of academic, personal and professional contexts. The result of the test is PASS or FAIL. The result conveys whether or not a candidate would be able to cope with a reasonable degree of autonomy in an English-medium academic / familiar professional context. 

By passing the English test at B2, candidates demonstrate the following competences:

For listening:
Ability to:
-	understand the main ideas of complex text on both concrete and abstract topics, including technical discussions in his/her field of specialisation;
-	standard spoken language, live or broadcast, on both familiar and unfamiliar topics normally encountered in personal, social, academic or vocational life;
-	the main ideas of propositionally and linguistically complex speech on both concrete and abstract topics delivered in a standard dialect, including technical discussions in his/her field of specialisation;
-	to follow extended speech and complex lines of argument provided the topic is reasonably familiar, and the direction of the talk is sign-posted by explicit markers;
-	to follow the essentials of lectures, talks and reports and other forms of academic/professional presentation, which are propositionally and linguistically complex.

For reading:
Ability to:
-	read with a large degree of independence, adapting style and speed of reading to different texts and purposes. Has a broad active reading vocabulary;
-	to scan quickly through long and complex texts, locating relevant details;
-	to obtain information, ideas and opinions from highly specialised sources within his/her field;
-	to understand specialised articles outside his/her field, provided technical or specialised terms are glossed in tests if they are beyond what can be reasonably be comprehended by a B2 level candidate.

For writing:
Ability to write clear, detailed texts on a variety of subjects related to his/her field of interest, synthesising and evaluating information and arguments from a number of sources. Generally high lexical accuracy. Relatively high degree of grammatical control. Does not make mistakes which lead to misunderstanding.

For speaking:
Ability:
-	to give clear, detailed descriptions and presentations on a wide range of subjects related to his/her field of interest, expanding and supporting ideas with subsidiary points and relevant examples;
-	to communicate complex information on the full range of matters related to his/her occupational role;
-	to give a clear, detailed description of how to carry out a procedure;
-	to give a clear, systematically developed presentation, with highlighting of significant points, and relevant supporting detail;
-	to depart spontaneously from a prepared speech and follow up interesting points raised by members of the audience, often showing remarkable fluency and ease of expression.

This course addresses with a phenomenological and experimental approach the emerging fields of 
a)	gravitational wave astronomy and related experimental tests on the nature of gravity and space-time;
b)	multimessenger observations of astrophysical phenomena, in particular exploiting gravitational waves, neutrinos and electromagnetic radiation.

This course aims to provide students with an opportunity for engaging in critical evaluation of different theoretical models of developmental psychology. Psychological development is considered as a complex and multidimensional process that affects the entire life cycle. Each phase of the life cycle presents new challenges to which a person, based on his/her own resources, can respond positively or negatively. We will also deal with functional and dysfunctional ways of facing the new evolutionary tasks that characterize the entire span of life, also addressing psychological disorders from an evolutionary psychopathology perspective. 

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
a.	understand the theories and methodologies of developmental psychology;
b.	develop critical skills and communicate clearly the acquired knowledge; 
c.	elaborate independently the acquired knowledge and relate what they have learned with other disciplines and to self-study also research areas of personal interest.

The Course aims at giving the students a basic knowledge of ethical and legal principles in AI. We will analyse existing principles and ask ourselves whether they may be suitable to regulate AI or whether it is necessary to develop new ones. 
At the end of the course, students will have legal and interdisciplinary skills that can guide them in carrying out their professional activity in a constitution-oriented and human-centered way. 
In particular, the student will:
- Know the main ethical and legal principles of AI;
- Use the acquired skills to analyse and understand the ethical dilemmas and legal problems related to the use of AI; 
- Know the main legal sources of AI in some relevant areas, such as autonomous vehicles, medicine or justice;
- Be aware of the potential and risks of an increasingly widespread and autonomous use of AI;
- Understand the importance of a plural debate and interdisciplinary approach in the study of AI
- Be able to participate actively in working groups and discussions on law and ethics of AI.

The course is thought as a part of the distinctive preparation of those students who are enrolled in the  " Etica, politica e scienze delle religioni" curriculum.
The aim of course “FILOSOFIA DELLA RELIGIONE”, part of first year of the three-year degree in Philosophy, is - first of all - to make students capable of understanding  the specific issues of the religious phenomenon, both from an anthropological and a social perspective, beyond the diversity of religious beliefs. Secondly, to provide tools to interpret religion in a conscious manner and to evaluate its potential factors of crisis and the relative implications, such as atheism and religious conflict.
At the end of the course “FILOSOFIA DELLA RELIGIONE”, the students will acquire a number of notions and categories thanks to which they will be able to:
A) define the specific differences among this discipline and theologies or other religion-related knowledges;
B) place the discipline, both historically and systematically, within the context of philosophical reflection as a whole;
C) be able to interpret, within modern or contemporary thought, the problematic confrontation of the religious reflection with the changes of the anthropological paradigm caused by the impact of natural sciences, the transformations of psychological experiences, the needs of redefining personal identity;
D) be able to read and interpret independently the classical texts;
E) identify and contextualize the key terms and the main concepts regarding the authors and texts studied during the course.

The aim of the course is to make students reflect on the specific scientific and methodological foundations of computer science, on the peculiarities as a discipline compared to other scientific disciplines, and on the specific aspects of its teaching. The course builds on these foundations and provides useful techniques and tools for teaching computer science, with a particular emphasis on high school level.

At the end of the course, the student:
- knows the historical and epistemological roots of computer science and the motivations underlying the need for its teaching;
- knows the national indications and curricula relating to computer science in schools at all levels;
- knows the multiple didactic approaches specific to the subject;
- knows the main cognitive difficulties that computer science learning poses (with particular reference to programming), and what are the possible strategies to adopt to overcome them;
- understands the pedagogical aspects and learning theories in the context of computer science teaching;
- is able to analyze computer science concepts from an educational viewpoint;
- is able to design simple learning units to introduce computing and programming concepts, scheduling its content in a suitable order;
- is able to present a computing concept in a suitable form for learning purposes;
- is able to perform a literature survey on computing education research.

acquisition of a basic knowledge concerning the literary history, the story of literary and cultural historiography in the german area and the basis of textual analysis.
At the end of the activity the student:
a. will know in general the development of the german literature from the origins to our time;
b he will know in particular the literature of the Goethezeit and the work of the young Goethe;
c. he will recognize and describe forms and peculiarities of a literary text;
d. he will be able to analyze from a semantic, an historical a representative work of the german literature of the 18th century.

The course aims at giving the student a deeper understanding of the fundamental principles of fiscal law, starting with statutory reserve and contribution capacity and concluding with a study of tax implementation mechanisms. The course also gives an overview of the operative taxation system focusing on income tax and value-added tax.
At the end of the course, student will be able:
1) to know and to understand the taxation law sources relating to the law system in the national context;
2) to know the fundamental principles of the Italian Constitution relating to the Italian tax system;
3) to know taxable persons, tax obligation and tax return, tax investigation, tax assessment, collection and refund;
4) to achieve a good level of knowledge in individual income tax law, in enterprise tax law and in corporation tax law;
5) to analyze and to make critical evaluation of corporate processes and dynamics with respect to taxation law;
6) to acquire the ability to illustrate the main issues of the course using the appropriated legal lexicon;
7) to learn and to apply the links between the different legal matters;
8) to analyze case studies emerging in practice and to apply the appropriate fiscal rules of the national legal system.

The course is thought as a part of the distinctive preparation of those students who are enrolled in the  " Etica, politica e scienze delle religioni" curriculum.
The aim of course "FILOSOFIA DELLA RELIGIONE", part of first year of master program "Filosofia e linguaggi della modernità", is – first of all – to make students capable of mastering the specific issues of religious phenomenon, that will be explored from anthropological and social point of views, beyond the specific diversity of religious beliefs. Secondly, the course aims to lead students – by deepening an important topic/author of philosophy of religion – to understand the dialectic relation between the religious phenomenon and the theoretical problems that concerns it.
At the end of the course students will know a series of terms, concepts and categories, thanks to which they will be able to:
a) identify and contextualize, with an accurate theoretical approach, the key terms and the main concepts examined during the course (with the help of authors and texts);
b) understand and interpret, in detail, topics and authors examined during the course (with the help of some classical works);
c) expose the results of a personal research on the authors and the subjects of the course.

Wooden Architecture is a specialist course of the fifth year of the Five-year Masters course Architecture and Building Engineering.
The aim of the course is to improve the student competences for designing sustainable wooden buildings in balance with the environment and with a low impact on the environmental matrices: air, water and soil.
The lectures and the design activities will be focused on the use of wood, a natural material, for build sustainable edifices. At same time, to improve the sustainability of the buildings, there will be introduced the main concepts related to:
	use of recyclable and/or recycled materials;
	exploitation of the energetic free contributions from the surrounding;
	use of systems for the energy production from renewable sources;
	optimization of the buildings energy consumption through the building automation.
The focus of the year work will be the design of a social or residential building. It will be defined at beginning of the semester.
With the above-mentioned background, the students will develop, at home and during the workshop activities, a project of a sustainable residential or public building in wood whose typological characteristics will be settled at beginning of the semester.

Aim of the module is the acquisition of knowledge and skills for environmental management of companies and public and private organizations, with particular attention to those in the tourism sector.
Attendance and active participation at three training activities offered by the course (lectures, seminars, multi-disciplinary laboratory) and self-study will enable students to:
know the environmental problems related to economic development;
include environmental issues into economic decisions and corporate strategy;
apply the Environmental Management Systems;  
apply LCA tools to
evaluate the environmental impacts of a product/service;
develop and carry out  a lifecycle study of a tourist service.
Regarding soft skills, active participation in all the proposed training activities make students able to organize a teamwork, apply problem solving techniques and presenting results by properly arguing.

The course aims to provide a comprehensive, but detailed view of the cellular and molecular complexity of the nervous system. Particular emphasis will be given to morphological characteristics and genetic mechanisms that characterize the properties of neurons and to the interneuronal communication systems underlying synaptic transmission.
By the end of the course, the students will be able to:
1. Carefully and comprehensively define the cellular and molecular complexity of central nervous system (Remember), comparing and discussing different cell types of the brain based on their morphological and functional characteristics (Understand-Analyzing);
2. Examine the molecular mechanisms responsible for neuronal properties such as neuronal transport, active and passive electrical properties (Analyzing);
3. Classify basic characteristics interneuronal communication and synaptic transmission, discriminating different chemical and electrical neuron-to-neuron communication systems (electrical and chemical synapses, different neurotransmitters and their receptors) (understand, analyze);
4. Explain and discuss the cellular and molecular basis of neuron-glia metabolic unit (neuron – astrocytes – capillaries, glycolysis versus oxidative phosphorylation) (understand, analyze).

The goals of this course are to introduce students to the main principles of calculus and to get them to acquire confidence in the application of the mathematical concepts learned. At the end of the course students will have a good understanding of the concepts of function, of limit and of differential calculus of a real variable function, and their application to concrete problems.

Specifically, the main concepts that students will master by the end of the course will be:

• the concepts of vector and matrix of real variables, and operations defined on them;

• basic knowledge about systems of linear equations and their solutions;

• knowledge of the concept of function and of the calculation of  limits together with the basic notions of graph of a function;

• knowledge of the concept of differentiable functions and of all the notions that allow the student to perform a study of the graph of a function;

• knowledge of the concept of integral of a function, and main results related to integral calculus;

At the end of the course, the main skills acquired will be:

• Ability to carry out operations on vectors and matrices, limits, and to compute derivatives and integrals of functions;

• Ability to identify the methods for solving the calculus-related problem at hand.

The main purpose of the District Heating System Design course is the analysis of multiple aspects related to the evaluations of this approach widely adopted to provide heat including, as specific topic, the design procedures. All these issues have to be considered to achieve the technical/economic feasibility for the realization of a District Heating System. They can be summarized in the following 4 macro areas:
- assessment of the thermal needs of the district as a set of different utilities;
- analysis of thermal energy production systems;
- analysis and design methodologies;
- economic evaluations and profitability of the DH project.
The expected results consist in the student's ability to develop a technical / scientific vision of the problems with respect to different options that have to be considered (location, energy generation, costs of the system). An evaluation of the use of renewable energy in district heating systems is also required.

The course, which is entirely taught in English, aims at introducing the students to the foundational concepts of private law as established in western legal tradition and, where applicable, in the E.U. and international legal landscape. Although private law is still fragmented both at national and supranational levels, concepts and principles show often common roots and, when not so, they show a distinctive aptness to respond to similar issues arising in the market and the society at large. 
Moving from the acknowledgment that a Uniform Private Law at EU and global levels does not exist as legal systems, the course aims at introducing the students to the comprehension of private law matters from the perspective of a transnational lawyer, who is able to address private law issues in both purely domestic (national) and cross-border situations and to acknowledge the role that both the E.U. and the international law play in providing principles and rules applicable in private law contexts. 
Active attendance and study of class materials will enable students to:
- explain the core concepts and principles commonly used in private law with special regard to those used within western legal tradition;
- map the legal sources and identify the applicable legal instruments (or the needed process for their identification) to a private law situation, even if it includes elements that are linked with more than one legal system;
- having regard to core matters of private law addressed in the course, identify the EU legislation applicable to them;
- in addressed areas of private law, outline the core contents of a judgment of the Court of Justice and discuss its possible relevance in matters of private law at national level;
- identify the existence of rights and define their legal nature within a concrete relation or situation in the area of private law;
- apply principles and rules of private law to concrete cases;
- identify the existence of conflicts and the main remedies provided by private law to protect individual and collective rights.

The course intends to deepen the institute of the mortis causa succession by historical comparative research.
At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
-  know successions in Roman law;
- know the main logical-argumentative techniques used by Roman jurists in the development of succession rules, which are common to many European legal systems;
- understand the "continuity" and "discontinuity" between the mortis causa succession of Roman sources and the institute of succession as regulated by the current Italian legal system.

Teaching Objectives:
The course aims at providing students with a comprehensive knowledge of the criminal sanctioning system, from a national as well as comparative perspective; particular attention will be devoted to the enforcement of penalties and the so-called «flexible enforcement». The course will focus on the purposes of criminal punishment, especially on individual deterrence and prevention, and on the system of criminal punishment and the relevant legal framework. 
Expected teaching results:
At the end of the course, the student is expected to show:
-	knowledge of the doctrine on the purposes of criminal punishment and its evolution;
-	comprehensive knowledge of the Italian sanctioning system;
-	understanding of the sanctioning procedures and mechanisms disciplined within the Italian Statute on Penitentiary Law;
-	critical assessment of the impact of ECHR case-law on domestic law;
-	general understanding of the rights of detainees;
-	ability to use the technical language in an appropriate and precise fashion.

The general goal of the course is providing the knowledge of the main quantum algorithms and their application to the development of machine learning schemes with quantum computers. The students will be involved in the study of the quantum versions of well-known procedures of classical machine learning. At the end of the course the students will have learned:
1) how the notions of quantum states and quantum measurements can be adapted into an information theoretical framework;
2) how to encode classical information into quantum systems and how to process it by means of quantum operations.
3) where quantum resources may be relevant in the context of Machine Learning;
4) the basics of the construction of quantum implementations of machine learning algorithms.

The purpose of the course is to develop the ability to understand and interpret fundamental texts of Italian literature.
The successful student will be able to:
a. explain the literal meaning of texts;
b. correctly define them according to critical categories (genre, verse form, characteristic stylistic and rhetoric devices);
c. frame them within the appropriate historical and cultural context;
d. know key moments and canonical authors in Italian literature.

The course would like to provide the students with the historical and conceptual instruments to better understand the classics of the Jewish thought, especially those from the modern and contemporary age. It aims to offer:
a) a basic knowledge of the historical context of these classics;
b) the philosophical, theological, and ethical concepts present in these classics;
c) the ability to recognize their sources;
d) the ability to understand the methods and the major themes of a rabbinical discussions;
e) the appreciation for the philosophical value of those methods and discussions.

In a professional context which is becoming increasingly complex and competitive, effective communication skills are deemed essential for legal practitioners who interact in domestic and cross-border situations. This is patently evident in scenarios where lawyers are required to communicate actively, e.g. interactions with colleagues and employees, client interviewing, conflict management through negotiation and mediation, legal and business relationships with institutions.
In this framework, the workshop on "Effective Communication and Soft Skills" is designed to provide students with basic theoretical and practical knowledge of how to properly and effectively communicate, being aware that hard skills represent only one approach to  communication.
In particular, at the end of the course students will be able to:
-recognize the fundamental features of different kinds of communication;
-identify the main differences between hard and soft skills;
-appropriately master essential communication skills, and especially assertive communication; 
-identify the fundamental features of cross-cultural communication and its underlying problems, specifically at a linguistic level;
-apply communication and soft skills in selected legal situations.

The course shall focus on the emerging issues of marketing management. Each topic will be analysed both from a methodological and a operative point of view. The expected skills at the end of the course are the following:
- knowledge of the main logics of communication and brand value management;
- comprehension of the main market decisions of the firms;
- consideration of the new opportunities of communication and relation with the customers

1) Training objectives:

The course aims to convey the essential elements of civil law provided for the annual balance sheet of insurance companies and also focuses on issues related to IAS / IFRS, Solvency and analysis of company documents. It is aimed at students who want to pursue a career in the insurance sector, auditing or consulting fields.

2) Expected Learning Outcomes:

At the end of the course, the student should be able to:
1. Illustrate the peculiarities of the financial statements of insurance companies;
2. Understand the main accounting issues related to the insurance financial statements in terms of accounting principles and disclosures;
3. Understand, to analyze and to interpret the financial statements of insurance companies;
4. Identify critical business realities, formulating them in a clear and structured manner;
5. Elaborate and to propose effective planning alternatives that are consistent with the organizational context of the enterprise.

The course has two main goals: 
1) To provide students with basic knowledge of the main categories of private law, with special emphasis on legal subjectivity and its forms, property law, the role of contract law and the other types of obligations, civil liability. Students will also learn how to find sources of law and how to interpret legal rules, with particular regard to EU law and the Italian Civil Code.
By the end of the course students will be able to:
a) Identify the main areas of private law;
b) Apply basic concepts of private law to new legal problems;
c) Use the main interpretation techniques in the field of private law;
d) identify the sources of private law which apply to a  specific problem.

The aim of the course is to provide the economic foundations for the study of law and economics.
At the end of the course, students will be able: 
- to understand and to explain how prices are determined in a market economy; 
- to understand and to explain how the market allocates scarce resources;
- to understand and to explain how different legal frameworks bring to different resources’ allocation.

The goal of the course is to provide students with theoretical and practical tools for the design and implementation of correct and efficient algorithmic solutions for a large set of computational problems.

At the end of the course, students are expected:
A) to remember the characteristics of the main data structures and to understand what could be their contribution in the solution of computational problems;
B) to formally describe a selected collection of computational problems and their solution, being able to discuss their correctness;
C) to know the main algorithmic techniques and to select those better suited to solve a particular problem;
D) to analyze the computational complexity of algorithms, i.e. to quantify the resources needed for their executions;
E) to compare distinct algorithmic solutions and to select the one which is better suited given a particular input.

Based on these competences related to the literature of “classical” algorithms, students should be able to solve a large array of computational problems, i.e.:
F) to precisely understand the problem to be solved, by defining the mathematical relationship between the input and the output of the problem;
G) to design an algorithmic solution for such problem, by adapting an existing solution or by building a new solution from scratch;;
H) to evaluate the correctness and the computational complexity of the proposed solution;
I) to implement the selected solution by using an imperative programming language.

The course aims at giving the student a deeper understanding of the fundamental principles of fiscal law, starting with statutory reserve and contribution capacity and concluding with a study of tax implementation mechanisms.
At the end of the course, student will be able:
1) to know and to understand the taxation law sources relating to the law system in the national context;
2) to know the fundamental principles of the Italian Constitution relating to the Italian tax system;
3) to know taxable persons, tax obligation and tax return, tax investigation, tax assessment, collection and refund;
4) to achieve an appropriate level of knowledge in individual income tax law;
5) to acquire the ability to illustrate the main issues of the course using the appropriated legal lexicon;
6) to learn the main links between the different legal matters discussed during the course.

General aims of the SOCIAL ETHICS course are:
1) to facilitate the identification and rigorous formulation of moral issues emerging within the various contexts in which modern and contemporary society is articulated; 
2) to encourage a competent assessment of the possibilities and limits of intervention of ethical reflection dealing with such problems; 
3) to investigate the presuppositions and forms of justification of philosophical ethics, favoring at the same time the argumented comparison with different ethics as well as the search for solutions to emerging moral dissensions in different social places and in relation to institutions.

At the end of the SOCIAL ETHICS course students will be able:
A) to make use of a general knowledge of ethics in its historical development and in its correlation with relevant social structures, transformations and problems;
B) to orient itself among the most significant theoretical paradigms of ethics, as well as to master the specific conceptual terminology;
C) reading and interpreting classical texts of ethics through historical contextualization, identification of fundamental theoretical structures, and critical discussion of their practical implications;
D) to recognize the patterns of action that structure the practical contexts and to interpret in philosophical terms the arising moral problems.

The aim of the course is to provide students with the basic technical and conceptual tools necessary to move independently in the field of historical research. Therefore, precise knowledge will be provided concerning:
the most important junctions in the history of historiography, with particular attention to medieval, early modern and modern history;
the most important research fields of history;
the characteristics and methods of the main contemporary historiographical schools;
the characteristics of the most important types of documents, their fields of application, together with some examples of their use by historians.
During practical lessons, which also include a visit to a research library, detailed knowledge will be provided on:
the main scientific journals and the most important catalogues and collections of sources;
historical research carried out using libraries and archives;
historical research carried out using the Internet;
the forms of the bibliographic citation;
the drafting of a short scientific essay on historical subjects.
The attendance of planned training activities (lectures and practical lessons) and individual study will ensure that, at the end of the course, students know and are able to define and describe, both orally and in writing, the characteristics and details of the aforementioned areas of knowledge.

At the end of the course, students will: 
- know and understand basic concepts of the debate on corporate governance and corporate social responsibility;
- know and understand main issues concerning on the efficiency of corporate governance structures; 
- know and understand institutions and practices of corporate governance in a national and international perspective.

The course aims at providing a basic introduction to the concepts and the tools for data exploration and visualization, thorugh class lectures and lab sessions. The core of the class is the exploration of the theoretical foundations and the practice of the diverse dimensionality reduction strategies, from the basic procedures to the more advanced state-of-the-art algorithms. Further, basics of clustering theory will also be shown. These topics will be complemented by a discussion on the principles of data visualization through the different types of graphics.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- describe the overall structure of a multidimensional dataset;
- effectively project a multidimensional dataset in a lower dimensional space highlighting the main features;
- choose a suitable graphical representation to pinpoint one or more quantitative aspects of the dataset;
- write the code to implement the chosen graph.

The course aims to review the main theories, notions and methods of empirical analysis adopted to reach a multidimensional understanding of contemporary migration. Adopting an interdisciplinary approach and considering migratory systems historically different, the course focuses on mobility since the second postwar period, with particular attention on the current globalization of migration.
Special attention will be paid to the notion of ‘national boundary’, understood as territorial and categorial dimension: on one side, the course will consider the migrants’ transnationalism, deepening its forms and in relation with the issues of assimilation, belonging and nationhood; on the other side, the process of borders enforcement will be taken into account, disentangling the ways it affects both mobility and the categories of identity. 

At the end of the course, students are expected to be able of arguing about contemporary migration:
- discerning among different phenomena, theoretical approaches and interpretative levels;
- achieving skills in deconstructing and interpreting  phenomena in a critical and documented way;
- being capable to formulate consistent statements and analyses not biased by value judgments;
- making a written text, that has to be clear, exhaustive and documented, focused on one of the topics developed during the course.

The course aims to introduce students to a specific topic about the Middle Ages, to show them a research method and to provide them with skills to carry out individual research on Middle Age history.
At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
(a) report the main contents of the course, using an appropriate vocabulary;
(b) expose methods that have been used in the research path to reach determined conclusions;
(c) analyse a historical source about the subjects covered in the teaching describing the features and articulations of its form and content
(d) judge the results of the research critically, hypothesising different solutions or proposing further research.

The goal of this course is to provide students with advanced notions on the
main problem and techniques in the designe and implementation of distributed systems. The course is a follow-up of "Distributed Systems 1".

Consider it as course on "Distributed Algorithms"; the focus is on the principles, rather than on a particular technology. Concretely this includes the following objectives:
- Present the principles underlying the functioning of distributed systems;
- Create an awareness of the major technical challenges in distributed systems design and implementation;
- Expose students to current techniques used to solve the aforementioned challenges;
- Provide experience in the implementation of typical algorithms used in distributed systems;
- Expose students to current technology and distributed infrastructure software.

Mastering the approaches suitable to capture the nonlinearities exhibited by solids and structures under extreme events is key for analyzing and designing systems under situations that cannot be captured through standard methodologies. The use of modern concepts and tools is envisioned within this course.
The ultimate outcome of this class is to understand the principles governing material and geometric nonlinearities characterizing solid and structural mechanics under extreme conditions, such as:
•	mechanics of extreme deformations;
•	cellular materials damping extreme loadings;
•	high-stress concentrations;
•	inelastic phenomena: time dependent behavior of solids and structures, such as viscoelasticity, viscoplasticity, damage, impact, phase transitions, etc.;
•	nonlinear elasticity, strain localization, localized buckling, etc.

The main learning objectives of this course are:
deepening the students' knowledge in  marketing;
developing their capability to apply that knowledge to a firm's activity;
developing their capability to work in the unfamiliar context of an international group, under stressful conditions.
At the end of the course the students will be able to:
identify the information needed for evaluating the market situation of a company operating in durable consumer goods (and by analogy of all firms);
understand such informartion and carefully analyse it in order to identify the possible strategies and marketing actions that the firm can implement;
define the details of these actions and plan them, working in cooperation with the team;
develop the capacity to work under stress, in a multinational group of previously unknown people;
acquire multi-cultural and behavioural soft skills useful for working in an international firm.

In the framework of the differential calculus for multivariable functions, and referring to the programme for a more detailed description of the course content, at the end of the course the student should:

- know and be able to apply the basic concepts of the differential calculus for vector-valued functions of several variables, with a specific focus on the dimensions 2 and 3, and to master its specific language. In particular, the student should be able to precisely state all the theorems and the definitions of the course programme;

- be able to illustrate theorems and definitions, also making use of examples (in particular of those proposed during the classes);

- be able to graphically illustrate the mathematical objects of the course, such as surfaces, solid figures, and vector fields;

- master the calculus techniques and argue properly;

- be able to solve problems similar to those proposed during the classes, and to derive new interesting pieces of information starting from those already developed;

- be able to prove a selection of the proposed theorems.

The course aims to explain basic knowledge of electromagnetism and of the wave nature of the light.
Attendance and active participation in training activities offered by the course and self-study will enable students to:
1) define the key elements for solving simple electromagnetic problems;
2) solve simple problems of electromagnetism and optics;
3) implement simple laboratory experiments to characterize basic electromagnetic devices;
4) critically evaluate the results obtained from laboratory experiments;
5) present the results in written reports that summarize the methods followed in the experiment, to  debate their the choice and to quantify the results;

The course offers the necessary skills aimed at carrying out in adequate, effective and efficient way applied social research. In particular, the course supplies the conceptual and methodological tools to correctly set a social research based on quantitative methods. 
At the end of the course, students will be able to:
1) define a research problem and formulate coherent and appropriate research hypotheses;
2) translate some key sociological concepts into variables;
3) describe the main features of various strategy for data collection;
4) select the most appropriate sources of micro-data to answer the research question of interest;
5) conduct a theoretically-oriented secondary data analysis;
6) interpret the results of this analysis and communicate them to both an academic and non-academic audience.

This module will embrace the anatomical, cellular, molecular and functional organization of the Peripheral Nervous System (PNS). 

At the end of this course, students will be able to:
•	Describe the anatomy of the PNS
•	Explain the similarities and differences between different branches of the PNS;
•	Understand the complexity of the physiological function controlled by the PNS;
•	Understand how the functions of the PNS are finely tuned at different levels;
•	Understand how the different components of the PNS operate in a coordinated manner;
•	Critically evaluate the experimental approaches used to study the PNS, and the evolving comprehension of the mechanisms underlining the functions of the PNS.

The course International Business Management is divided into two modules each of 8 ECTS: International Marketing e International Corporate Strategy.
International Marketing:
The main objective of this module is to develop the ability to understand marketing issues linked to the presence of the company in foreign markets.
ILO, therefore, are:
knowledge and understanding of globalisation dynamics; knowledge and understanding of the internationalisation process of the firm and of the entry modes in foreign markets;
develoment of the capacity to implement the acquired knowledge in operational conditions through carrying out analysis of foreign markets and the drafting of international marketing plans;
acquisition of the soft skills needed to work in multinational groups (also in multiple locations).
At the end of the course the students shall be able to:
understand the dynamics of globalisation and internatonalisation within a company as well as those of the enty in foreign markets;
apply their knowledge to real situations;
carry out analysis of foreign markets targeted to specific needs of companies;
draft marketing plans for an international environment;
work in international groups both in personal contact and with distance links.
International Corporate Strategy:
To succeed in the future, managers must develop the resources and capabilities needed to gain and sustain advantage in competitive markets—traditional and emerging. The way in which organizations attempt to develop such competitive advantage constitutes the essence of their strategy.
The module has been designed to allow students to gain the knowledge and expertise necessary to perform a manager role as a strategist by encouraging and enabling students to develop the intellectual and professional acumen needed for the conception and analysis of responsible business strategies; to make appropriate choices between strategic options; and then to follow a strategic trajectory that will deliver results that are robust, ethically sound and socially responsible. Accordingly, the module adopts a contingency approach that is grounded in the understanding of the non-existence of a best way in strategy.

On completion of the module you should be able to:
• Assess, analyse and reflect upon strategy and strategic decision-making.
• Apply strategy concepts and models to analyse and appraise a company’s strategy.
• Identify and evaluate strategic choices for the future.

The course focuses on the history of republican Italy, with a specific attention toward the role of European integration in national political, economic, social and cultural events.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
- know the moments, processes and fundamental stages of republican history;
- orientate themselves in the historiographical debate about the history of the Italian Republic;
- understand the effects of European integration on Italy

The module is part of the fundamental preparation for students in the degree course in Philosophy.
The aim of course is to provide a series of notions and categories in order to recognize and problematize in philosophical terms the interpretative modes and the conceptual distinctions that orient, in past and present life, the understanding of the existences in their relationship with the others and the world. In particular, every year a fundamental phenomenon of existence (e.g. birth, death, pain, play, gift, destiny, freedom, love) will be analysed with its theoretical implications, starting from relevant authors and currents of thought regarding the topic being considered. To this is added the supplementary study of classical texts, not necessarily linked to the subject of the monographic course, functional to the theoretical training of the student. This will allow to master concepts, doctrines, paradigms, styles of reflection and argumentation that have characterized the development of the western thought in a theoretical perspective. The attention to the conceptual dimension, the semantic distribution of key terms, the logical-formal structure of arguments and the mutual questioning of theory and experience will improve the ability to decipher life contexts, thus detecting aspects not immediately evident and inedited connections between different knowledge.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
A) Identify, reconstruct and explain the philosophical subject examined during the course, knowing how to contextualize it both historically and systematically;
B) to identify, reconstruct and present in a convincing manner the argumentative strategies exerted in the philosophical contexts examined during the course;
C) to independently organize the acquired knowledge and the results of the analysis carried out, with appropriate references to the literature;
D) to re-elaborate the acquired knowledge through the production of a written philosophical review, referring to one of the texts specifically indicated in the program and related to the monographic subject of the course. This review will be sent to the professor at least 10 days before the exam.

The course is divided in two partitions:
- Innovation and Entrepreneurship Basics --> For EIT Digital, AI and Innovation and ICT Innovation students
- Innovation and Business in ICT --> For Computer Science and Information and Communication/Telecommunications Engineering Master's

-----

Innovation and Entrepreneurship Basics: 


The course introduces students to the field of Innovation and Entrepreneurship (I&E) as a theory and as a practice, contextualising it in the field of ICT. The goal of the course is to give students strong fundamentals in the field of I&E, acquire a broader perspective of their main field of study, and help them develop “soft skills” such as leadership, critical thinking, and creativity.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- Outline key I&E concepts such as Digital Transformation, and discuss how they relate to current socio-technical phenomena;
- Critically assess technologies not just technically, but also with respect to their social and policy impacts;
- Create rough drafts of sustainable business models starting from an idea and/or product;
- Discuss the role of entrepreneurship in society from an economic and social perspective;
- Outline a few archetypical models of organisations and how they function;
- Discuss how technologies can become sources of disruption for contemporary society;
- Present and defend their ideas in public;
- Discuss ethical implications of innovations, business models and technologies;
- Identify and discuss technological macro-trends and contextualise them in the I&E field;
- Positively work in a group setting, managing deadlines and internal group dynamics.

-----

Innovation and Business in ICT:

The objective of this course is to develop theoretical and practical understanding of the innovation and entrepreneurial processes from idea generation to exploitation. It is aimed at students who want to enhance their entrepreneurial and innovation skills, or take an entrepreneurial role by setting up their new ventures or by developing innovative ideas in existing companies. This course will help students develop both hard skills (e.g. business modelling, entrepreneurial finance) and soft skills (e.g. empathy, creative thinking, storytelling). 

At the end of the course, students will be able to:

- Understand the stages/phases of the entrepreneurial and innovation processes from the initial perception of an innovative idea to its realisation in a market or social context
- Identify and evaluate entrepreneurial and innovation opportunities
- Reflect on the skills and behaviours of entrepreneurs and innovators
- Reflect on the challenges entrepreneurs and innovators face, and the resources and skills they need to draw upon, when developing new ideas in uncertain environments
- Critically assess the merits of alternative models and strategies for innovation that entrepreneurs can adopt to benefit from the value of new ideas
- Exhibit enhanced skills in terms of critical thinking, systems thinking, information synthesis, and creativity

This course aims to provide a critical knowledge of the history of Italian literature in the period between Tasso and the end of the nineteenth century.
Within this chronological frame, we will focus either on a literary theme or genre, through texts by various authors, or on the study of a single author or work, also with respect to their critical reception through history.
At the end of the course students will be able to:
a. supply a critical and historical framework for the theme, genre, author, or work at hand;
b. have in-depth knowledge and comment texts introduced in class;
c. confidently orient themselves within the assigned secondary literature

The course is designed to give Students an overall knowledge  of the evolution from Latin to Romance literatures and languages in its basic lines, with reference to both historical grammar and literary history.
By the end of the course, Students will have acquired
- a general understanding of the main literary genres, texts and authors of medieval Romance literatures;
- the ability to translate and analyze medieval Romance texts in verse and prose;
- a comparative approach in the analysis of historical-literary themes and motifs as well as historical-linguistic and philological aspects and phenomena.

The course shall focus on the emerging issues of marketing management. Each topic will be analysed both from a methodological and a operative point of view. The expected skills at the end of the course are the following:
- knowledge of the main logics of communication and brand value management;
- comprehension of the main market decisions of the firms;
- consideration of the new opportunities of communication and relation with the customers

Competition law fosters and maintains market competition by prohibiting anti-competitive conduct. This course is meant to introduce students to the legal and economic principles that inform the structure and enforcement of competition law in an international dimension. 
This course's objective is first an interdisciplinary appraisal of European and US antitrust/competition law. Secondly, the module will cover antitrust/competition principles in selected other countries. Lastly, the course is aimed at considering the impact of the increasingly significant international dimension of competition policy, such as the role of the International Competition Network, problems of extraterritoriality and other issues at the interface between competition policy and trade law.
By the time students complete, they should be able to demonstrate a practical and theoretical understanding of the fundamental competition/antitrust issues posed by a series of common business practices, such as distribution contracts, intellectual property licences, and mergers. In particular, this involves students’ ability to:
a) explain and discuss the main objectives of competition policy;
b) identify actual business and strategy issues relevant to competition policy;
c) utilize legal and economic tools to provide an in-depth analysis of these critical issues.

The students are supposed to know and to be able to apply the basic concepts of the integro differential calculus for vector valued functions of several variables, with special regard to dimensions 1,2, and 3. More precisely, the student are expected:
- to describe the precise statements of theorems and definitions;
- to illustrate theorems and definitions through examples;
- to visualize, describe and give a graphical representation of the mathematical objects (curves, surfaces, solid figures, coordinates transformations, vector fields,...);
- to master the techniques of calculus and arguing properly;
- to solve problems with a degree of difficulty comparable to what they have seen during the exercises sessions;
- to describe the proofs of a selected number of theorems

An overall goal of the course is to consolidate the mathematical preparation acquired by the students in the fields of Mathematical Analysis, Linear Algebra and Geometry.

The course provides the basic knowledge of Newtonian mechanics and classical electromagnetism, their experimental foundations and their operational skills in solving physical problems and in the development of technological applications.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
- know the physical laws at the base of Newtonian mechanics with their experimental foundations and their fields of application;
- solve simple physical problems through correct modeling and correct use of the mathematical tools necessary to reach the quantitative solution.
Attendance and active participation in the training activities proposed by the course (lectures and classroom exercises) and individual study will allow students to:
1) be familiar with the basics of the scientific method applied to classical mechanics;
2) acquire the habit of critical analysis of concepts that enter into scientific and physical theories in particular;
3) understand and summarize the principles and laws in the Galilean context and in Newtonian dynamics;
4) apply the physical laws learned to the solution of exercises and problems of classical mechanics.

An engineering approach to software development is fundamental for coping with the increasing complexity of systems and to guarantee their economical sustainability. As for any other engineering discipline, the software production requires a systematic organization of the activities, the adoption of a well-defined process and methods and tools to support the quality and the respect of the project constraints. The objective of the course is providing to the students concepts, approaches and techniques for the analysis, the design, and the development of the software. In particular, the course will focus on process models, modelling languages and verification and validation techniques. Moreover, diagrammatic languages, requirements analysis methods, design principles and testing techniques will allow the students to design high quality software. The students will be practicing by developing and implementing a web service applying the most modern development techniques, including the adoption of RESTful directives and the use of standard languages for the documentation of web APIs, the collaboration in the development of the source code in a central repository, the automation of code testing, and the configuration of services and tools to set-up a continuous integration process for the software. Finally, project management concepts and metrics for software products will be introduced. 
At the end of the course, the student will be able to: 
1. define the most suitable development process and model for the analysis and the design of the software under consideration; 
2. represent with the different types of diagrams the requirements, the architecture, the intarction among the components, and the deployment of the system; 
3. define and mange in a consistent and complete way the functional and non functional requirements of a software system highlighting priorities and criticises. 
4. Define the architecture of a software system adopting architectural styles and principles of refinement, abstraction, modularity, functional independency and refactoring; 
5. Design a component of a software system identifying the control type and following the step-by-step process for the respect of the general design principles; 
6. describe requirements and implement them in an agile manner, with short development cycles to ensure regular and frequent delivery of software to users;
7. Define and document a web service compliant with RESTful directives, collaborate into the development of the source code, testing the code, and automating the deployment of the software with a continuous integration process.

The course aims to provide the basics notions for understanding the legal and institutional context in which the various economic actors work, through the analysis of the structure and methods of intervention of public institutions that – globally, at the European and at the national level – operate for the regulation of economy.
At the end of the course the student will be able to:
- identify the public institutions that take part in the governance of the economy, distinguishing between global, European and national level;	
- identify the rules and legal acts used for the regulation of the economy;	
- know the powers and procedures used by regulatory authorities and understand how they work;	
- distinguish the different ways for public authorities to intervene in the economy and understand the working dynamics of enterprises with public participation;	
- know and understand the functioning of the administrative tools used to regulate business activity in the market;	
- know and understand the ways in which public institutions intervene for the safeguard of the competitivity of the market.

The course aims to provide students with the basic concepts of:
- measure and integration theory;
- function series (in particular, power and trigonometric series);
- the theory of ordinary differential equations (in particular, of the linear type).
At the end of the course, through the frequency and active participation to the proposed training activities (frontal lessons and classroom exercises) and individual study, the student will be able to understand the following:  
- that the different types of the considered integrals are different declinations of the same abstract concept;
- the various convergence types of function series (pointwise, uniform, total);
- theoretical bases of the existence for the Cauchy's problem relative to an ordinary differential equation;
- the applications of these topics which the student will find in Advanced Mathematical Analysis and Mathematical Physics.
The student will be able to present the theoretical arguments at the basis of this understanding by proving theorems, exposing links and comparisons between different aspects of theory and between theory and applications, proposing examples useful to illustrate an abstract argument. In addition, the student will apply the theory to solve exercises whose characteristics will be specified during the exercise sessions held by the teacher within the course itself.

The course aims to introduce students to the study of the several legal issues involved in the management of data, by critically analysing a selection of topics characterizing this area. At the end of the course, students will be able:
- to familiarise with the basic concepts of the legal issues involved in Data science;
- to be able to critically analyse such issues;
- to learn how to manage a data science scenario from a legal point of view;
- to complete their data scientist profile with the necessary legal knowledges.

The course aims to provide students with the tools necessary to approach the field of  physics  that deals with the properties of innovative materials  widely used in industry, for example: metals, semiconductors, oxides, for applications in the field of catalysis and photocatalysis
At the end of the course students will be able to:
1. Know the basics of thermodynamics, quantum mechanics and statistical mechanics relevant for the physics of materials;
2. Understand the appropriate differential equations for the study of issues related to the atomic and electronic transport;
3. Relate the concepts of thermodynamics, quantum mechanics and statistical mechanics with experimental properties of materials: metals, insulators and semiconductors;
4. Know the basic principles regarding  the materials used in catalysis and photocatalysis.

This Course aims to transmit an integrated approach to the design and building construction, developing the relationship between architectural-spatial, technological-constructive, structural, energy-technical installation and environmental design aspects. The specific objective is to develop the basic technical knowledge and operational skills applied to the understanding, control, definition and design of the fabrication and detail building project, according to a methodological approach that conceives the construction project as a process of verification and coherent synthesis between design ideation and technical-constructive feasibility.

The expected learning outcomes (knowledge and skills) are:

Knowledge and understanding.
The student will acquire, through the lectures, the knowledge and understanding of the basic theoretical and applied issues related to the design and building construction with particular reference to the:
- knowledge of the building process, design levels, technical-information contents and graphic representation of the fabrication and detail building project;
- knowledge of the relationships between type, analysis of user needs, functional definition, site, spatial composition, environmental context, building construction;
- knowledge of the design principles of nodes and interfaces between basic construction systems, of their development in the fabrication and detail building project;
- knowledge of the design principles of technical installations, responses to fire prevention regulations, accessibility and inclusive design issues, their integration into the fabrication and detail building project.

Ability to apply knowledge and understanding.
The student will acquire, through the group practical exercise, skills in the practice of the fabrication and detail building project with particular reference to the:
- ability to understand and define analytical methods, techniques, procedures and operational tools aimed at the construction project;
- ability to understand and design a fabrication and detail building project of medium complexity, the technical and communicative contents of the drawings;
- ability to understand and control the coherence between spatial and context-related choices, construction technologies, structural aspects and technical installation needs.

Autonomy of judgment, communication and learning skills.
The student will acquire, through the lectures and the group practical exercise, the ability to:
- act, interact, communicate, evaluate, with a critical spirit and independent judgment, within the fabrication and detail building project and the integration between spatial, technological, structural, technical installation aspects;
- conceiving, designing and draw the fundamental constructive elements, identifying congruent and compatible solutions.

Learning about destination governance and management with focus on community destination.
Active attendance to the lessons and teaching activities (interactive frontal lectures, case-study analysis, multidisciplinary project and team work) and individual learning will allow students:
•	to analyze the features of tourism destinations;
•	to evaluate the challenges of governance and management in community destinations;
•	to apply theoretical frameworks to identify and analyse actors, activities an relationships that characterise community destination;
•	to evaluate management choices made by Destination Management Organisation (DMO);
•	to create an innovative and experiential tourism product within a community destination (team work).
Active attendance to the lessons and teaching activities will allow students to critically evaluate features and structure of destination management strategies within community destinations. Students will be able to apply problem solving techniques, to organize project work and to present and discuss the results.

The course aims to: 
- Develop knowledge on the most relevant historical phases of the Middle Ages.
- Develop confidence in engaging with current scholarly debates.
- Develop skills in analysing a variety of types of primary sources.

After attending the course and after reading the reference bibliography, the students will be able to:
- define and describe the most important turning points of the Medieval history;
- recognize and analyze a variety of types of primary sources;
- analyze and comment a historiographic text;
- analyze a historic map;
- define and use the specific terms of the medieval studies.

The aim of the course is to provide the students with the basic concepts for the understanding of the structural and functional organization of prokaryotic cells and viruses, as well as their main biotechnological applications.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
-Understand fundamental concepts of microbiology;
-Describe prokaryotic and viral structures and how they relate to cell functionalities and to the interaction with other organisms and the environment;
-Describe metabolic diversity of prokaryotes and how these organisms derive energy, electrons, and carbon from their environment;
-Describe basic genetic mechanisms of microbes with specific reference to horizontal gene transfer;
-Describe the basis of pathogenicity mechanisms of microbes;
-Discuss the main options for the control of microbial growth in vitro and in vivo;
-Prepare and recognize microscopic preparations, culture plates and growth media; 
-Identify, enumerate and transform bacterial cells;
-Evaluate potential benefits and detriments caused by microorganisms;
-Retain and apply specialized language relevant to microbiology.

The course aims at providing a basic introduction to the concepts and the tools for data exploration and visualization, thorugh class lectures and lab sessions. The core of the class is the exploration of the theoretical foundations and the practice of the diverse dimensionality reduction strategies, from the basic procedures to the more advanced state-of-the-art algorithms. Further, basics of clustering theory will also be shown. These topics will be complemented by a discussion on the principles of data visualization through the different types of graphics.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- describe the overall structure of a multidimensional dataset;
- effectively project a multidimensional dataset in a lower dimensional space highlighting the main features;
- choose a suitable graphical representation to pinpoint one or more quantitative aspects of the dataset;
- write the code to implement the chosen graph.

This is a general physics course, supporting more advanced courses at second and third year. In particular, the objectives are:
    • know the physical quantities and their measurement units;
    • know the basis of vectorial calculus and develop the ability of calculating using vectors;
    • know the basics of the laws of mechanics and fluids, as well as thermodynamics;
    • develop a basic knowledge of electromagnetism and of the wave nature of light.

Attending the course, actively participating to the proposed activities and studying individually will allow the students to:
    • evaluate the effects of different applied forces on the motion of a material point;
    • describe the effects of pressure and forces on a fluid, both at rest and in motion;
    • describe the simplest processes of heat exchange;
    • evaluate electrical forces between electrical charges, as well as voltages and currents in simple electrical circuits;
    • solve simple problems of electromagnetism;
    • describe image formation by means of simple optical systems.

The course aims to teach students the clinical path and associated methodologies that accompany an oncologic patient from cancer diagnosis to the choice of the most appropriate therapy. In detail, the course describes different methods of bioptic sampling and processing, diagnostic criteria of tumor staging, surgery and pharmacological strategies for the treatment of specific types of solid cancer. Particular attention will be dedicated to technological innovations in the field of tumor diagnosis, in vivo imaging and radiology, as well as to dissecting the difference between classical chemotherapeutic drugs and innovative “target” therapies.
At the end of the course students will be able to:
-	Define different clinical approaches adopted for the diagnosis and treatment of specific forms of tumor;
-	Compare pros and cons of different clinical strategies; 
-	Classify a pathologic condition in low, medium, and high risk categories and propose a clinical approach and predict possible outcomes;
-	Examine and estimate tumor response to a specific therapy;
Integrate clinical information with genetic data in order to design targeted treatments.

The course would like to provide the students with the historical and conceptual instruments to better understand the classics of the Jewish thought, especially those from the modern and contemporary age. It aims to offer:
a) a basic knowledge of the historical context of these classics;
b) the philosophical, theological, and ethical concepts present in these classics;
c) the ability to recognize their sources;
d) the ability to understand the methods and the major themes of a rabbinical discussions;
e) the appreciation for the philosophical value of those methods and discussions.

At the end of the course, the student is expected to:
be familiar with the history of the sociology of culture, its leading figures and most relevant work;
connect current research to some of the classical roots of the discipline and to key questions in contemporary social theory;
be able to read critically work in the cultural sociological tradition and to identify intellectual positions and differences among scholars;
be able to design research in the areas of sociology of culture and cultural sociology;
carry on basic research in autonomy, and to apply a range of methods to answer to specific research questions.

The course offers an introduction to atmosphere and climate processes, to the physical mechanisms governing them, and to how their understanding supports meteorological and climatological analysis and prediction.
The course aims at providing students, coming from different university curricula, a common background on the basics of the earth's atmosphere processes.
The course will also briefly introduce students to concepts and processes that will be developed in depth in the other courses the students will attend within the programme.

At the end of the course students will be enabled to:
- understand the basic physical laws governing atmospheric processes;
- be familiar with the main weather and climate phenomena introduced during frontal lectures, and with the physical variables involved in those phenomena;
- provide order-of-magnitude estimates to atmospheric variables and balances;
- discuss covered topics with critical reasoning;
- apply the basic equations to solve exercises on the course topics;
- possess the basics to analyse and interpret weather maps.

The course would like to provide the students with the historical and conceptual instruments to better understand the classics of the Jewish thought, especially those from the modern and contemporary age. It aims to offer:
a) a basic knowledge of the historical context of these classics;
b) the philosophical, theological, and ethical concepts present in these classics;
c) the ability to recognize their sources;
d) the ability to understand the methods and the major themes of a rabbinical discussions;
e) the appreciation for the philosophical value of those methods and discussions.

The General and Inorganic Chemistry course provides the basic concepts of inorganic chemistry with the aim to understand and interpret natural phenomena both in everyday life and in the future professional activity.

The main aims of the course are to:
•	develop the proper chemical knowledge and property of language suitable to handle chemical problems with a rigorous scientific approach;
•	provide a description of the structure of atoms and chemical bonds that lead to the formation of inorganic compounds and explain their physico-chemical properties;
•	illustrate the interactions between atoms and between molecules and the resulting solid, liquid and gaseous states of aggregation of matter;
•	provide a description of the transformation of matter through chemical reactions from a thermodynamics point of view, looking at thermal balance, spontaneous reaction trend, and equilibrium conditions;
•	develop the capacity to do chemical calculations relative to mass, charge and energy balance;
•	develop the capacity to analyse and study the most common reactions of simple inorganic compounds such as solid solute dissolutions, acid and base dissociations in water solutions, oxidation-reduction processes.
This General and Inorganic Chemistry course is therefore complementary to the Physics ones in the study of the intrinsic properties of the matter and in its transformations, and is propaedeutic to organic and applied chemistry courses. 

At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
•	describe the elementary particle structure of atoms, isotopes and their ions;
•	describe the electronic configurations of the various elements, to predict their main periodic properties and their chemical reactivity;
•	understand and justify atomic bonding in inorganic compounds by means of ionic- and valence- bond theory;
•	understand the interatomic and intermolecular interactions in the various aggregation states of the matter an interpret the phase diagrams of elements and pure substances;
•	describe the behaviour of the ideal gas phase;
•	describe the chemical solutions, the main concentration units and the colligative properties and quantify their effects;
•	describe the equilibrium state of a chemical reaction, calculate its equilibrium constant from the thermodynamic data of reagents and products, and predict their theoretical final quantities;
•	calculate the solubility of different compounds (gasses, molecular or ionic solids) in saturated aqueous solutions;
•	calculate the pH value of ideal aqueous solutions for strong and weak acids and bases, hydrolysing salts, buffer solutions;
•	calculate the electric potential of chemical electrodes and the electromotive force of chemical cells.

This course will provide to the students the tools needed to simulate the hydrological cycle at various spatial and temporal scales. Students will learn how to simulate each of the individual hydrological fluxes in real applications in order to deal with optimal management of water resources and flood protection. Hydrological processes described in the basic course “Hydrology” will be here extended from the point scale to the watershed scale.
At the end of the course the student will be able:
•	to use hydrologic modeling to quantitatively estimate the role of physical processes in the hydrologic cycle;
•	to critically evaluate the different methods and models commonly used in hydrological modelling;
•	to set-up, parameterize and use hydrological models with particular emphasis on surface processes and watershed response.

The course will explore the interactional and institutional conditions for the design of physical, technological, and organizational devices that will provide greater opportunities for the inclusion of disadvantaged individuals and groups.

Students are expected to :
  • understand the centrality of the phenomenon;
  • acquire the ability to discern the mechanisms that contribute to its creation, as well as to understand their relevance in the contemporary world;
  • gain the ability to recognize the key elements of cultural phenomena and to place them in a proper analytical framework related to the subject of the course;
  • familiarize with the main frameworks related to the topic;

Students who will actively participate in the course will, in addition:
  • acquire the ability to read and contextualize texts that explore the problems faced during the course;
  • stimulate the research ability through the participation in the experimental phase  programmed the second half of the course;
  • acquire competencies for group work;
  • improve their oral presentation capacity.

The course aims to introduce the basic concepts of mechanics, thermodynamics, and optics, even for a better understanding of arguments in the chemical and biological fields.  The students are introduced to the experimental method  both  through lectures and laboratory activity, learn to formulate models and use mathematics to solve both problems, and conceptual and numerical problems.
At the end of the course  the student will be able to:
1) Measure physical quantities and assign to these the measurement error;
2) Understand the laws of mechanics, thermodynamics, and optics;
3) Solve various problems in these areas;
4) Carry out some laboratory experiments in mechanics, thermodynamics, and optics.

Philosophy of law means to look at law from a philosophical point of view, that is to question about law, its nature, its relations with morality or justice and so on, by adopting a peculiar method of discussion, argumentative and rhetorical in its nature.

At first, the course aims at illustrating the nature of this method.
Then, it focuses on the main legal philosophical questions by adopting synchronic and historical perspectives.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- manage the basic notion of truth;
- critically discuss the main legal philosophical questions;
- develop analytical skills about legal reasoning;
- understand the implications of the developments of law in its contemporary evolution.

The course aims to provide the concepts, methodologies and tools needed to understand and solve the main problems regarding people and relationships faced by junior and middle managers in companies operating in an international environment.
Upon completion of the course the student will be able to:
-	Recognize and understand the main motives behind individual behaviour in corporate environments;
-	Use combinations of intrinsic and extrinsic motivation levers to improve individual and group performance;
-	Understand the complexity and the nuances of the management of groups composed of persons who are heterogeneous by cultural and technical background; cognitive styles, nationalities;
-	Understand the main sources of conflict in small groups;
-	Effectively use differences in small groups to produce original solutions to new problems; 
-	Effectively handle communication and decision-making in work contexts.

The course aims to lead the students to the acquisition of knowledge on the historical development and the present status of ethnomusicology, on the objects and research methods of the discipline, on selected expressions of Italian and foreign traditional music.

At the end of the course the students will be able to:

-	identify and place in time the phases of development of Ethnomusicology, to define the role of the discipline within the Humanities area and Musicological Studies;

-	reflect on the meaning of categories such as traditional, folk and ethnic music; to identify their properties and traits of otherness, as well as the borders regions and the areas of transcultural creation;

-	autonomously retrace the thematic itinerary and the musical documents presented by the teacher, proving solid interpretation skills (in terms of complex reading of sound phenomena and on the base of the individual musical knowledge).

-	critically apply the research methods and the interpretation instruments to new objects of study and personal experiences of analysis;

-	employ appropriate methodological criteria in potential professional pathways connected to the specific area of the cultural heritage (in libraries, archives, museums, cultural offices, performing arts institutions, publishing business);

-	through an itinerary in the world of the sound expression, master fundamental themes and concepts of cultural anthropology, in order to promote, also in the educational domain, models of integration, social cohesion and interculturality.

The course aims at providing a basic introduction to the concepts and the tools for data exploration and visualization, thorugh class lectures and lab sessions. The core of the class is the exploration of the theoretical foundations and the practice of the diverse dimensionality reduction strategies, from the basic procedures to the more advanced state-of-the-art algorithms. Further, basics of clustering theory will also be shown. These topics will be complemented by a discussion on the principles of data visualization through the different types of graphics.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- describe the overall structure of a multidimensional dataset;
- effectively project a multidimensional dataset in a lower dimensional space highlighting the main features;
- choose a suitable graphical representation to pinpoint one or more quantitative aspects of the dataset;
- write the code to implement the chosen graph.

The overriding goal of this course is to acquire the basic concepts of politics, in a view to develop the capacity to understand, empirically and theoretically, the main social and political phenomena in Europe and worldwide. Students will gain insight into the interaction between interests, values and institutions in Europe and globally. In addition, the course provides an opportunity for students to engage in debate, discussion, and reflection on the main issues of international and European politics.

By the end of the course students should have acquired:

-	an in-depth understanding of the main concepts and issues in international and European politics;

-	various theoretical approaches to analyse contemporary international and European relations;

-	an ability to think critically, interpret, and draw pertinent conclusions regarding social and political phenomena at the international and European level;

-	a capacity to conduct independent analyses of issues in international and European politics, linking theories and empirical evidence, and presenting the results of the analyses in an effective way.

The educational goal of the course is to acquire a comprehensive competence in designing and developing autonomous aerial and terrestrial mobile systems, commonly known as UAVs (unmanned aerial vehicles) and UGVs (unmanned ground vehicles).
The course aims at teaching a solid design methodology including topics such as:
1) Vehicle dynamics.
2) Control and actuation systems.
3) Electrical and electronic components.
4) Navigation systems and positioning algorithms.
5) Programming of autonomous systems on local or distributed configuration.

The course focuses on the most advanced technological solutions and the theoretical and pragmatic aspects related to the creation of specific services on the platforms used in class and real-time information processing on the vehicle.

After completing the course, the student will be able:
- to understand the complexity, the problems, and the potential of autonomous mobile systems;
- to evaluate the different enabling technologies for communication, processing and management of energy autonomy, and choose the most ideas for the project case;
- to apply the best techniques and methods for the configuration of the drone system intended as a product, configuration of data processing, and configuration of the data acquisition and processing service.
- to make comparative evaluations about the different technological solutions available for UGV and UAV systems;
- to assess and analyse the practical and theoretical implications of an autonomous mobile system;
- to design an autonomous mobile system for a particular service or application or a specific objective;
- to critically assess the benefits and limitations of existing commercial or academic solutions.

The course aims at giving the fundamental notions of Microeconomics and Macroeconomics, developing the ability to understand and to interpret economic phenomena through the analysis of some relevant events drawn from Economic History.
By the end of the course students will be able:
- to know the basic economic notions;
- to explain the main phenomena, both at the microeconomic and the macroeconomic levels, and their consequences;
- to understand and interpret relevant past economic events in light of the notions acquired;
- to give an answer to some fundamental economic problems.

The course aims to: 
- Develop knowledge on the most relevant historical phases of the Middle Ages.
- Develop confidence in engaging with current scholarly debates.
- Develop skills in analysing a variety of types of primary sources.

After attending the course and after reading the reference bibliography, the students will be able to:
- define and describe the most important turning points of the Medieval history;
- recognize and analyze a variety of types of primary sources;
- analyze and comment a historiographic text;
- analyze a historic map;
- define and use the specific terms of the medieval studies.

Ethnicity and Ethnic diversity is a feature of all society and one of the dimensions of inequality alongside and intertwined with class, race, gender, generation and religion. By adopting interdisciplinary tools, the course aims at providing students with an understanding of ethnicity from a theoretical, empirical and policy-oriented perspective – and in relation to other forms of inequality and discrimination. We reflect on how ethnicity is connected to issues such as citizenship, immigration, marriage and families, employment, and violence, in Europe and in different international contexts. 

Upon the successful completion of the course, students will gain (knowledge-related objectives):   

1)	     The ability to define in a clear and comprehensive way the notion of ethnicity and its intersection with key related concepts such as nation, class, culture, race, religion and gender. 
2)	A critical knowledge of the main theories of ethnicity from the perspective of different disciplines within social sciences      
3)	Familiarity with the main classical and contemporary researches on the topic and with reference to different geopolitical contexts;
4)	Relate and analyse in a comparative way different case-studies;   
5)	Awareness of the importance of ethnicity in social analysis and intervention, territorial planning, community development and policy advising.       

By the end of the course, students are also required to develop the following skills: 

6)	Capacity to share their ideas, doubts and questions during class activities and to interact constructively with their peers and the teacher; 
7)	Organise and present work in progress through PPT;
8)	Organise and write an essay on a selected topic.

The course has three educational goals:
1)	have a good knowledge of the main characteristics and problems of the Italian and European labour market;
2)	understand the mechanisms underpinning the labour supply decisions of individuals and families, as well as some related choices (education and fertility);
3)	learn to analyse the functioning of the labour market and to evaluate the possible consequences of labour market institutions and policies, as well as of information asymmetries, on employment, wages, payment schemes and gender differences. 
The course for Economics and Management has also the additional aim to deepen the knowledge of the Italian and European labour market (mainly through empirical evidence).

The course aims to provide students with fundamental knowledge in order to understand the similarities and diversity of organisms from an evolutionary point of view, using phylogenetic analysis based on diagnostic characters as a tool. The course also aims to provide students with basic notions on the organization of the main organs and tissues that compose them, and on the functioning of organs and systems as integrated systems. The ultimate aim of the course is to provide students with a general understanding of the main characteristics of model organisms related to their use in research and innovation laboratories.

Attendance and active participation in the three training activities proposed by the course (lectures, thematic insights with presentation of validated scientific contributions, practical exercises) and individual study will allow female students / students to:

a) Explain the evolutionary and biodiversity generation mechanisms based on scientific evidence, starting from Darwin's observations and arriving at genetic variability and the main speciation models;
b) Exemplify models that explain the origin of life based on molecular evidence, fossil records, and the effects of developmental genes on the evolution of anatomical structures;
c) Differentiate the main groups of animal organisms on the basis of their evolutionary relationship (phylogeny), starting from simple unicellular and multicellular organisms, and arriving at the more complex multicellular organisms;
d) Apply the principles of cladistic taxonomy as a tool for analyzing and organizing mono-para- and polyphyletic groups;
e) Remember / analyze the anatomy and integrated functioning of the main systems and systems of animal organisms;
f) Remember / recognize the main types of tissues by observing histological preparations;
g) To recall / recall the main characteristics of model organisms used in research and innovation laboratories;
h) Apply scientific investigation as a method for asking questions about the natural world, relating knowledge, reasoning on hypotheses and solutions, experimenting and seeking answers, interpreting data and creating further knowledge.

The aim of this class is to get the student familiar with ideas, theories and methods, with a multidisciplinary approach, in the field of Clinical Psychology. Main topics of the course are: activity of the Clinical Psychologist, Assessment, Diagnostic Process, Intervention, and clinical psychophysiology. 
At the end of this course, students will be able to: 
A.	suggest an assessment procedure, in order to generally recognize the presence of a disease;
B.	discriminate between different psychopathologies studied during class;
C.	apply and strengthen their critical thinking, specifically on clinical case analysis, thanks to hands-on sessions.
D.	try practically instruments and models used during assessment and treatment

The course aims to offer the knowledge of the Italian administrative system, starting with its constitutional foundations and its legal sources. It analyzes organization and activity of the public authority, focusing on the administrative procedure. 
A special attention will be given to the administrative decision, including its invalidity regime, the civil liability of the public administration, the public contracts and the fundamental features of the administrative justice. 
The analysis of the Italian system will be linked to the EU one, of which it forms an integral part. 
The course will therefore be dedicated to the relationship between the Italian administrative system and the EU order. 
There will also be a focus on the recent reforms introduced by Law 124/2014. 
At the end of the course the student will be able to: 
- Identify the features of administrative law in relation to private law and understand its logic; 
- understand the main national administrations and their organizational features, and recognize the principles governing their functioning; 
- understand the administrative powers and their limits; 
- Understand the relationship between national administrations and the European Union system; 
- Analyze the administrative procedure, its structural and functional phases and identify the principal guarantees in it; 
- Examine the binding acts of the administration, analyze their invalidity and identify its consequences in terms of reviewability; 
- understand how to identify the discretionary power of the public administration and the implications of these powers in relation to the rule of law and judicial reviewability 
- understand individual rights and interests in front of the exercise of administrative powers and their legal protection;

This course introduces the student to the basic concepts of hydrology and explores the main components of the hydrological cycle including precipitation, evapotranspiration, infiltration, groundwater flow and runoff generation. Students will learn about each physical hydrological process and how to represent hydrometeorological variables (also in a statistical sense).
At the end of the course the student will be able:
• 	to define, explain and correctly use terms and concepts used to describe basic physical hydrologic processes;
•	to use a Geographical Information System (GIS) in order to delineate watershed boundaries;
•  	to perform simple hydrological modeling aimed at estimating hydrological fluxes at catchment-scale.

Leadership is one among the most important personal features, for an individual to be successful in society and organizations. 
This course aims to let participants having the experience of what it is to be a leader and what it is to exercise leadership effectively.

At the end of the course, participants:
1. will be able to persuasively discuss what it is to be a leader;
2. will be aware of what is required, in order to develop one's personal leadership skills;
3. will exhibit improved team-working and personal examination skills.

The aim of the module is to provide students with a sound and updated knowledge of the trends of the world economy and the theory of economic policy in the framework of international openness and aimed at acquiring a critical knowledge of the fundamental policy choices.
This module enphasises the description of phenomena and in particular on market and authority failures, limiting the application of formal economic models. Where possible, empirical evidence is discussed.

At the end of the course, students:

- will know the problems and the objectives of economic policy;
- will have recalled elements to understand microeconomic problems addressed by economic policy, such as market power, public goods, externalities; as well as macroeconomic concepts (e.g. IS, LM)
- will master basic macroeconomic concepts, such as aggregate demand and supply, employment, inflation, interest rates, exchange rates;
- will have acquired elements to understand and critically evaluate policy instruments and policies: monetary, fiscal, exchange rates and budgetary;
- will have acquired empirical evidence to understand and critically appreciate the economic policy of the European Monetary Union and its institutional arrangements;
- will have acquired theoretical knowledge and empirical evidence for understanding economic policy issues related to globalization and the transnational corporations that form part of it;
- will have overall gained the confidence in interpreting the economic policy choices that characterize the current international context.

This module will embrace the anatomical, cellular, molecular and functional organization of the Peripheral Nervous System (PNS). 

At the end of this course, students will be able to:
•	Describe the anatomy of the PNS
•	Explain the similarities and differences between different branches of the PNS;
•	Understand the complexity of the physiological function controlled by the PNS;
•	Understand how the functions of the PNS are finely tuned at different levels;
•	Understand how the different components of the PNS operate in a coordinated manner;
•	Critically evaluate the experimental approaches used to study the PNS, and the evolving comprehension of the mechanisms underlining the functions of the PNS.

The course is designed to give Students an overall knowledge  of the evolution from Latin to Romance literatures and languages in its basic lines, with reference to both historical grammar and literary history.
By the end of the course, Students will have acquired
- a general understanding of the main literary genres, texts and authors of medieval Romance literatures;
- the ability to translate and analyze medieval Romance texts in verse and prose;
- a comparative approach in the analysis of historical-literary themes and motifs as well as historical-linguistic and philological aspects and phenomena.

The course offers the attending students (those who attend at least 80% of the classes) the following educational objectives:
Acquisition of basic sociological knowledge and of some specific topics related to culture and communication sociology;
Know how to apply technical and theoretical knowledge to the worlds of social belonging (we will call this capacity/behavior “sociological imagination”) and to the interaction design environment;
Know how to produce and interpret data;
Direct experimentation of inter-relational and communicative dynamics typical of team work;
Know how to communicate in research team dynamics management, to speak in public, and to introduce sociological knowledge.

For those students who will instead choose not to attend, the course will offer the following educational objectives:
Acquisition of basic sociological knowledge and of several specific topics related to culture and communication sociology;
Know how to learn independently;
Know how to communicate in the introduction of sociological knowledge.

The course introduces Spanish culture and literature during the Golden Age through novel and short stories study. The student will acquire the tools to read original texts through historical, linguistic and literary contextualization.
At the end of the course the students
- will know the main historical, cultural and religious characteristics of Spain, with particular reference to the early modern age;
- will know the main theories about the structure of the classic novel and the basic notions of narratology;
- will have learned to recognize the lexicon and style of peculiar genres of the Golden Age novel;
- will have basic knowledge of legal and bibliographical aspects related to the production of the ancient book

The course aims to introduce the students to the European Union (EU) political system by presenting its institutions, the EU public policies, the dynamics behind the policy-making processes, and the future perspectives of the EU.
At the end of the course the student:
• knows the political and institutional processes governing the functioning of the EU and affecting the relations between its member states;
• is able to analyze the main policy choices of the European leaders on the continental and international scenarios;
• is able to read the main events of the history and the contemporaneity of the European Union using theoretical concepts.

1. Teaching objectives and contents.
The aim of the course is to make students acquainted with the timely knowledge of the construction of the financial statements, with particular reference to the application of national accounting principles and standardas. Teaching will enable you to thoroughly and in depth detail the national accounting principles with regard to intangible assets, financial assets, securities transactions, equity method in valuation of equity investments, inventory valuation, how to consider taxes in the financial statements and the link between civil law and tax law. Finally, some basic elements will be offered on the cash flow reports.

2. Expected results.
At the end of the course, students will be able to:
1. Understand the role of the national accounting principles in the drafting of the financial statements;
2. Interpret the financial notes as a space in which administrators illustrate the choices made (among the various possible options) with reference to the application of national accounting principles;
3. Discuss different capitalization / non-capitalization alternatives with reference to multi-year liabilities and assess the overall impact of these choices at the level of overall corporate profitability;
4. Determine the cost of recording a material asset in the balance sheet, taking into account the accessory costs and the various ways in which these assets can become part of the company's assets, and finally to evaluate the transactions linked to the business (i.e. Maintenance of tangible fixed assets, spare parts, capital contributions);
5. Determine the recording cost of equity holdings in the balance sheet and know when to apply the cost method and under which circumstances it is preferable to apply the equity method;
6. Analyze the impacts of different valuation criteria on the stock of business profitability, also taking into account different market conditions;
7. Determine the value of current, deferred, anticipated and accrued taxes in the financial statements, taking into account the provisions of the accounting principles and the TUIR - Unique Income Tax Act;
8. Understand the role and functioning of the cash flow statement as a tool for analyzing corporate flows.

The objective of the course is the acquisition of knowledge and competencies aimed at the comprehension of territorial marketing methods and instruments, with particular respect to tourist development. The attendance and the active participation of the training activities given in the course (lessons, seminars and the final inter-disciplinary laboratory), combined with the individual study, will allow to the students to:
-	Apply correctly the managerial approaches to the management of territory;
-	Work out a strategy of attraction of firms, capital and tourist flows in a territory;
-	Create and manage a territorial brand;
-	Understand the different tools of territorial marketing, in particular the communication process and the perceived image of the territory.

The course aims to teach students the clinical path and associated methodologies that accompany an oncologic patient from cancer diagnosis to the choice of the most appropriate therapy. In detail, the course describes different methods of bioptic sampling and processing, diagnostic criteria of tumor staging, surgery and pharmacological strategies for the treatment of specific types of solid cancer. Particular attention will be dedicated to technological innovations in the field of tumor diagnosis, in vivo imaging and radiology, as well as to dissecting the difference between classical chemotherapeutic drugs and innovative “target” therapies.
At the end of the course students will be able to:
-	Define different clinical approaches adopted for the diagnosis and treatment of specific forms of tumor;
-	Compare pros and cons of different clinical strategies; 
-	Classify a pathologic condition in low, medium, and high risk categories and propose a clinical approach and predict possible outcomes;
-	Examine and estimate tumor response to a specific therapy;
Integrate clinical information with genetic data in order to design targeted treatments.

The main learning objectives of this course are:
deepening the students' knowledge in  marketing;
developing their capability to apply that knowledge to a firm's activity;
developing their capability to work in the unfamiliar context of an international group, under stressful conditions.
At the end of the course the students will be able to:
identify the information needed for evaluating the market situation of a company operating in durable consumer goods (and by analogy of all firms);
understand such informartion and carefully analyse it in order to identify the possible strategies and marketing actions that the firm can implement;
define the details of these actions and plan them, working in cooperation with the team;
develop the capacity to work under stress, in a multinational group of previously unknown people;
acquire multi-cultural and behavioural soft skills useful for working in an international firm.

The course focuses on the history of republican Italy, with a specific attention toward the role of European integration in national political, economic, social and cultural events.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
- know the moments, processes and fundamental stages of republican history;
- orientate themselves in the historiographical debate about the history of the Italian Republic;
- understand the effects of European integration on Italy

The course aims to give students the basic tools to learn and deepen the characteristics of labor law and the fundamental principles that characterize it through the study of the various institutes. 
The subject of the course is the study of the legislative and contractual discipline applicable to employment relationships also in relation to the principles established by the Constitution, from international and community sources. Particular attention will be given to the jurisprudence of the various institutes. 
The training goal is to provide students with a wealth of knowledge that allows them to use the various sources of labor law reasonably to properly address the issues and to address the issues that may arise in future professional activity. 

At the end of the course students will have to demonstrate: knowledge of the structural features of Labor law and its fundamental principles; 
ability to master the normative sources (including international and community) and its jurisprudence; 
ability to understand and correctly use the language of speech; 
ability to solve practical cases related to personnel management.

The course aims that the students understand the functioning principles of several optoelectronics devices, such as laser, LEDs, phototectors, image sensors, photovoltaic cells. This is done by introducing the students to the basic concepts of the physics of the semiconductors, including the physics of pn junction and of low dimensional structures, and by specializing the presentation to those concepts that are instrumental to the understanding of the characteristics of the optoelectronic devices. In this way, students will be able in the following of their career to use these devices or develop new devices based on the physical principles that underlay optoelectronics.

Optoelectronics will be presented starting from the basic equations ruling optical transitions in semiconductors and arriving to specific applications of optoelectronics to such technologies as solid-state lighting, optical communications, energy production and image recording.

Due to the course attendance and to the active participation in the course and to the individual study, the student will be able to:
- Understand the basic principle of the physics of semiconductor optoelectronic devices;
- Critically evaluate the most important parameters, which characterize the performance of semiconductor optoelectronic devices;
- Know how to design, develop or use optoelectronic devices.

The objective of the course is to introduce into the “Law of Diversity” and its elements and instruments by illustrating and discussing the role and potential of law, and in particular of Human and Minority  Rights, as a means of regulation and stabilization, especially after ethnic conflict.
In particular, students who have passed the exam shall be able to:
-	give an account of the debate regarding the definition of “minority” and to delimit it from other groups (such as migrants, indigenous peoples, etc.);
-	give an account of the historical evolution in Europe, leading to the Nation-State, and to the consequent marginalization of minority groups;
-	illustrate the different constitutional approaches regarding the phenomenon of diversity;
-	explain the fundamental rights, procedures and institutional solutions of minority-proection regarding linguistic, political and religious rights, including power-sharing and affirmative action.

The course aims to provide the concepts, methodologies and tools needed to understand and solve the main problems regarding people and relationships faced by junior and middle managers in companies operating in an international environment.
Upon completion of the course the student will be able to:
-	Recognize and understand the main motives behind individual behaviour in corporate environments;
-	Use combinations of intrinsic and extrinsic motivation levers to improve individual and group performance;
-	Understand the complexity and the nuances of the management of groups composed of persons who are heterogeneous by cultural and technical background; cognitive styles, nationalities;
-	Understand the main sources of conflict in small groups;
-	Effectively use differences in small groups to produce original solutions to new problems; 
-	Effectively handle communication and decision-making in work contexts.

The course gives students a basic knowledge of the legal context which supports international contracting in global trade. Contractual choices are described as one aspect of the wider commercial strategies to be planned by firms entering foreign markets. The most efficient and effective ways to deal with the risks of cross-border transactions are discussed, with specific reference to the main models of international business contracts, global value chains and the applicable legal rules. 
By the end of the course, the student will be able to:
- identify the rules which apply to international contracts, their sources in national or international law, or the private parties enacting them;
- establish the binding or non-binding nature of rules applicable to international contracts; 
- understand the factors to take into account when choosing the most suitable contractual scheme for an international transaction or the organization of a global value chain; 
- understand how to read an international contract; 
- identify, for a specific international transaction, the legal consequences from the point of view of risk allocation, distribution of rights and obligations between the parties, as well as sharing of profits;
- understand benefits and costs of alternative dispute resolution procedures.

The goal of the course is to provide the attending students with the essential necessary tools to understand and to use the relativistic quantum theory of fields, namely the scientific theory realizing the coherent merger between the theory of special relativity and the quantum mechanical.
At the end of the course, the attending student should be able:
1. to know the fundamental elements of the quantum theory of free fields and their quantization procedure;
2. to understand the fundamental equations to be used to describe the interactions of quantum fields;
3. to understand and utilize the relativistic theory of scattering;
4. to have a good knowledge of the principles of quantum electrodynamics.

Students are expected to learn general principles and concepts about:
1.	Solid-state materials fabrication methods;
2.	Particle-atom interactions, with the aim to understand the main materials characterization techniques;
3.	Electric and optical properties, in particular of semiconductors, junctions and heterostructures of interests for energy&environmental applications;
4.	Catalysis, surface and interface effects and their application to electro-, photo-, and photo-electrocatalysis processes.
A set of case-study lessons on applications (solar fuels: hydrogen production and CO2 conversion, solar wastewater treatments, nanodiamond sensors, laser propulsion for space technology) will highlight current topics in the energy&environmental field. At the end of the course, students will be capable of:
1.	Discussing the fundamental principles dictating materials properties;
2.	Design a material based on the properties required by a specific application;
3.	Plan a materials synthesis and characterization, selecting the appropriate fabrication methods and analysis techniques;
4.	Discuss the main issues open in the energy&environmental field.

The aim of the course is to introduce students to the formal techniques for the automatic verification of security properties on cryptographic protocols. After discussing the theoretical foundations of programming languages, the course applies the related techniques to model protocols and construct algorithms which verify their robustness to attacks.

At the end of the course, students must have learned to:
- reason about fixed points of a functions over a domain;
- model protocols in suitable formalisms;
- know the negative results associated to protocol verification;
- describe the main protocol verification techniques (model checking, static analysis);
- understand some algorithms for protocol verification;
- use a software tool for protocol verification, including the generation of formal security proofs;
- know the basis of the logic used to write such formal proofs.

"The aims of the course are to offer students an introduction to the main legal systems of the world and to equip them with methodologies and instruments of comparative law. 
At the end of the course students will be able to:
- identify the main features of a legal system and of the various families of legal systems; 
- acquire skills aimed at placing the main systems of the Western legal tradition in a current, European and global perspective;
- acquire an adequate understanding of the characteristics and systemological placement of some families of ""non-Western"" legal systems, based on different conceptions of the social order and law;
- identify the characteristics and the different methods of comparative law as a science: functionalism, structuralism and other epistemological paradigms of more recent definition;
- identify the key elements of an institute which are relevant for uncovering its function and compare it with a similar model (functionalism); identify the different formants and evaluate their convergence or dissociation (structuralism) with regard to a specific factual situation."

1) Training objectives:

The course aims to convey the essential elements of civil law provided for the annual balance sheet of insurance companies and also focuses on issues related to IAS / IFRS, Solvency and analysis of company documents. It is aimed at students who want to pursue a career in the insurance sector, auditing or consulting fields.

2) Expected Learning Outcomes:

At the end of the course, the student should be able to:
1. Illustrate the peculiarities of the financial statements of insurance companies;
2. Understand the main accounting issues related to the insurance financial statements in terms of accounting principles and disclosures;
3. Understand, to analyze and to interpret the financial statements of insurance companies;
4. Identify critical business realities, formulating them in a clear and structured manner;
5. Elaborate and to propose effective planning alternatives that are consistent with the organizational context of the enterprise.

This course aims to provide students with an opportunity for engaging in critical evaluation of different theoretical models of social and emotional development. The course aims also to give an overview of research findings in social and emotional development and an appreciation of methods for investigating social and emotional development in infancy.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
a)	understand the theories and methodologies of the theories on emotional development;
b)	develop critical skills and communicate clearly the acquired knowledge; 
c)	elaborate independently the acquired knowledge and relate what they have learned with other disciplines and to self-study also research areas of personal interest;

In this module the students will be guided to investigate applications – already established, under experimentation, or expected for the future – of neuroscience and psychology in the real world.

The objective is to develop awareness and skills of autonomous and critical thinking on scientific, methodological, ethical and social issues connected in particular with applied cognitive neuroscience.

At the end of the module, the students will be able to:
1) Identify and circumscribe applications of cognitive neuroscience in the real world;
2) Identify and discuss the basic neuroscientific knowledge on which the logic of a specific application rests;
3) Identify and discuss the research methodology and the scientific evidence (existing and/or desirable) to enable a competent evaluation of the efficacy of such application;
4) Identify and discuss potential ethical and social issues connected with the application.

The course aims to: 
- Appreciation of the political, social and cultural history of the Medieval age.
- Develop confidence in engaging with current scholarly debates.
- Develop skills in analysing a variety of types of primary sources.

After attending the course and after reading the reference bibliography, the students will be able to:
- define and describe the specific characters of the Medieval history;
- define and describe the most important turning points of the Medieval history;
- recognize and analyze a variety of types of primary sources;
- analyze and comment a historiographic text;
- analyze a historic map;
- define and use the specific terms of the medieval studies.
- be able to briefly present a book on medieval history.

International law is the branch of law that deals with the way relations among the subjects of the international community are regulated. The course in International Law (‘Diritto internazionale’) aims at giving students a basic understanding of how the law of the international community works, as well as providing them with an in-depth knowledge of the most important rules and principles that, by putting obligations and bestowing rights and faculties on international actors, govern both their status and behaviour.

The following learning goals are expected to be met:

− Knowledge of the fundamentals of international life, and the norms that act as drivers and bonds therein, thus being able to identify them when analysing current events;
− Understanding of both the basic features of the international legal order and its peculiarities with respect to the domestic legal system, particularly as regards the making, the ascertainment and the enforcement of law;
− Capacity to appreciate the notion of effectiveness as related to the law of the international community, as well as the difference between international law and international politics/relations;
− Awareness of the existence of a multitude of international legal fields, and how their different regulation is due to the diversity of the underlying interests;
− Comprehension of the way the Italian legal order interacts with international law;
− Ability to approach directly (i.e., without resorting to the textbook) legal sources, as well as, to a certain extent, specialised literature;
− Familiarity with the proper legal jargon, which shall be mastered when using Italian and at least recognised when reading English texts.

LITERATURE: Special enquiry on some poetological, estetical and philosophical problems of the modern German literature. The student will be able to:
a. take part in debates in German on the discussed works;
b. read and discuss the analysed texts in original;
c. describe a text in its cultural and literary context;
d. thoroughly analyse every section of a text.

The course of International Economic Law aims at providing the fundamental instruments to understand the international legal framework in which economic relations between States take place. In particular, at the end of the course students shall:

- understand the main factors of legal and, to some extent, also economic nature that influence the conduct of States in the fields of trade, investment and finance, at both the domestic and international levels;
- acquire basic knowledge of the rules governing the international trade in goods and services, transnational investment and financial/monetary policies, and of the rights and duties of all actors involved in these activities;
- appreciate the role played by the most important international organizations in shaping the decisions of States relating to trade, investment and finance, and how these institutions may help settle international disputes in their respective fields of action;
- be able to identify the most relevant legal issues underlying the major events of the international economic life, as reported by the press;
- be familiar with the legal and economic jargon used in international negotiations, policymaking and litigation in the areas covered by the course;
- critically assess the current debates about the impact of international economic law on State sovereignty, on the one hand, and human rights and the environment, on the other, and the proposals to tackle these problems.

The aim of the course is to give a basic knowledge on electrical and magnetic phenomena, on circuits, on electromagnetic induction and on wave phenomena, focusing on elastic, sound and electromagnetic waves.
After the course the student should be able to:
1) calculate forces and fields produced by simple charge distributions; 
2) know the behaviour of different materials in presence of electromagnetic fields; 
3) treat simple circuits with resistors, condensators and inductances;
4) know the principle of electromagnetic induction with applications;
5) know the working principles of optical intruments, by calculating in some cases position and dimensions of the images;
6) know the principles of interference and diffraction by calculating the phase difference between waves in some cases;
7) know the behaviour of elastic and sound waves.

The course, focusing on the basic notions of theory and dynamics of structures, is organized into three parts:
- Theory of plates and shells;
- Inelastic behaviour of solids: at first viscoelastic behaviour is briefly analyzed, then plasticity is focused on. The theory of plasticity is illustrated with some applications to evolutive structural analysis and finally the fundamentals of limit analysis are presented and some simple applications are illustrated;
- Dynamic response of elastic structures within the small displacement regime: normal modes and natural frequencies, resonance conditions, uncoupled modal response in dynamics.

By the end of the course, the successful student will be able to:
- Analyze the mechanical fields within bidimensional structural elements;
- Predict the failure conditions of structure in the plastic regime;
- Analyze the dynamical properties of structures and predict their response in a dynamic setting.

The Course adopts an European perspective to the study of development cooperation and introduces students to techniques of policy writing. It tackles core topics in the debate on international cooperation such as the implications of international trade for development, human rights and democracy promotion. It uses a teaching method aimed at facilitating interaction between the academic and professional worlds, strengthening students’ competences on policy writing and facilitating dialogue with practitioners and representatives of the European institutions.
By the end of the course students will be able to:
•	Understand political dynamics behind European development cooperation in the context of global governance;
•	Develop critical thinking concerning potentialities and challenges of trade as an instrument of development cooperation;
•	Apply theoretical concepts to case studies;
•	Mastering techniques of policy writing.

The course provides the theoretical methodologies to model and study interconnected dynamical systems (dynamical networks) and lays the foundations for the control and optimisation of such systems. The students learn and apply fundamental concepts of graph theory, system theory and optimisation.
At the end of the course, the students are able to:
1.	analyse and classify graphs based on their properties (e.g. undirected/directed, weighted, balanced, regular);
2.	compute the adjacency matrix, Laplacian matrix, incidence matrix associated with a graph;
3.	assess node centrality in graphs using the most appropriate centrality measure (e.g. degree/eigenvector/Katz/PageRank/closeness/betweenness centrality) for a given purpose;
4.	formulate application problems (e.g. traffic control, flow networks, opinion dynamics) adopting a suitable graph representation;
5.	analyse linear dynamics defined over networks (distributed averaging and flow dynamics);
6.	turn a set of chemical reactions into a dynamical network and study its behaviour;
7.	solve multi-agent coordination problems by applying consensus algorithms;
8.	design optimal flow distributions in a network by formulating and solving a suitable optimisation problem;
9.	design flow controllers adopting a decentralised approach.

The course aims to offer students the knowledge of the basic notions of the theory of legal order,  of the most relevant concepts of the theory of the State and of the constitutional foundations of the Italian Republic, with particular attention to the study of constitutional bodies, sources of law and constitutional justice. The matters will be explained, if possible, through specific institutional and political references.

At the end of the course the students will be able to:
- recognize the normative sources and to seek the dispositions;
- apply the criterions of interpretation;

- know the essential elements of the government organizations in the light of the principles of theory of the State;
- classify the sources of the Italian juridical order and to resolve the possible conflicts of norms 
- describe the formation, the operation and the powers of the constitutional bodies 
- describe the contents and the formalities of the administrative activity as well as the organization of the public administration;

- define the characters of the actions and the acts as well as the possible pathologies;

- represent the jurisdictional function and to describe the jurisdictional apparatus 

- identify the functions of the constitutional Court and the general role acquitted in the system; to seek and select / analyze its judgements 
- address in a conscious and critical manner the resolution of issues concerning the application of the principal Italian public law institutes.

This course aims to provide a critical knowledge of the history of Italian literature in the period between Tasso and the end of the nineteenth century.
Within this chronological frame, we will focus either on a literary theme or genre, through texts by various authors, or on the study of a single author or work, also with respect to their critical reception through history.
At the end of the course students will be able to:
a. supply a critical and historical framework for the theme, genre, author, or work at hand;
b. have in-depth knowledge and comment texts introduced in class;
c. confidently orient themselves within the assigned secondary literature

The course aims to provide knowledge in the field of comparative constitutional law. It will focus on the protection of Constitutions by the States. After providing a basic framework of the methodology of legal comparison, it will focus on the creation and protection of Constitutions, in the light of the models of comparative constitutional justice. The analysis of historical and contemporary significant cases will be used to understand the impact of constitutional justice on social change. Students will also make a presentation of topical cases.
At the end of the course, students will be able to:
- use the methodology of comparative legal analysis in the field of constitutional law;
- understand the protection and evolution of Constitutions;
- know the main models of constitutional justice;
- understand and analyze the interaction between (constitutional and lower) Courts and State institutions (e.g. Parliaments)
- understand and analyze the interaction between Constitutional Courts and other disciplines (e.g. history, religion, science);
- identify and analyze cases of constitutional significance;
- understand, analyze and make a presentation of significant cases.

The course has three educational goals:
1)	have a good knowledge of the main characteristics and problems of the Italian and European labour market;
2)	understand the mechanisms underpinning the labour supply decisions of individuals and families, as well as some related choices (education and fertility);
3)	learn to analyse the functioning of the labour market and to evaluate the possible consequences of labour market institutions and policies, as well as of information asymmetries, on employment, wages, payment schemes and gender differences. 
The course for Economics and Management has also the additional aim to deepen the knowledge of the Italian and European labour market (mainly through empirical evidence).

The aim of this course is to offer students a theoretical framework and some tools for the analysis of individual choices under uncertainty and asymmetric information (with particular attention to financial markets).
At the end of the course, students will be able to:
1) be aware of and illustrate graphically the effects of credit markets imperfections and changes in the interest rates on saving and borrowing decisions;
2) identify the structure of a choice problem under uncertainty and know which factors influence individual preferences for uncertain prospects;
3) use graphical and mathematical tools to describe the main decisions under risk (insurance demand, portfolio choices, saving and borrowing decisions) and be aware of the main relationships between individual preferences and choice characteristics;
4) understand the main factors that influence the structure of contracts between two agents (in particular, risk attitudes and  information), and identify the most appropriate incentives in various situations.

The course follows the general course of Comparative Law (Sistemi giuridici comparati, 1st year). It consists of an introduction to the law of African countries. At the end of the course, the students will be able to:

-	Demonstrate a clear understanding of the nature and practice of African Legal Systems;
-	Be acquainted with the terminology and concepts developed by comparative law with regard to Africa;
-	Communicate accurately about African systems of law and “non-western” legal traditions more generally;  
-	Find sources for conducting research into African legal systems and the dynamics of their transformation.

The goal of the course is to provide students with theoretical and practical tools for the design and implementation of correct and efficient algorithmic solutions for a large set of computational problems.

At the end of the course, students are expected:
A) to remember the characteristics of the main data structures and to understand what could be their contribution in the solution of computational problems;
B) to formally describe a selected collection of computational problems and their solution, being able to discuss their correctness;
C) to know the main algorithmic techniques and to select those better suited to solve a particular problem;
D) to analyze the computational complexity of algorithms, i.e. to quantify the resources needed for their executions;
E) to compare distinct algorithmic solutions and to select the one which is better suited given a particular input.

Based on these competences related to the literature of “classical” algorithms, students should be able to solve a large array of computational problems, i.e.:
F) to precisely understand the problem to be solved, by defining the mathematical relationship between the input and the output of the problem;
G) to design an algorithmic solution for such problem, by adapting an existing solution or by building a new solution from scratch;;
H) to evaluate the correctness and the computational complexity of the proposed solution;
I) to implement the selected solution by using an imperative programming language.

Object of the course are the structural characteristics of civil proceedings, and the basic concepts of civil procedure; special regard is made to those aspects, which are more useful in the light of job prospects.
At the end of the course the student should be able to:
- distinguish among the judicial redresses (execution proceedings; provisional measures; res iudicata proceedings); 
- identify the judge which has jurisdiction and competence over the case;
- distinguish between declaratory judgements, constitutive judgements and enforceable judgements;
- identify the basic structure of ordinary cognizance proceedings and of the so called “procedimento per decreto ingiuntivo”
- recognize the main characteristics of the “consulente tecnico di ufficio”
- get familiar with arbitration (included the so called “arbitrato societario”)

The course aims at providing the fundamental concepts to understand the dynamics of geophysical flows and their mathematical and numerical modelling. The focus will be on the mathematical description that allows for representing processes at different scales (from atmosphere and ocean to small water bodies) with different approximations of the same fundamental equations.

At the end of the course, the student will be able to:
• understand the theoretical aspects of fluid mechanics and transport mechanisms in the environment;
• understand the mathematical description of the processes by means of partial differential equations;
• interpret the studied processes by means of simplified analytical solutions;
• implement some simple numerical schemes to solve idealized problems;
• estimate the relevant quantities in real-world problems;
• critically approach the use of numerical models for meteorological applications.

The course aims to provide students with the basic concepts of electricity and magnetism and the basic knowledge of the electrical and magnetic properties of matter. In this way, students will be able in the following courses to understand the application of the Maxwell equations in the study of time dependent electric and magnetic phenomena and the theory of electromagnetic radiation and its interaction with matter.

Electromagnetism will be presented starting from the phenomenology and examples will be discussed related to natural manifestations of electromagnetic phenomena and their technological applications.

Due to the frequency and to the active participation in the training activities offered by the course (lectures, exercises and tutoring) and to the individual study, the student will be able to:
- Describe the electrical and magnetic properties of matter;
- Understand the four Maxwell equations;
- Solve electromagnetism problems.

The course aims to provide an introduction to Psychology and to illustrate recent progress in experimental research. At the beginning of the course, the history and origins of Psychology will be dealt with. Then, the main topics of Psychology will be analysed. The course purports to promote active learning and participation. At the end of the course, student should be able to:
- analyse critically the scientific literature on cognitive psychology topics;
- outline the main topics in psychology adopting a proper lexicon;
- to shape the learned concepts to applied contexts.

The course aims to provide a comprehensive, but detailed view of the cellular and molecular complexity of the nervous system. Particular emphasis will be given to morphological characteristics and genetic mechanisms that characterize the properties of neurons and to the interneuronal communication systems underlying synaptic transmission.
By the end of the course, the students will be able to:
1. Carefully and comprehensively define the cellular and molecular complexity of central nervous system (Remember), comparing and discussing different cell types of the brain based on their morphological and functional characteristics (Understand-Analyzing);
2. Examine the molecular mechanisms responsible for neuronal properties such as neuronal transport, active and passive electrical properties (Analyzing);
3. Classify basic characteristics interneuronal communication and synaptic transmission, discriminating different chemical and electrical neuron-to-neuron communication systems (electrical and chemical synapses, different neurotransmitters and their receptors) (understand, analyze);
4. Explain and discuss the cellular and molecular basis of neuron-glia metabolic unit (neuron – astrocytes – capillaries, glycolysis versus oxidative phosphorylation) (understand, analyze).

The aim of course “FILOSOFIA DELLA STORIA”, part of second year of the three-year degree in Philosophy, is - first of all - to make students capable of understanding  the specific issues of questions on history  through an analysis of its genesis and evolution. Secondly, to provide tools to interpret the intrinsic historical content of every philosophy. 
At the end of the course “FILOSOFIA DELLA STORIA”, the students will acquire a number of notions and categories thanks to which they will be able to:
A) define the specific peculiarity among this discipline;
B) place the discipline, both historically and systematically, within the context of philosophical reflection as a whole;
C) be able to interpret, within modern or contemporary thought, the problematic confrontation of the reflection on history with the changes of the anthropological paradigm caused by the impact of natural sciences, the transformations of psychological experiences, the needs of redefining personal identity;
D) be able to read and interpret independently the classical texts;
E) identify and contextualize the key terms and the main concepts regarding the authors and texts studied during the course.

Deepening the understanding of the functioning of markets and of the determinants and effectiveness of firms' strategies, through the analysis of a specific market with appropriate data.
Specific skills to be acquired include:
- applying theoretical concepts learnt in other courses to the analysis of a market and an enterprise; 
- identifying the most appropriate data to describe a phenomenon of interest (e.g. the evolution of a specific market and its main determinants);
- ability to work with data in order to extract relevant information;
- organizing and discussing the results of the analysis and drafting a research report; 
- team work; 
- presenting the results to an audience.

The course provides the theoretical methodologies to model and study interconnected dynamical systems (dynamical networks) and lays the foundations for the control and optimisation of such systems. The students learn and apply fundamental concepts of graph theory, system theory and optimisation.
At the end of the course, the students are able to:
1.	analyse and classify graphs based on their properties (e.g. undirected/directed, weighted, balanced, regular);
2.	compute the adjacency matrix, Laplacian matrix, incidence matrix associated with a graph;
3.	assess node centrality in graphs using the most appropriate centrality measure (e.g. degree/eigenvector/Katz/PageRank/closeness/betweenness centrality) for a given purpose;
4.	formulate application problems (e.g. traffic control, flow networks, opinion dynamics) adopting a suitable graph representation;
5.	analyse linear dynamics defined over networks (distributed averaging and flow dynamics);
6.	turn a set of chemical reactions into a dynamical network and study its behaviour;
7.	solve multi-agent coordination problems by applying consensus algorithms;
8.	design optimal flow distributions in a network by formulating and solving a suitable optimisation problem;
9.	design flow controllers adopting a decentralised approach.

The course is designed to offer students theoretical and practical knowledge of the mechanisms of conflict management that have progressively emerged as dispute resolution methods alternative to in-court proceedings on civil and commercial matters at an international, European and domestic level, i.e. negotiation, collaborative practice, mediation (also in family matters) and arbitration. 
At the end of the course students will be able to:
-recognize the fundamental features of negotiation, collaborative practice, mediation and arbitration as methods of civil and commercial conflict management;
-identify the main differences between these conflict management strategies and in-court proceedings;
-appropriately choose the most efficient way (between negotiation, collaborative practice, mediation, arbitration and in-court proceedings) to solve a conflict or a dispute on civil and commercial matters;
-acquire basic knowledge of the international, European and (if any) domestic regulations on negotiation, collaborative practice, mediation and arbitration;
-master essential negotiation, mediation and collaborative practice techniques, and manage arbitration proceedings;
-identify possible obstacles to negotiation, collaborative practice, mediation, as well as potential issues in managing arbitration proceedings and ways to solve them;
-implement best practices as a lawyer-negotiator, lawyer in mediation and mediator, lawyer in collaborative practice, lawyer in arbitration and arbitrator.

Students will be introduced to basic principles and language of economics. The course will present the methodology and the essential concepts of the economic theory with their application to individuals, firms, markets and the dynamic of economic aggregates.

At the end of the course the student 
• Will know and will be able to explain the working of markets and other economic institutions;
• Will know and will be able to explain the main measures of the economic aggregates and their relationship;
• will be able to explain the role of the economic institutions and the state in the economic system;
• will be able to interpret and explain with the language of economics the main facts that are at the centre of the national debate.

The main learning objectives of this course are:
deepening the students' knowledge in  marketing;
developing their capability to apply that knowledge to a firm's activity;
developing their capability to work in the unfamiliar context of an international group, under stressful conditions.
At the end of the course the students will be able to:
identify the information needed for evaluating the market situation of a company operating in durable consumer goods (and by analogy of all firms);
understand such informartion and carefully analyse it in order to identify the possible strategies and marketing actions that the firm can implement;
define the details of these actions and plan them, working in cooperation with the team;
develop the capacity to work under stress, in a multinational group of previously unknown people;
acquire multi-cultural and behavioural soft skills useful for working in an international firm.

The course aims to provide students with basic information on the main topics of historical linguistics, with particular reference to the Indo-European languages.
At the end of the course, the students will be able to:
a) recognize the main types of linguistic change;
b) place the phenomena of linguistic change in their historical and geographical context;
c) distinguish the languages of the Indo-European family in groups and sub-groups.

The purpose of the course is:

a) to provide the theoretical notions (knowledge) about energy transformations, heat transfer and applied acoustics necessary to understand building physics, the methodologies to assess the energy performance of a building and the techniques used to control the internal microclimate.

b) to provide the skills (know how):
- to prepare energy balances applying the principle of energy conservation in a proper way;
- to solve problems dealing with one-dimensional heat transfer in steady state;
- to calculate the global heat exchange coefficient (U) for simple geometries (flat and cylindrical structures).
- to solve heat transmission problems in multiple dimensions (thermal bridges) even in transient conditions, possibly using numerical methods;
- to carry out a general analysis of the moist air processes of technical interest (HVAC systems and surface and/or interstitial condensation processes in building structures).

The general aim of the course of THEORETICAL PHILOSOPHY is to provide a set of theoretical tools through which it will be possible to recognize and problematize fundamental distinctions and conceptual frameworks that, in the life contexts of the past and of the present, guide the understanding of the world, of others and of self. At a level of greater abstraction, the course proposes to reflect on the theoretical decisions that structure the various forms of knowledge and delimit scientific disciplines, especially those to which the degree course is addressed.
The comprehensive study of classical philosophical texts will allow to master concepts, doctrines, paradigms, reflection and argumentation styles that have characterized the development of Western thought in theoretical perspective.
The attention given to the conceptual dimension, the semantic stratification of key terms, the logical structure of arguments and the mutual problematization of theory and experience will improve the ability to understand reality and life contexts at different abstraction levels.
Classroom lessons, open to dialogue and controversy, will favor reasoned exposition of theses, reports, objections, helping students to face communicative situations typical of future professional life.

At the end of the course of THEORETICAL PHILOSOPHY students will be able to:
A) identify, reconstruct and expose the philosophical models examined during the course, placing them in their historical and systematic framework;
B) reconstruct and expose convincingly the argumentative strategies employed in the examined philosophical contexts;
C) organize the acquired knowledge and the results of the analyzes carried out, documenting the proposed theses and considering relevant objections;
D) re-elaborate the acquired knowledge, testing the possibility of ridescriving things in different terms and giving appropriate formulation to any identified problematic aspects.

The goal of the course is to deepen the knowledge of the configuration of social and general interest services, delving in particular into how the current system of supply came into place. More specifically, the course will address who the social entrepreneurship actors involved in the system are, what their role is, and what are the main management practices. The course will enable participants to identify how welfare systems have changed, not only due to actions on the part of the State and the public administration, but also due to a bottom-up phenomenon of creation of private enterprises with social aims that are increasingly gaining strength both at the national and international levels.
 The course is structured in themes. The first is introductory, and aims to provide basic notions of institutional economics, i.e. the branch of economics that seeks to explain the origin and functioning of coordination mechanisms and enterprise types. The second theme will then address the concepts of welfare system and the evolution of welfare systems, in order to understand the role played by different institutions. The third theme will focus on the study of social entrepreneurship, how social enterprises can be defined according to facts and to the law, how social entrepreneurship was born and how it evolved, which are the management mechanisms of a good social enterprise, and what the future might hold.


At the end of the course, students will know basic economic notions and will be able to critically discuss:

- institutionalist theories on the various ways of coordinating economic activities;

- the distinctive features of the social service sectors and the conditions for their production;

- the various modes of production and financing of social services;

- the organizational and legal forms that can be used in the field of social services and work integration;

- the emergence, evolution and current situation of social service organizations in Italy following the reform of the third sector.

In addition, through group work that forms part of the assessment, students are expected to develop: 

- an ability to find both primary and secondary data - communicative and presentation abilities

OBJECTIVES
An engineering approach to the software development results fundamental for coping with the increasing complexity of systems and to guarantee their economical sustainability. As for any other engineering discipline, the software production requires a systematic organization of the activities, the adoption of a well-defined process and methods and tools to support the quality and the respect of the project constraints. The objective of the course is providing to the students concepts, approaches and techniques for the analysis, the design, and the development of the software. In particular, the course will focus on process models, modelling languages and verification and validation techniques. Moreover, diagrammatic languages, requirements analysis methods, design principles and testing techniques will allow the students to design high quality software. The students will be practicing by developing and implementing a web service applying the most modern development techniques, including the adoption of RESTful directives and the use of standard languages for the documentation of web APIs, the collaboration in the development of the source code in a central repository, the automation of code testing, and the configuration of services and tools to set-up a continuous integration process for the software. Finally, project management concepts and metrics for software products will be introduced.

EXPECTED RESULTS
At the end of the course, the student will be able to: 
1. define the most suitable development process and model for the analysis and the design of the software under consideration; 
2. represent with the different types of diagrams the requirements, the architecture, the intarction among the components, and the deployment of the system; 
3. define and mange in a consistent and complete way the functional and non functional requirements of a software system highlighting priorities and criticises. 
4. Define the architecture of a software system adopting architectural styles and principles of refinement, abstraction, modularity, functional independency and refactoring; 
5. Design a component of a software system identifying the control type and following the step-by-step process for the respect of the general design principles; 
6. Define and document a web service compliant with RESTful directives, collaborate into the development of the source code, testing the code, and automating the deployment of the software with a continuous integration process.

The course offers an introduction to atmosphere and climate processes, to the physical mechanisms governing them, and to how their understanding supports meteorological and climatological analysis and prediction.
The course aims at providing students, coming from different university curricula, a common background on the basics of the earth's atmosphere processes.
The course will also briefly introduce students to concepts and processes that will be developed in depth in the other courses the students will attend within the programme.

At the end of the course students will be enabled to:
- understand the basic physical laws governing atmospheric processes;
- be familiar with the main weather and climate phenomena introduced during frontal lectures, and with the physical variables involved in those phenomena;
- provide order-of-magnitude estimates to atmospheric variables and balances;
- discuss covered topics with critical reasoning;
- apply the basic equations to solve exercises on the course topics;
- possess the basics to analyse and interpret weather maps.

This course aims to provide students with an opportunity for engaging in critical evaluation of different theoretical models related to the child development and useful for dealing with the relationship with pupils with greater awareness.

At the end of the course, students will be able to:
a)	understand the the fundamental concepts in the study of child and adolescent development;
b)	understand the basic notions relating to the development of the main psychological functions of the human being; 
c)	elaborate independently the acquired knowledge and relate what they have learned with other disciplines and to self-study also research areas of personal interest.

1) Students will acquire a basic knowledge of the main events and turning points in the history of the Global Cold War;
2) Students will acquire and develop the skills to orient themselves in the main events and debates on the turning points in the Cold War and its global implications
3) Students will be able to elaborate on important questions and articulate persuasive and well-structured historical arguments.

The course provides the basic notions and tools to analyze and discuss the ethical implications of digital technologies with specific reference to security, privacy, wellbeing, sustainability, and social implications of new technologies. The course has the general aim of illustrating how the ethical aspects are not limited to the use of technologies but they also belong to (and should be discussed during) the design process. 
Concerning the specific objectives, the students should be able to:
-know the main ethical principles;
-identify the ethical aspects to be considered in the studies involving human beings;
-identify and discuss the ethical aspects emerging in the different design phases;
-understand how trade-offs among requirements in the different design phases have an impact on the ethical aspects.

The course aims to deepen the themes of the analysis of the narrative text starting from the novels and short stories of the main protagonists of this literary genre in the second half of the nineteenth century. At the end of the course the students:
- will know the main historical, cultural and religious features of nineteenth-century Spain, with particular reference to its role in the European context and the relationship with gender issues;
- will know the main theories on the structure of the realist novel and the elementary notions of narratology applied in spanish;
- will have learned to recognize the constituent elements of short forms of narration.
